WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.640
[Amit Varma]: We sometimes think of the economy as something removed from the real world.

00:00:08.640 --> 00:00:13.480
[Amit Varma]: There's numbers and graphs and tables and data, all things for policy wonks to look

00:00:13.480 --> 00:00:15.600
[Amit Varma]: at or rich people with advisors.

00:00:15.600 --> 00:00:18.160
[Amit Varma]: But what does it have to do with our daily life?

00:00:18.160 --> 00:00:19.840
[Amit Varma]: Well, everything.

00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:24.040
[Amit Varma]: One of the common themes on my show is that economics has human consequences.

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:28.460
[Amit Varma]: Bad economic policy in a country like India can affect the lives of millions of people.

00:00:28.460 --> 00:00:33.600
[Amit Varma]: One reason I often say that some of Indira Gandhi's economic policies or Narendra Modi's

00:00:33.600 --> 00:00:36.660
[Amit Varma]: demonetization were crimes on humanity.

00:00:36.660 --> 00:00:38.440
[Amit Varma]: They hurt the poor the most.

00:00:38.440 --> 00:00:43.720
[Amit Varma]: The thing is, bad policy is often couched in good intentions, and the bad outcomes they

00:00:43.720 --> 00:00:48.440
[Amit Varma]: result in are often delayed, and the causation is often not obvious.

00:00:48.440 --> 00:00:53.520
[Amit Varma]: We need to talk more about economics so that people don't get fooled by lofty narrative

00:00:53.520 --> 00:00:56.440
[Amit Varma]: and can figure out when they are being had.

00:00:56.440 --> 00:00:58.680
[Amit Varma]: That's one reason I started The Seen and The Unseen.

00:00:58.680 --> 00:01:02.880
[Amit Varma]: The title of the show is inspired by Frederick Barcia's famous essay, That Which is Seen

00:01:02.880 --> 00:01:04.200
[Amit Varma]: and That Which is Not Seen.

00:01:04.200 --> 00:01:09.680
[Amit Varma]: I thought I'd examine the seen intentions and unseen outcomes of public policy.

00:01:09.680 --> 00:01:12.400
[Amit Varma]: Of course, the show has evolved to be much, much more than that.

00:01:12.400 --> 00:01:17.520
[Amit Varma]: I now do deep dive conversations, studying to examine not just economics, but also politics,

00:01:17.520 --> 00:01:19.840
[Amit Varma]: society and even the human condition.

00:01:19.840 --> 00:01:25.320
[Amit Varma]: That said, economics is at the end of the day, the study of human behavior under conditions

00:01:25.320 --> 00:01:26.320
[Amit Varma]: of scarcity.

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:32.920
[Amit Varma]: And so here I am, doing something I do every few months, taking stock of the Indian economy.

00:01:32.920 --> 00:01:41.160
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:41.160 --> 00:01:42.160
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:42.160 --> 00:01:45.160
[Unknown]: Please welcome your host, Amit Badman.

00:01:45.160 --> 00:01:48.640
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen.

00:01:48.640 --> 00:01:52.140
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is a formidable economist, Ela Patnaik.

00:01:52.140 --> 00:01:56.720
[Amit Varma]: If there's one economic commentator whose body of work reveals a journey of the Indian

00:01:56.720 --> 00:01:59.200
[Amit Varma]: economy in the last 30 years, it's Ela.

00:01:59.200 --> 00:02:04.980
[Amit Varma]: A child of Marxist parents, Ela studied at JNU in the 1980s, but was encouraged by her

00:02:04.980 --> 00:02:07.640
[Amit Varma]: parents to think through the world for herself.

00:02:07.640 --> 00:02:10.560
[Amit Varma]: She went to do a PhD in England in the early 90s.

00:02:10.560 --> 00:02:15.800
[Amit Varma]: And just as India changed with liberalization, Ela swept aside the received dogmas of her

00:02:15.800 --> 00:02:19.700
[Amit Varma]: Indian education and discovered the wonders of an open economy.

00:02:19.700 --> 00:02:24.560
[Amit Varma]: She talks a fair bit about this fascinating journey in our conversation today, and also

00:02:24.560 --> 00:02:30.560
[Amit Varma]: of how for so many years she swam against the tide, both in economic policymaking and

00:02:30.560 --> 00:02:31.560
[Amit Varma]: in the public discourse.

00:02:31.560 --> 00:02:36.520
[Amit Varma]: Ela is a professor at the National Institute of Public Finance and Policy, NIPFP, and has

00:02:36.520 --> 00:02:42.560
[Amit Varma]: worked at many senior levels in Indian policymaking, including as a principal economic advisor

00:02:42.560 --> 00:02:44.160
[Amit Varma]: to the government of India.

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:49.080
[Amit Varma]: A mutual friend described her as an economist who brought macroeconomic thinking to India,

00:02:49.080 --> 00:02:53.380
[Amit Varma]: and she was one of the driving forces behind the RBI's inflation targeting.

00:02:53.380 --> 00:02:55.360
[Amit Varma]: If that sounds boring, it isn't.

00:02:55.360 --> 00:02:59.640
[Amit Varma]: Ela's also enlightened millions of people with her columns and her work on television,

00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:03.180
[Amit Varma]: and is now a bonafide econ superstar on YouTube.

00:03:03.180 --> 00:03:07.160
[Amit Varma]: She does a bunch of shows for the print, including one called Ela-nomics, I'll link it from the

00:03:07.160 --> 00:03:08.160
[Amit Varma]: show notes.

00:03:08.160 --> 00:03:12.640
[Amit Varma]: We not only discuss the road that she has traveled here, but also India's hesitant journey,

00:03:12.640 --> 00:03:17.920
[Amit Varma]: especially when it comes to economic reforms, where most of our governments since 1991 have

00:03:17.920 --> 00:03:19.720
[Amit Varma]: failed us, including this one.

00:03:19.720 --> 00:03:23.960
[Amit Varma]: There isn't a simple narrative that explains this, and what has gone wrong is not the fault

00:03:23.960 --> 00:03:25.720
[Amit Varma]: of one party alone.

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:30.960
[Amit Varma]: The Indian economy has been going down, down, down for over a decade now, when Pranab Mukherjee

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:36.040
[Amit Varma]: took over at the Finance Ministry and set us on the road to ruin, a road that Narendra

00:03:36.040 --> 00:03:39.200
[Amit Varma]: Modi's government seemed to gleefully embrace.

00:03:39.200 --> 00:03:43.960
[Amit Varma]: But if the decade leading up to 2020 was bad, the year since then has been worse because

00:03:43.960 --> 00:03:44.960
[Amit Varma]: of COVID.

00:03:44.960 --> 00:03:49.920
[Amit Varma]: Ela and I take it step by step, discussing our broad journey after 1991, zooming into

00:03:49.920 --> 00:03:55.200
[Amit Varma]: the last 10 years, and then zooming in further to the impact of COVID and looking ahead.

00:03:55.200 --> 00:04:00.120
[Amit Varma]: Like so many of my episodes, by the way, this feels like the latest installment in an ongoing

00:04:00.120 --> 00:04:02.000
[Amit Varma]: conversation on the seen and the unseen.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:06.040
[Amit Varma]: I've linked earlier episodes on the economy in the show notes, as also important episodes

00:04:06.040 --> 00:04:08.560
[Amit Varma]: with Pooja Mehra, Ajay Shah and Karthik Muralitharan.

00:04:08.560 --> 00:04:13.080
[Amit Varma]: Do you remember the argument Karthik and I had in our healthcare episode, episode 225

00:04:13.080 --> 00:04:15.040
[Amit Varma]: about the high taxes on petrol?

00:04:15.040 --> 00:04:19.960
[Amit Varma]: I feel they're horrendous, Karthik disagrees, and I got a chance to ask Ela for her views

00:04:19.960 --> 00:04:20.960
[Amit Varma]: on that.

00:04:20.960 --> 00:04:23.560
[Amit Varma]: Guess whose side she came down on, bloat, bloat.

00:04:23.560 --> 00:04:25.400
[Amit Varma]: Anyway, time now for the conversation.

