[Amit Varma]: The course costs Rs 10,000 plus GST, or about $150, and the June classes begin on June 5th.

00:05:11.800 --> 00:05:17.720
[Amit Varma]: So if you're interested, head on over to register at indiauncut.com slash clear writing.

00:05:17.720 --> 00:05:20.520
[Amit Varma]: That's indiauncut.com slash clear writing.

00:05:20.520 --> 00:05:25.200
[Amit Varma]: Being a good writer doesn't require God given talent, just the willingness to work hard

00:05:25.200 --> 00:05:29.560
[Amit Varma]: and a clear idea of what you need to do to refine your skills.

00:05:29.560 --> 00:05:30.560
[Amit Varma]: I can help you.

00:05:30.560 --> 00:05:33.880
[Amit Varma]: Hello, welcome to the scene in the unseen.

00:05:33.880 --> 00:05:34.880
[Guest]: Hi, Amit.

00:05:34.880 --> 00:05:35.880
[Guest]: How are you?

00:05:35.880 --> 00:05:36.880
[Amit Varma]: I'm good.

00:05:36.880 --> 00:05:40.920
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, that very question, how are you, you know, takes on kind of so much significance

00:05:40.920 --> 00:05:45.400
[Amit Varma]: in these times, because every day there is sort of some harrowing news from somewhere

00:05:45.400 --> 00:05:46.400
[Amit Varma]: or the other.

00:05:46.400 --> 00:05:47.400
[Amit Varma]: How are you?

00:05:47.400 --> 00:05:49.160
[Amit Varma]: How have the last few months been for you?

00:05:49.160 --> 00:05:52.200
[Guest]: Hunkered down, staying at home or work from home.

00:05:52.200 --> 00:05:57.960
[Guest]: We've just been fortunate that nobody very, very close has been ill or we've not lost

00:05:57.960 --> 00:06:03.480
[Guest]: somebody as in the immediate family, though, you know, these are difficult times.

00:06:03.480 --> 00:06:08.800
[Guest]: Every day we lose friends and family members in the extended family.

00:06:08.800 --> 00:06:11.760
[Amit Varma]: But now for the last few days, it's been a little bit better.

00:06:11.760 --> 00:06:12.760
[Amit Varma]: Wonderful.

00:06:12.760 --> 00:06:15.640
[Amit Varma]: So tell me about your early life.

00:06:15.640 --> 00:06:18.680
[Amit Varma]: Like I'm guessing you're a 70s and 80s kid.

00:06:18.680 --> 00:06:20.520
[Amit Varma]: You know, you're just a little older than me.

00:06:20.520 --> 00:06:24.400
[Amit Varma]: You went to college in the 1980s, Hindu College, then JNU, all of that.

00:06:24.400 --> 00:06:27.000
[Amit Varma]: Tell me about what those years were like growing up.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:28.360
[Amit Varma]: Like what kind of kid were you?

00:06:28.360 --> 00:06:32.200
[Amit Varma]: What drew you towards the sort of things that you studied?

00:06:32.200 --> 00:06:34.980
[Amit Varma]: And in general, what were the influences around you?

00:06:34.980 --> 00:06:38.840
[Amit Varma]: Because one of the things I realized while talking to guests who grew up around that

00:06:38.840 --> 00:06:43.040
[Amit Varma]: time or are of that age is that, you know, young people today have all the influences

00:06:43.040 --> 00:06:44.320
[Amit Varma]: of the world open to them.

00:06:44.320 --> 00:06:48.600
[Amit Varma]: You know, the whole world is at their fingertips through the Internet and whatever.

00:06:48.600 --> 00:06:54.320
[Amit Varma]: But back in the day, growing up in the 70s, 80s, even 90s, we got, you know, little driblets

00:06:54.320 --> 00:06:56.560
[Amit Varma]: of influences from here and there.

00:06:56.560 --> 00:07:01.680
[Amit Varma]: So whatever got through to us was, you know, likely to play a big part in shaping us.

00:07:01.680 --> 00:07:06.120
[Amit Varma]: Give me a sense of that landscape of your growing up in the, you know, when you did.

00:07:06.120 --> 00:07:09.160
[Guest]: So my parents were both professors at JNU.

00:07:09.160 --> 00:07:15.440
[Guest]: And that is, at least at that time, even more so was a place where there was always a lot

00:07:15.440 --> 00:07:16.680
[Guest]: of intellectual debate.

00:07:16.680 --> 00:07:21.640
[Guest]: There's always debate about issues, what's happening in the world.

00:07:21.640 --> 00:07:25.400
[Guest]: And you know, I was a science student till class 12.

00:07:25.400 --> 00:07:29.080
[Guest]: And I thought I would do science because I'd got the NTS.

00:07:29.080 --> 00:07:33.600
[Guest]: And you know, it was like, wow, at that time, it was very, a big achievement at that time,

00:07:33.600 --> 00:07:34.600
[Guest]: certainly.

00:07:34.600 --> 00:07:39.720
[Guest]: I was planning all the way to maybe take the JNU or something and then changed my mind

00:07:39.720 --> 00:07:45.160
[Guest]: because the kind of debates that we would have at home and with, you know, various.

00:07:45.160 --> 00:07:49.160
[Guest]: So my mothers and fathers, students and colleagues would always be dropping in.

00:07:49.160 --> 00:07:52.320
[Guest]: And, you know, there was always a lively debate.

00:07:52.320 --> 00:07:57.160
[Guest]: And I think that's what attracted me to economics that, you know, this is something I want to

00:07:57.160 --> 00:07:59.400
[Guest]: understand more deeply.

00:07:59.400 --> 00:08:06.080
[Guest]: And then instead of taking the JEE, I went and joined, I just applied for economics,

00:08:06.080 --> 00:08:07.080
[Guest]: actually.

00:08:07.080 --> 00:08:08.080
[Guest]: Only that.

00:08:08.080 --> 00:08:09.080
[Amit Varma]: Incredible.

00:08:09.080 --> 00:08:10.080
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a bit about your parents.

00:08:10.080 --> 00:08:14.240
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about the kind of debates you had at home, for example.

00:08:14.240 --> 00:08:19.880
[Guest]: There would be debates about what were the reasons for whatever was happening on the

00:08:19.880 --> 00:08:22.040
[Guest]: political scene.

00:08:22.040 --> 00:08:26.160
[Guest]: And usually it would be traced back to economics.

00:08:26.160 --> 00:08:32.720
[Guest]: And my parents were both Marxists, you know, JNU was, there was a lot of Marxism in JNU

00:08:32.720 --> 00:08:33.720
[Guest]: at that time.

00:08:33.720 --> 00:08:39.480
[Guest]: So my parents were like everybody else in JNU, quite leftist.

00:08:39.480 --> 00:08:43.760
[Guest]: And they would trace almost everything that happened in history.

00:08:43.760 --> 00:08:48.520
[Guest]: My mother was a professor of philosophy and my father of African studies, African politics.

00:08:48.520 --> 00:08:52.520
[Guest]: So everything would get traced back to economics.

00:08:52.520 --> 00:08:57.080
[Guest]: And I mean, that's basically Marxism that it is that the economy is the base and the

00:08:57.080 --> 00:08:58.080
[Guest]: rest of the superstructure.

00:08:58.080 --> 00:08:59.520
[Guest]: So it would go back to that.

00:08:59.520 --> 00:09:06.240
[Guest]: I mean, I didn't, you know, perhaps stick to many of those kind of beliefs, which I

00:09:06.240 --> 00:09:09.000
[Guest]: think were far more rigid than they should have been.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:14.740
[Guest]: But in terms of trying to understand the world, that was my beginning.

00:09:14.740 --> 00:09:18.440
[Guest]: That was the place from where I started.

00:09:18.440 --> 00:09:22.320
[Amit Varma]: And I guess initially there must have then been an attraction to Marxism itself, because

00:09:22.320 --> 00:09:26.400
[Amit Varma]: I think the attraction to all big ideas is that, hey, this explains the world so well.

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:27.880
[Amit Varma]: And that's why you were attracted to it.

00:09:27.880 --> 00:09:31.560
[Amit Varma]: But there is a trap there that then you can try to explain everything through that.

00:09:31.560 --> 00:09:33.400
[Amit Varma]: So what was that attraction like?

00:09:33.400 --> 00:09:34.840
[Amit Varma]: And how did you kind of get past it?

00:09:34.840 --> 00:09:40.920
[Amit Varma]: Like, when did you begin to get past it and rebel as it were against your parents beliefs?

00:09:40.920 --> 00:09:46.560
[Guest]: Only after I was only after I finished my master's.

00:09:46.560 --> 00:09:52.160
[Guest]: So while I was in college, while I was at university, anyway, you know, you think of

00:09:52.160 --> 00:09:57.960
[Guest]: the influences at that time, the friends you have, everybody around you and at home.

00:09:57.960 --> 00:10:06.160
[Guest]: So those were very, very, I should say, dominant influences, both because of social circles,

00:10:06.160 --> 00:10:09.600
[Guest]: as well as the general atmosphere.

00:10:09.600 --> 00:10:13.440
[Guest]: So I did my master's at the Center for Economic Studies and Planning where, you know, we had

00:10:13.440 --> 00:10:20.320
[Guest]: Prabhat Patnaik, Utsav Patnaik, now later Jayati Ghosh was my MPhil advisor.

00:10:20.320 --> 00:10:25.480
[Guest]: But you know, towards the end of my master's and beginning of my MPhil, which I did my

00:10:25.480 --> 00:10:27.080
[Guest]: MPhil in JNU.

00:10:27.080 --> 00:10:30.800
[Guest]: So that time I started, you know, questioning too many things.

00:10:30.800 --> 00:10:37.240
[Guest]: So I think I'm not a person who can belong to any political party because what that requires

00:10:37.240 --> 00:10:41.040
[Guest]: is agreeing with 100% of everything they say.

00:10:41.040 --> 00:10:47.800
[Guest]: So you know, regardless of which the party is, every party member is expected to, you

00:10:47.800 --> 00:10:50.240
[Guest]: know, carry forward the party line.

00:10:50.240 --> 00:10:54.800
[Guest]: So that really didn't suit me as I questioned too many things.

00:10:54.800 --> 00:11:00.560
[Guest]: So I think that's when it became clear that no, this is not where my future lies.

00:11:00.560 --> 00:11:05.960
[Amit Varma]: In fact, what you just said about, you know, that need for purity, we see it more and more

00:11:05.960 --> 00:11:11.400
[Amit Varma]: in social media these days where, you know, you have different echo chambers forming and

00:11:11.400 --> 00:11:14.120
[Amit Varma]: stringent enforcements of, you know, purity.

00:11:14.120 --> 00:11:18.000
[Amit Varma]: And like I always say that, you know, whenever I go on Twitter or whatever, and you see labels

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:23.000
[Amit Varma]: thrown about like socialist or libertarian or this or that, and I think all labels are

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:27.240
[Amit Varma]: fundamentally toxic because all labels are limiting in a particular sense.

00:11:27.240 --> 00:11:31.800
[Amit Varma]: And it's almost as if like 90% of the time, those labels are used on social media.

00:11:31.800 --> 00:11:36.320
[Amit Varma]: It's as if you're trying to put someone in a category of us or the other.

00:11:36.320 --> 00:11:38.960
[Amit Varma]: And that just makes the whole discourse very toxic.

00:11:38.960 --> 00:11:43.040
[Amit Varma]: But to kind of get back to, you know, your sort of intellectual evolution during those

00:11:43.040 --> 00:11:48.320
[Amit Varma]: times, were there any sort of aha moments during that phase, like, of course, there

00:11:48.320 --> 00:11:52.000
[Amit Varma]: are these little pinpricks of questionings when you're saying, wait a minute, you're

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:55.120
[Amit Varma]: saying this, and this doesn't seem quite right, it's surely more nuanced.

00:11:55.120 --> 00:11:56.120
[Amit Varma]: And I get that.

00:11:56.120 --> 00:11:59.840
[Amit Varma]: But were there sort of any aha moments when you look at things differently?

00:11:59.840 --> 00:12:03.520
[Amit Varma]: Any books that kind of influenced you that way?

00:12:03.520 --> 00:12:09.320
[Guest]: So I remember one moment, which was when, you know, some of the, there was some meeting

00:12:09.320 --> 00:12:16.480
[Guest]: going on, and some of the leftist, leading leftist leaders were opposing infrastructure

00:12:16.480 --> 00:12:21.600
[Guest]: development in Delhi, saying, oh, you're building these big roads and highways, and there are

00:12:21.600 --> 00:12:22.600
[Guest]: people starving.

00:12:22.600 --> 00:12:29.480
[Guest]: And, you know, I stood up from wherever I was, I was maybe 19, 18, 19 or something.

00:12:29.480 --> 00:12:34.080
[Guest]: And I stood up and said, no, no, we need the roads, I stood up from the audience, and this

00:12:34.080 --> 00:12:35.080
[Guest]: person was on stage.

00:12:35.080 --> 00:12:39.280
[Guest]: And I said, no, we need the roads, we, you know, that's how GDP will grow.

00:12:39.280 --> 00:12:41.960
[Guest]: You are not going to remove poverty without GDP growth.

00:12:41.960 --> 00:12:44.680
[Guest]: So you have to have infrastructure.

00:12:44.680 --> 00:12:50.040
[Guest]: And everybody was stunned, because, you know, that was not something that people said at

00:12:50.040 --> 00:12:51.040
[Guest]: that time.

00:12:51.040 --> 00:12:54.000
[Guest]: So this is in the early 80s.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:13:00.760
[Guest]: And it was almost as if anything Western is bad, any modernization, any infrastructure

00:13:00.760 --> 00:13:05.240
[Guest]: development, which is, you know, these big flyovers, why are you spending money on flyovers?

00:13:05.240 --> 00:13:09.520
[Guest]: I don't remember too many other incidents, but that was one that like kind of hit me

00:13:09.520 --> 00:13:12.600
[Guest]: that no, no, no, this is completely wrong.

00:13:12.600 --> 00:13:14.500
[Guest]: This is not what it should be.

00:13:14.500 --> 00:13:19.000
[Amit Varma]: And it also speaks to like a fundamental mindset that we've kind of had, and we still in many

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:24.040
[Amit Varma]: ways have, which is a very intuitive mindset of seeing the world as a zero-sum place, right?

00:13:24.040 --> 00:13:27.840
[Amit Varma]: That if you're spending on roads, you know, you should be spending the poor instead, as

00:13:27.840 --> 00:13:29.600
[Amit Varma]: if there is a fixed pie.

00:13:29.600 --> 00:13:33.280
[Amit Varma]: And of course, that whole zero-sum mindset plays into everything.

00:13:33.280 --> 00:13:37.880
[Amit Varma]: It plays into when you talk about redistribution vis-a-vis growth, it plays into practically

00:13:37.880 --> 00:13:38.960
[Amit Varma]: everything that we do.

00:13:38.960 --> 00:13:42.320
[Amit Varma]: And in some cases, it needs to because the government does have a limited sum of money

00:13:42.320 --> 00:13:45.840
[Amit Varma]: and there are opportunity costs and all of that, of course, is there.

00:13:45.840 --> 00:13:50.720
[Amit Varma]: But as far as the economy is concerned, it's dangerous to think of it that way.

00:13:50.720 --> 00:13:55.600
[Amit Varma]: Now, what I've often seen, like when I kind of grew up in the 80s, you know, I kind of

00:13:55.600 --> 00:13:59.720
[Amit Varma]: imbibed all the typical conventional wisdom, which involves this kind of zero-sum thinking

00:13:59.720 --> 00:14:00.760
[Amit Varma]: as well.

00:14:00.760 --> 00:14:04.820
[Amit Varma]: And it's natural to do that, one, because of course, the environment around me was that

00:14:04.820 --> 00:14:10.280
[Amit Varma]: kind of proto-socialist environment, my, you know, my dad was an IAS officer, and it was

00:14:10.280 --> 00:14:14.880
[Amit Varma]: just natural to believe in the power of the state and not think of the fatal conceit as

00:14:14.880 --> 00:14:15.880
[Amit Varma]: it were.

00:14:15.880 --> 00:14:19.880
[Amit Varma]: But a lot of the truths about the world are deeply counterintuitive, that things are not

00:14:19.880 --> 00:14:24.080
[Amit Varma]: zero-sum, that the economy is a positive something, that there is something called spontaneous

00:14:24.080 --> 00:14:28.080
[Amit Varma]: order that sometimes you, you know, the government can achieve things not by trying to control

00:14:28.080 --> 00:14:32.640
[Amit Varma]: it from the top down, but by just enabling society to solve its own problems.

00:14:32.640 --> 00:14:34.680
[Amit Varma]: But these are very counterintuitive.

00:14:34.680 --> 00:14:39.360
[Amit Varma]: So over a period of time when, you know, what was that kind of process like when you try

00:14:39.360 --> 00:14:40.760
[Amit Varma]: to figure this stuff out?

00:14:40.760 --> 00:14:44.600
[Amit Varma]: Were there particular books, were there thinkers who influenced you?

00:14:44.600 --> 00:14:48.840
[Amit Varma]: Take me through a little bit of that intellectual evolution that you must have gone through.

00:14:48.840 --> 00:14:53.240
[Amit Varma]: And I guess some of it would be academics, but some of it would also be outside academics,

00:14:53.240 --> 00:14:56.480
[Amit Varma]: just looking at things around you as it were.

00:14:56.480 --> 00:14:58.840
[Guest]: Yes, so two things really.

00:14:58.840 --> 00:15:09.560
[Guest]: One in terms of being in JNU and with people here, I felt very uncomfortable when I was

00:15:09.560 --> 00:15:12.280
[Guest]: told what to think.

00:15:12.280 --> 00:15:17.240
[Guest]: I mean, being told what to say is something else, but I've been fortunate that my mother

00:15:17.240 --> 00:15:21.280
[Guest]: was a PhD in philosophy and a professor of philosophy.

00:15:21.280 --> 00:15:26.560
[Guest]: And I had been taught to question, question, question, question, question from, you know,

00:15:26.560 --> 00:15:28.840
[Guest]: from the day I was born, I was taught to question.

00:15:28.840 --> 00:15:35.320
[Guest]: And so I became quite uncomfortable when I was told to accept things because I was being

00:15:35.320 --> 00:15:36.440
[Guest]: told something.

00:15:36.440 --> 00:15:41.040
[Guest]: And so that was one, you know, in terms of the environment, that was the one thing that

00:15:41.040 --> 00:15:43.400
[Guest]: I rebelled against.

00:15:43.400 --> 00:15:49.600
[Guest]: And I find myself very uncomfortable in situations when people tell me what to think.

00:15:49.600 --> 00:15:53.760
[Guest]: But I think the second was going for my PhD to a completely different system.

00:15:53.760 --> 00:15:56.520
[Guest]: So I went to the UK for my PhD.

00:15:56.520 --> 00:16:03.680
[Guest]: I got this Commonwealth Nehru Centenary Fellowship, which after JNU, which was a big, big change.

00:16:03.680 --> 00:16:10.720
[Guest]: So the things that one learned, the things one saw, my PhD advisor, everything, you know,

00:16:10.720 --> 00:16:14.160
[Guest]: helped in making me think very, very differently.

00:16:14.160 --> 00:16:20.720
[Guest]: So I should say I came back a very different person, in my mind, I came back different,

00:16:20.720 --> 00:16:24.160
[Guest]: thought differently, completely.

00:16:24.160 --> 00:16:25.600
[Amit Varma]: And how did your parents react to that?

00:16:25.600 --> 00:16:31.240
[Amit Varma]: The fact that, you know, you're no longer the obedient little Marxist girl, but you've

00:16:31.240 --> 00:16:32.240
[Amit Varma]: become something else.

00:16:32.240 --> 00:16:34.000
[Guest]: No, they were okay with it.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:40.120
[Guest]: I mean, the way that, you know, the fundamental principle was that you have to think for yourself,

00:16:40.120 --> 00:16:41.120
[Guest]: not for my parents.

00:16:41.120 --> 00:16:44.480
[Guest]: So, you know, for the others, it might be different, but for my parents, it was that

00:16:44.480 --> 00:16:46.320
[Guest]: you have to think for yourself.

00:16:46.320 --> 00:16:50.560
[Guest]: And no matter what you think, whether you agree or you disagree, the most important

00:16:50.560 --> 00:16:55.720
[Guest]: thing is that you think for yourself and not say or do things that you're told to do.

00:16:55.720 --> 00:17:01.440
[Guest]: In fact, my father, right from my childhood, discouraged me to join the bureaucracy.

00:17:01.440 --> 00:17:07.360
[Guest]: So he said, no, this is not something for you because, you know, you question too much.

00:17:07.360 --> 00:17:12.920
[Guest]: I was perhaps the only one in my master's class who did not take the UPSC exam because

00:17:12.920 --> 00:17:15.280
[Guest]: at that time there weren't many jobs around.

00:17:15.280 --> 00:17:18.560
[Guest]: So almost everybody was taking these competitive exams.

00:17:18.560 --> 00:17:23.160
[Guest]: But, you know, my father was, no, you have to think for yourself and this is not something

00:17:23.160 --> 00:17:29.800
[Guest]: you can do if you are part of a bureaucracy, which I understand very well.

00:17:29.800 --> 00:17:33.120
[Guest]: So yes, they were fine with it.

00:17:33.120 --> 00:17:34.120
[Amit Varma]: That's wonderful.

00:17:34.120 --> 00:17:38.760
[Amit Varma]: It strikes me that every good economist is not just shaped by the study of economics,

00:17:38.760 --> 00:17:42.920
[Amit Varma]: but also whatever other influences they're kind of exposed to.

00:17:42.920 --> 00:17:46.460
[Amit Varma]: And on the one hand, you have like your mom is a professor of philosophy, you're questioning

00:17:46.460 --> 00:17:51.080
[Amit Varma]: things like you said, too, I would imagine that, you know, because we had these political

00:17:51.080 --> 00:17:55.800
[Amit Varma]: discussions at home and so on and so forth, there would also have been a very keen focus

00:17:55.800 --> 00:17:59.040
[Amit Varma]: in your mind on the intersection of economics in the real world.

00:17:59.040 --> 00:18:02.560
[Amit Varma]: It's not just something that you're studying, it's something that actually affects lives

00:18:02.560 --> 00:18:06.800
[Amit Varma]: like in that early example of, you know, fighting for roads.

00:18:06.800 --> 00:18:11.240
[Amit Varma]: So you know, if you were to then look at that, what are the different kinds of things that

00:18:11.240 --> 00:18:15.680
[Amit Varma]: shape the economist you are apart from the economics, like part of it would, I'm guessing,

00:18:15.680 --> 00:18:18.960
[Amit Varma]: be the politics, was there reading that went into it?

00:18:18.960 --> 00:18:22.520
[Amit Varma]: You know, give me a sort of a fuller sense of yourself, if I may ask.

00:18:22.520 --> 00:18:28.120
[Guest]: One of the most important things, apart from, you know, reading books and things which naturally

00:18:28.120 --> 00:18:32.760
[Guest]: you can imagine, you know, being in a house surrounded by books, one did that.

00:18:32.760 --> 00:18:37.960
[Guest]: But I think one of the very important things was this daily reading of newspapers from

00:18:37.960 --> 00:18:39.440
[Guest]: childhood.

00:18:39.440 --> 00:18:42.680
[Guest]: And I think many people don't perhaps do that.

00:18:42.680 --> 00:18:47.840
[Guest]: And so maybe they're not so connected with the world and with the country.

00:18:47.840 --> 00:18:51.360
[Guest]: But if you're doing that every day, and if you're sitting around, you know, the dinner

00:18:51.360 --> 00:18:57.120
[Guest]: table talking about what happened and why it happened, and you're doing that at breakfast,

00:18:57.120 --> 00:18:58.720
[Guest]: you're doing that at dinner.

00:18:58.720 --> 00:19:01.200
[Guest]: So you know, you do that day after day.

00:19:01.200 --> 00:19:05.780
[Guest]: I think that really makes a difference to who you are and what you want to do.

00:19:05.780 --> 00:19:10.800
[Guest]: So if you know, you kind of get into that, that I don't just want to interpret the world,

00:19:10.800 --> 00:19:16.480
[Guest]: I want to change it, but not necessarily by a communist revolution.

00:19:16.480 --> 00:19:22.500
[Guest]: But it just goes in so deep that when you see problems, so you know, when you grow up,

00:19:22.500 --> 00:19:29.560
[Guest]: you want to like, for me, I've always worked on last 20 years, 25 years, my entire working

00:19:29.560 --> 00:19:35.840
[Guest]: life as an economist has been working on real problems that are there in the economy, and

00:19:35.840 --> 00:19:41.440
[Guest]: not on something, you know, abstract or something very far away.

00:19:41.440 --> 00:19:46.480
[Guest]: So it's been working on those problems, and then trying to work towards solutions wherever

00:19:46.480 --> 00:19:49.440
[Guest]: one could find those and working towards that.

00:19:49.440 --> 00:19:53.440
[Guest]: And I think that's the influence really.

00:19:53.440 --> 00:19:55.800
[Amit Varma]: And were the newspapers you read English newspapers?

00:19:55.800 --> 00:19:57.240
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah.

00:19:57.240 --> 00:20:01.760
[Amit Varma]: So we used to get let me let me ask you a question not quite related to economics, but

00:20:01.760 --> 00:20:06.320
[Amit Varma]: it's come up on my show before and it came up recently, like one of my friends recently

00:20:06.320 --> 00:20:11.080
[Amit Varma]: posted on Twitter, where he kind of lamented that we are such a divided nation today.

00:20:11.080 --> 00:20:15.080
[Amit Varma]: And I don't remember us being so divided in the 80s and the 90s.

00:20:15.080 --> 00:20:18.880
[Amit Varma]: And you know, and my point there was that no, we were always divided, we were just in

00:20:18.880 --> 00:20:22.640
[Amit Varma]: a bubble and the bubble wasn't divided, but we were in a bubble where we didn't kind of

00:20:22.640 --> 00:20:24.420
[Amit Varma]: see the rest of the country.

00:20:24.420 --> 00:20:28.200
[Amit Varma]: And I've had guests on the show before, like Akshay Mukul, who wrote the book on the Gita

00:20:28.200 --> 00:20:32.160
[Amit Varma]: Press and the political scientist, Rahul Verma.

00:20:32.160 --> 00:20:36.440
[Amit Varma]: And one of the interesting points I got while talking to them was that growing up they read

00:20:36.440 --> 00:20:41.640
[Amit Varma]: newspapers in Hindi, and, you know, other guests have read newspapers in their languages.

00:20:41.640 --> 00:20:46.840
[Amit Varma]: And their contention was that because they were not just reading, you know, English newspapers,

00:20:46.840 --> 00:20:50.960
[Amit Varma]: they could see outside the elite bubble, they got a sense of what the other India as it

00:20:50.960 --> 00:20:53.480
[Amit Varma]: were, was also like to them.

00:20:53.480 --> 00:20:58.400
[Amit Varma]: In fact, this upsurge of Hindutva is not an aberration, but you know, it was always there,

00:20:58.400 --> 00:20:59.960
[Amit Varma]: it was always kind of coming up.

00:20:59.960 --> 00:21:02.920
[Amit Varma]: And I don't want to ask you about the politics in particular.

00:21:02.920 --> 00:21:06.960
[Amit Varma]: But the thing is, even I grew up in a similar elite bubble to yours, I'm guessing where

00:21:06.960 --> 00:21:10.160
[Amit Varma]: you're just reading everything in English, and you're mixing with a certain kind of people

00:21:10.160 --> 00:21:11.640
[Amit Varma]: and all of that.

00:21:11.640 --> 00:21:17.280
[Amit Varma]: And at what point does one sort of get awareness of that bubble and be able to actually see

00:21:17.280 --> 00:21:21.640
[Amit Varma]: outside like not in a sense of intellectually knowing that, yeah, you know, there are, you

00:21:21.640 --> 00:21:25.920
[Amit Varma]: know, there's a world out there that is different, but, you know, actually in terms of getting

00:21:25.920 --> 00:21:27.200
[Amit Varma]: it engaging with it.

00:21:27.200 --> 00:21:35.760
[Guest]: I think I was fortunate because my parents, being communists, they would be people who

00:21:35.760 --> 00:21:39.880
[Guest]: would be coming straight from villages, so they were not like they were not leaders,

00:21:39.880 --> 00:21:43.600
[Guest]: they were not active, but just, you know, the fact that they were JNU professors, people

00:21:43.600 --> 00:21:45.760
[Guest]: would come to them, meet them.

00:21:45.760 --> 00:21:50.960
[Guest]: Many of my father's students would, you know, couldn't speak a word of English, would be

00:21:50.960 --> 00:21:52.400
[Guest]: right straight from a village.

00:21:52.400 --> 00:21:55.800
[Guest]: We also had a, there was a reservation system in JNU.

00:21:55.800 --> 00:22:00.840
[Guest]: So that encouraged, they used to give points for coming from a backward region, from a

00:22:00.840 --> 00:22:04.560
[Guest]: lower income category, and the rest.

00:22:04.560 --> 00:22:06.680
[Guest]: And that would encourage a lot of people to come.

00:22:06.680 --> 00:22:11.000
[Guest]: So I think that I was fortunate that I wasn't, I mean, of course, English newspapers were

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:13.240
[Guest]: something that, you know, you read what you get at home.

00:22:13.240 --> 00:22:19.680
[Guest]: We used to get, I think, one Hindi Jan Satta or something, Hindi paper on Sundays.

00:22:19.680 --> 00:22:22.480
[Guest]: But you know, you and I didn't have a choice.

00:22:22.480 --> 00:22:26.680
[Guest]: We were born into the family, we were born in and we read the papers that our parents

00:22:26.680 --> 00:22:27.680
[Guest]: bought.

00:22:27.680 --> 00:22:33.240
[Guest]: But, you know, I was fortunate in that sense that there was a mix of people and a lot of

00:22:33.240 --> 00:22:41.000
[Guest]: them not elite coming from backgrounds, which and my mother particularly used to, you know,

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:47.680
[Guest]: encourage them to come home to her students when they came from backgrounds where they

00:22:47.680 --> 00:22:49.840
[Guest]: had huge gaps also in their learning.

00:22:49.840 --> 00:22:53.280
[Guest]: So they would be sitting and, you know, working with her and studying.

00:22:53.280 --> 00:22:58.480
[Guest]: So I was fortunate not to, you know, be in a complete bubble and to be able to interact

00:22:58.480 --> 00:23:03.520
[Guest]: with people from all over the country and from different backgrounds.

00:23:03.520 --> 00:23:08.400
[Amit Varma]: And how did your conception of yourself during these years kind of evolve like for a lot

00:23:08.400 --> 00:23:10.840
[Amit Varma]: of people, certainly for me, it's very shaky early on.

00:23:10.840 --> 00:23:15.880
[Amit Varma]: It takes many years to get to somewhere where you can kind of begin to think of yourself

00:23:15.880 --> 00:23:16.880
[Amit Varma]: as well.

00:23:16.880 --> 00:23:17.880
[Amit Varma]: These are the things I want to do.

00:23:17.880 --> 00:23:20.520
[Amit Varma]: And this is a place I want to occupy in the world and all of that.

00:23:20.520 --> 00:23:25.360
[Amit Varma]: And yet it seems just looking at your bare biographical details where you do your BA

00:23:25.360 --> 00:23:30.160
[Amit Varma]: in economics from Hindu and then your MA and your MPhil from JNU and then you go to the

00:23:30.160 --> 00:23:33.840
[Amit Varma]: University of Surrey and you do your PhD and then you come back here.

00:23:33.840 --> 00:23:37.520
[Amit Varma]: And just looking at the bare bones of that, it seems that okay, you kind of got it figured

00:23:37.520 --> 00:23:40.220
[Amit Varma]: out that you want to learn economics the best you can.

00:23:40.220 --> 00:23:44.520
[Amit Varma]: And then you want to kind of work within India and try to actually make a difference in the

00:23:44.520 --> 00:23:45.520
[Amit Varma]: real world.

00:23:45.520 --> 00:23:46.520
[Amit Varma]: Was it always kind of like that?

00:23:46.520 --> 00:23:49.120
[Amit Varma]: Or did your conception of self evolve?

00:23:49.120 --> 00:23:55.320
[Amit Varma]: Like at what point did it firm up and what is that conception of self in a sense?

00:23:55.320 --> 00:23:58.520
[Guest]: Well, to begin with, what is that conception?

00:23:58.520 --> 00:24:03.120
[Guest]: It is that I try to do what I can, I try to understand what I can.

00:24:03.120 --> 00:24:10.160
[Guest]: And as I said, one has been, I guess, brought up in a way that it's almost as if every problem

00:24:10.160 --> 00:24:12.060
[Guest]: is one's own responsibility.

00:24:12.060 --> 00:24:14.560
[Guest]: So if you see a problem, you don't ignore it.

00:24:14.560 --> 00:24:18.320
[Guest]: You study it, you understand it and you see if there is a way out.

00:24:18.320 --> 00:24:21.240
[Guest]: And in economic policy, there are so many problems.

00:24:21.240 --> 00:24:26.840
[Guest]: And particularly when one is coming from a background where, as a country, when we are

00:24:26.840 --> 00:24:32.000
[Guest]: coming from a background where we had almost stopped people from doing anything, there

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:38.580
[Guest]: were so many restrictions, then it's a great place to study economics and understand what's

00:24:38.580 --> 00:24:39.580
[Guest]: going on.

00:24:39.580 --> 00:24:44.200
[Guest]: Because you see where the restrictions are removed, what happens and when they are not,

00:24:44.200 --> 00:24:45.600
[Guest]: then what happens.

00:24:45.600 --> 00:24:52.000
[Guest]: And then it's also if you are in that space where, so I always wanted to write and I started

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:58.080
[Guest]: writing right after my PhD and once I started working on the Indian economy.

00:24:58.080 --> 00:25:04.540
[Guest]: So you are in a place where you can study it and at least, the least one can do is write

00:25:04.540 --> 00:25:09.460
[Guest]: about those issues and help everybody understand your point of view.

00:25:09.460 --> 00:25:15.580
[Guest]: So I'm not in the bureaucracy or a politician who can actually be the ones who decide that

00:25:15.580 --> 00:25:17.480
[Guest]: change happens.

00:25:17.480 --> 00:25:25.000
[Guest]: But it happens because of ideas, because one writes and people listen and read and if one

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:30.640
[Guest]: is able to speak in a language that is simple and convey what one thinks, then people get

00:25:30.640 --> 00:25:36.680
[Guest]: convinced and you know, then that's what makes life meaningful.

00:25:36.680 --> 00:25:42.460
[Amit Varma]: And how important is that role as a public intellectual in the sense that you are an

00:25:42.460 --> 00:25:45.920
[Amit Varma]: economist at the same time, you're someone who has worked with the government at different

00:25:45.920 --> 00:25:49.040
[Amit Varma]: times as an advisor and so on and so forth.

00:25:49.040 --> 00:25:54.120
[Amit Varma]: At the same time, you've written prolifically, you've done forays into audiovisual, you know,

00:25:54.120 --> 00:25:58.280
[Amit Varma]: for example, you had policy with Patnaik, your show for NDTV more than a decade ago

00:25:58.280 --> 00:26:02.760
[Amit Varma]: and now you do Elonomics and you know, the other stuff that you do for the print, like

00:26:02.760 --> 00:26:07.280
[Amit Varma]: a lot of people will write a lot because it kind of helps them in their thinking process

00:26:07.280 --> 00:26:10.920
[Amit Varma]: that you know, as they write, they learn more about a subject and it's something they want

00:26:10.920 --> 00:26:11.920
[Amit Varma]: to do.

00:26:11.920 --> 00:26:15.600
[Amit Varma]: And another way of looking at it is that look, if I want to make a difference, that difference

00:26:15.600 --> 00:26:20.040
[Amit Varma]: also comes from getting these ideas out there in the discourse.

00:26:20.040 --> 00:26:24.160
[Amit Varma]: And one of the issues with this, I'm guessing for you would have been that the discourse

00:26:24.160 --> 00:26:25.560
[Amit Varma]: is kind of stunted.

00:26:25.560 --> 00:26:29.520
[Amit Varma]: In a sense, some of the things that you say at different points in time, and certainly

00:26:29.520 --> 00:26:34.000
[Amit Varma]: I would imagine it would be the case in the 90s, are just not out there, right?

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:35.760
[Amit Varma]: So what has this process been for you?

00:26:35.760 --> 00:26:40.920
[Amit Varma]: Like, do you do you see it as, you know, part of your duty almost to do this stuff, to have

00:26:40.920 --> 00:26:42.760
[Guest]: this public facing face as well?

00:26:42.760 --> 00:26:44.120
[Guest]: Yes, absolutely.

00:26:44.120 --> 00:26:50.180
[Guest]: So I get a stomachache if I don't say what I am thinking, if I don't write.

00:26:50.180 --> 00:26:54.640
[Guest]: So I've always, you know, been writing, I used to have a column in the Business Standard

00:26:54.640 --> 00:27:00.520
[Guest]: and the Indian Express and, you know, apart from the TV show and the print column that

00:27:00.520 --> 00:27:01.880
[Guest]: I'm doing now.

00:27:01.880 --> 00:27:03.720
[Guest]: So it's almost, it's a part of me.

00:27:03.720 --> 00:27:05.600
[Guest]: I mean, now I've done it for so long.

00:27:05.600 --> 00:27:08.360
[Guest]: I started writing my columns in 99.

00:27:08.360 --> 00:27:13.280
[Guest]: So it's just been, you know, too many years for me to even think of myself as separate

00:27:13.280 --> 00:27:14.280
[Unknown]: from that.

00:27:14.280 --> 00:27:18.840
[Guest]: It was very painful during when I was in government, I was told not to write, I had to stop writing.

00:27:18.840 --> 00:27:23.880
[Guest]: So for a year and a half, of course, they kept me so busy that it didn't, you know,

00:27:23.880 --> 00:27:24.880
[Guest]: hurt too much.

00:27:24.880 --> 00:27:28.480
[Guest]: And some of the things I was doing was what I had been writing about.

00:27:28.480 --> 00:27:29.680
[Guest]: So it didn't hurt that much.

00:27:29.680 --> 00:27:36.960
[Guest]: But yeah, it's very difficult to be somebody who doesn't, isn't thinking, isn't worrying,

00:27:36.960 --> 00:27:41.280
[Guest]: isn't talking, isn't trying to convince, isn't trying to help other people to understand.

00:27:41.280 --> 00:27:44.480
[Guest]: So it's very much completely a part of me.

00:27:44.480 --> 00:27:51.240
[Guest]: I mean, I'm just fortunate that I'm in a situation where I have the freedom to do so, where I'm

00:27:51.240 --> 00:27:56.400
[Guest]: able to do so, where I have the time and the luxury because, you know, many jobs don't

00:27:56.400 --> 00:27:59.040
[Guest]: even give you the time to do that.

00:27:59.040 --> 00:28:02.320
[Guest]: So fortunately, you know, we are able to do that.

00:28:02.320 --> 00:28:06.160
[Guest]: So it's a good place to be in.

00:28:06.160 --> 00:28:10.760
[Amit Varma]: And for people who care about ideas, I guess, especially people who engage deeply with policy

00:28:10.760 --> 00:28:15.560
[Amit Varma]: like you do, I guess there is a sort of a dual imperative, which for many people is

00:28:15.560 --> 00:28:19.160
[Amit Varma]: an either or where on the one hand, when you look at the political marketplace, what you're

00:28:19.160 --> 00:28:25.860
[Amit Varma]: saying is that I want to be able to influence the decision makers to make the right decisions.

00:28:25.860 --> 00:28:29.440
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, you're looking at the demand end of the political marketplace and

00:28:29.440 --> 00:28:33.880
[Amit Varma]: saying that I want to get my ideas out in the public domain, where you know, they can

00:28:33.880 --> 00:28:37.560
[Amit Varma]: hopefully change the discourse and then the change at the top can happen later.

00:28:37.560 --> 00:28:40.980
[Amit Varma]: And you're someone who's kind of been trying to do this simultaneously.

00:28:40.980 --> 00:28:46.160
[Amit Varma]: And I would just imagine thinking aloud, that this then almost creates two contradictory

00:28:46.160 --> 00:28:50.320
[Amit Varma]: pressures that when you're working with policy makers, and when you're working with government,

00:28:50.320 --> 00:28:54.320
[Amit Varma]: you have to moderate your ideas, you have to talk about incremental steps go one step

00:28:54.320 --> 00:28:55.320
[Amit Varma]: at a time.

00:28:55.320 --> 00:29:00.300
[Amit Varma]: But when you're trying to get your ideas out into the public domain, there is perhaps the

00:29:00.300 --> 00:29:06.160
[Amit Varma]: urge to kind of just lay it all out as it is, because you know, why that urge to moderation?

00:29:06.160 --> 00:29:08.680
[Amit Varma]: Why not move that Overton window as it were?

00:29:08.680 --> 00:29:10.640
[Amit Varma]: So is this something that you've thought about?

00:29:10.640 --> 00:29:13.720
[Amit Varma]: Or is it that you've managed to reconcile these easily?

00:29:13.720 --> 00:29:14.720
[Guest]: Yes.

00:29:14.720 --> 00:29:19.080
[Guest]: So usually I end up saying things many years before the world is ready to hear them.

00:29:19.080 --> 00:29:23.800
[Guest]: So you know, things like inflation targeting, which I started writing about in 2006.

00:29:23.800 --> 00:29:26.440
[Guest]: And then finally, it happened in 2016.

00:29:26.440 --> 00:29:30.840
[Guest]: So and there are many such examples, you know, talking about business cycles, microstabilization,

00:29:30.840 --> 00:29:33.000
[Guest]: many, many, most of my work.

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:38.400
[Guest]: So you know, when nobody listens, and it's okay, you get a bit disappointed, you get

00:29:38.400 --> 00:29:43.120
[Guest]: but that's life, you know, and if you obsess on it, and you go on for some time, and then

00:29:43.120 --> 00:29:46.120
[Guest]: you realize, okay, nobody's listening.

00:29:46.120 --> 00:29:51.840
[Guest]: So you step back and you say, okay, let me write about something that people talk about.

00:29:51.840 --> 00:29:56.400
[Guest]: But then every once in a while, you get an opportunity, you know, there's a peg, and

00:29:56.400 --> 00:30:01.400
[Guest]: you get an opportunity and you write about some of the things that are dearest to you.

00:30:01.400 --> 00:30:06.480
[Guest]: But you know, there's not that much of a contradiction and conflict that I feel because most of the

00:30:06.480 --> 00:30:14.040
[Guest]: time, one is able to interpret and understand things because of a understanding of the larger

00:30:14.040 --> 00:30:15.760
[Guest]: picture.

00:30:15.760 --> 00:30:18.160
[Guest]: And then you write and talk about those.

00:30:18.160 --> 00:30:23.440
[Guest]: So when let's say there is a capital control that is imposed, which is completely arbitrary

00:30:23.440 --> 00:30:27.920
[Guest]: and which you know is going to hurt, you know, these things keep happening.

00:30:27.920 --> 00:30:34.680
[Guest]: So in a sense, policymakers are constantly for the last 20 years, giving me opportunities

00:30:34.680 --> 00:30:37.600
[Guest]: week after week, to be able to say something.

00:30:37.600 --> 00:30:40.480
[Guest]: So which come out of that broader understanding.

00:30:40.480 --> 00:30:43.920
[Guest]: So there's not that much of a conflict, it gives me, you know, little things give me

00:30:43.920 --> 00:30:47.800
[Guest]: opportunities to put my ideas across.

00:30:47.800 --> 00:30:51.320
[Amit Varma]: So when you came back to India after doing your PhD, what was your thinking?

00:30:51.320 --> 00:30:54.240
[Amit Varma]: What was the kind of work that you wanted to do? because one would imagine that for

00:30:54.240 --> 00:31:00.160
[Amit Varma]: many people, a natural progression then is to just become an academic outside somewhere

00:31:00.160 --> 00:31:04.200
[Amit Varma]: and kind of chill and live a charmed life and do papers and all of that.

00:31:04.200 --> 00:31:05.760
[Amit Varma]: But you actually came back.

00:31:05.760 --> 00:31:07.280
[Amit Varma]: So what was your thinking?

00:31:07.280 --> 00:31:08.280
[Amit Varma]: What did you want to do?

00:31:08.280 --> 00:31:10.560
[Amit Varma]: Were you were you kind of clear about the path ahead?

00:31:10.560 --> 00:31:13.040
[Guest]: And is that more or less the path that you've taken?

00:31:13.040 --> 00:31:14.240
[Guest]: Pretty much, pretty much.

00:31:14.240 --> 00:31:20.680
[Guest]: So I wanted not to be teaching because when I was teaching before I left, I was teaching

00:31:20.680 --> 00:31:25.560
[Guest]: at Stephens and it was, you know, it was a heavy workload.

00:31:25.560 --> 00:31:28.600
[Guest]: And one didn't really get time to do research.

00:31:28.600 --> 00:31:33.880
[Guest]: And I wanted to do research after my PhD and not teach because, you know, there they may

00:31:33.880 --> 00:31:36.720
[Guest]: still be an environment where you get a lot of time off.

00:31:36.720 --> 00:31:40.520
[Guest]: But here, at least, you know, it's very difficult.

00:31:40.520 --> 00:31:42.760
[Guest]: So I wanted to work for a think tank.

00:31:42.760 --> 00:31:47.520
[Guest]: And I joined in CAER, National Council of Applied Economic Research.

00:31:47.520 --> 00:31:54.360
[Guest]: And I got to work on the Indian economy, which for me was just what I wanted to do.

00:31:54.360 --> 00:31:58.920
[Guest]: My PhD had been on a closed economy model because when I had left India and all the

00:31:58.920 --> 00:32:01.960
[Guest]: experience one had was closed economy.

00:32:01.960 --> 00:32:04.640
[Guest]: So I'd gone in 91 for my PhD.

00:32:04.640 --> 00:32:07.200
[Guest]: And by 96, it was an open economy.

00:32:07.200 --> 00:32:11.700
[Guest]: So though my PhD was on a closed economy model, it was an endogenous growth model.

00:32:11.700 --> 00:32:20.840
[Guest]: But I had been teaching there in Surrey and then learnt open economy macro while teaching

00:32:20.840 --> 00:32:22.640
[Guest]: because that's what macro teaching there was.

00:32:22.640 --> 00:32:24.280
[Guest]: It was all open economy.

00:32:24.280 --> 00:32:31.040
[Guest]: So here, when I came back, I think it was just the perfect thing for me that, you know,

00:32:31.040 --> 00:32:34.960
[Guest]: nobody else was particularly studying open economy macro for India in 96.

00:32:34.960 --> 00:32:37.200
[Guest]: The economy had barely opened up.

00:32:37.200 --> 00:32:41.240
[Guest]: Very few people had actually even been trained in open economy macro.

00:32:41.240 --> 00:32:43.800
[Guest]: Macro itself had gone out of fashion.

00:32:43.800 --> 00:32:48.120
[Guest]: So, you know, things had been okay in the rest of the world for a while.

00:32:48.120 --> 00:32:54.520
[Guest]: And when Indians went to do PhDs abroad, they did development economics, very few did macro.

00:32:54.520 --> 00:33:02.480
[Guest]: So it was a complete virgin territory, you know, one could do open economy macro, understand

00:33:02.480 --> 00:33:07.280
[Guest]: the Indian economy through the perspective of open economy macro because the economy

00:33:07.280 --> 00:33:09.680
[Guest]: was opening up.

00:33:09.680 --> 00:33:13.560
[Guest]: And almost all the problems that were arising.

00:33:13.560 --> 00:33:21.600
[Guest]: So I had two projects at NCEI, one was on business cycles, and the other was on exchange

00:33:21.600 --> 00:33:23.560
[Guest]: rates and interest rates.

00:33:23.560 --> 00:33:24.560
[Guest]: So financial markets.

00:33:24.560 --> 00:33:31.120
[Guest]: So I was very fortunate to get these two to start working on because this is all three.

00:33:31.120 --> 00:33:36.560
[Guest]: I mean, this is really where all the knowledge of everything that I had studied in open economy

00:33:36.560 --> 00:33:38.860
[Guest]: macro could be applied.

00:33:38.860 --> 00:33:45.760
[Guest]: So I was very fortunate that, you know, I was tooled up, I understood the impossible

00:33:45.760 --> 00:33:50.680
[Guest]: trinity, which many people here still hadn't even started reading.

00:33:50.680 --> 00:33:58.600
[Guest]: And I was able to apply those and study, you know, the Indian economy from a new perspective.

00:33:58.600 --> 00:34:01.000
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a bit more about this impossible trinity.

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:04.560
[Guest]: See, when you're in closed economy, what does a closed economy mean?

00:34:04.560 --> 00:34:10.360
[Guest]: You trade, but you don't have capital account openness, you don't allow capital flows.

00:34:10.360 --> 00:34:11.960
[Guest]: What are capital flows?

00:34:11.960 --> 00:34:17.120
[Guest]: Cross-border flows of money for sale or purchase of assets.

00:34:17.120 --> 00:34:19.320
[Guest]: So you don't allow those, you allow trade.

00:34:19.320 --> 00:34:20.320
[Guest]: That's the current account.

00:34:20.320 --> 00:34:21.960
[Guest]: Your current account is open.

00:34:21.960 --> 00:34:27.280
[Guest]: Then what you can do is that you can hike your interest rates as much as you like.

00:34:27.280 --> 00:34:32.440
[Guest]: And money may come in, money could have come in if it had been an open economy.

00:34:32.440 --> 00:34:35.160
[Guest]: But because you're closed, nothing happens.

00:34:35.160 --> 00:34:41.120
[Guest]: You can fix your exchange rate, you can fix your interest rate, so you can have both.

00:34:41.120 --> 00:34:45.400
[Guest]: Not that the economy had too many business cycles, they just had monsoon cycles before

00:34:45.400 --> 00:34:46.400
[Guest]: 91.

00:34:46.400 --> 00:34:51.560
[Guest]: But if you needed to hike interest rates for any reason or lower interest rates for any

00:34:51.560 --> 00:34:57.640
[Guest]: reason, you don't have to worry about the effect that that will have on exchange rates.

00:34:57.640 --> 00:35:02.800
[Guest]: But now if the economy becomes open, then capital can flow in.

00:35:02.800 --> 00:35:08.240
[Guest]: Let's say if interest rates go up in India and capital flows in, then that's going to

00:35:08.240 --> 00:35:10.840
[Guest]: appreciate your exchange rate.

00:35:10.840 --> 00:35:14.000
[Guest]: If capital flows out, that is going to weaken your currency.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:19.400
[Guest]: Now the impossible trinity says that these are the three corners of the trinity, an open

00:35:19.400 --> 00:35:24.440
[Guest]: capital account, monetary policy independence, that is you determine what your interest rate

00:35:24.440 --> 00:35:27.240
[Guest]: is going to be, and exchange rate policy.

00:35:27.240 --> 00:35:30.960
[Guest]: So you cannot have all three at the same time.

00:35:30.960 --> 00:35:34.840
[Guest]: If you close the capital account, then yes, you can have the other two.

00:35:34.840 --> 00:35:38.640
[Guest]: But once the capital account opens, then you can't have those two.

00:35:38.640 --> 00:35:41.640
[Guest]: So that's the trinity.

00:35:41.640 --> 00:35:45.400
[Amit Varma]: And among sort of economic policy makers in the country, you would imagine that they've

00:35:45.400 --> 00:35:49.880
[Amit Varma]: been used to decades of thinking about the economy in a particular way, which is threat

00:35:49.880 --> 00:35:53.160
[Amit Varma]: hold, command and control, closed economy, blah, blah, blah.

00:35:53.160 --> 00:35:58.360
[Amit Varma]: Now, through circumstances or whatever, you know, the balance of payments crisis and blah,

00:35:58.360 --> 00:36:00.200
[Amit Varma]: blah, we've actually opened it up.

00:36:00.200 --> 00:36:03.120
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, a few people have made some reforms.

00:36:03.120 --> 00:36:05.880
[Amit Varma]: But does the mindset shift over time?

00:36:05.880 --> 00:36:10.920
[Amit Varma]: Like, one of the things that I think about is that yes, 91 is seminal in the sense that

00:36:10.920 --> 00:36:15.560
[Amit Varma]: we opened so much up, but at the same time, you know, it's it's very partial in terms

00:36:15.560 --> 00:36:17.120
[Amit Varma]: of what we could have done.

00:36:17.120 --> 00:36:22.160
[Amit Varma]: And also what I can't put my finger on is that is there a mindset shift at all?

00:36:22.160 --> 00:36:27.400
[Amit Varma]: Because after that initial impetus, it seems to me that inertia sets in again.

00:36:27.400 --> 00:36:30.560
[Amit Varma]: And further reforms, you know, sort of slow down.

00:36:30.560 --> 00:36:35.440
[Amit Varma]: So in just in terms of the mindset, both within the government and within economists who are

00:36:35.440 --> 00:36:40.520
[Amit Varma]: working here, what is you know, how are how are they adapting?

00:36:40.520 --> 00:36:44.860
[Amit Varma]: You know, how are they noticing like you pointed out that how it's a delightful time to study

00:36:44.860 --> 00:36:50.520
[Amit Varma]: economics because it's almost like these experiments where you had a control and then the control

00:36:50.520 --> 00:36:55.040
[Amit Varma]: gets removed and you can see exactly what the consequences and there are so many insights

00:36:55.040 --> 00:36:57.560
[Amit Varma]: because there are so many things changing.

00:36:57.560 --> 00:37:01.840
[Amit Varma]: But you know, you're a young person who is forming at that moment in time, I would imagine

00:37:01.840 --> 00:37:06.640
[Amit Varma]: that everyone who is a major economic commentator at the time or is in government there in the

00:37:06.640 --> 00:37:12.800
[Amit Varma]: 40s and 50s, settled ways of thinking, is that an issue when you are in this landscape,

00:37:12.800 --> 00:37:16.400
[Amit Varma]: looking around studying these things that really no one in India is studying because

00:37:16.400 --> 00:37:21.960
[Amit Varma]: like you said, they're doing development economics and, you know, hunger and nutrition and redistribution

00:37:21.960 --> 00:37:22.960
[Amit Varma]: and all that.

00:37:22.960 --> 00:37:26.960
[Amit Varma]: What is it like, you know, are you someone who kind of stands apart?

00:37:26.960 --> 00:37:30.840
[Guest]: Yeah, very lonely, I would say very difficult and very lonely.

00:37:30.840 --> 00:37:41.920
[Guest]: So if I give you a concrete example, when we opened up in 91, after opening up the current

00:37:41.920 --> 00:37:47.760
[Guest]: account in about 93-94, we started opening the capital account and we started getting

00:37:47.760 --> 00:37:55.560
[Guest]: a lot of FII investment and that meant that the rupee started appreciating and RBI started

00:37:55.560 --> 00:38:01.400
[Guest]: buying dollars, they didn't, they just bought dollars, unsterilized, I mean, they just bought

00:38:01.400 --> 00:38:02.400
[Guest]: dollars.

00:38:02.400 --> 00:38:06.940
[Guest]: So the money supply in the economy increased and they started getting inflation.

00:38:06.940 --> 00:38:13.320
[Guest]: So by mid-96 or so, we started getting a lot of inflationary pressures.

00:38:13.320 --> 00:38:21.200
[Guest]: But the mindset was that this has nothing to do with opening up or should we allow exchange

00:38:21.200 --> 00:38:25.200
[Guest]: rate flexibility, should we not try to fix the exchange rate.

00:38:25.200 --> 00:38:31.920
[Guest]: You know, the exchange rate stayed at 31.36 for 16 months after we made it flexible.

00:38:31.920 --> 00:38:40.360
[Guest]: So we said now the exchange rate is no longer administered and we are moving to a floating

00:38:40.360 --> 00:38:44.040
[Guest]: managed float, but it stayed at 31.36.

00:38:44.040 --> 00:38:49.880
[Guest]: Now in those 16 months, RBI was busy buying up dollars and because they had understood

00:38:49.880 --> 00:38:51.960
[Guest]: so little, they were not sterilizing them.

00:38:51.960 --> 00:38:57.560
[Guest]: So back to back, in other words, in our audience, we're not used to the word sterilized intervention

00:38:57.560 --> 00:38:58.560
[Guest]: by the central bank.

00:38:58.560 --> 00:39:04.080
[Guest]: It basically means that you buy foreign currency and so in your monetary base, you're adding

00:39:04.080 --> 00:39:09.080
[Guest]: to your monetary base by buying foreign currency because for every rupee you buy, you've issued,

00:39:09.080 --> 00:39:14.000
[Guest]: sorry, for every dollar you buy, you've issued a number of rupees.

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:17.800
[Guest]: If you sterilize it, which means that if you're worrying about the impact it's going to have

00:39:17.800 --> 00:39:25.320
[Guest]: on the monetary base, then you sell government bonds and you pull that money back so that

00:39:25.320 --> 00:39:30.760
[Guest]: you don't let liquidity in the economy increase.

00:39:30.760 --> 00:39:33.440
[Guest]: You know, it was early days, they also had no experience.

00:39:33.440 --> 00:39:39.960
[Guest]: So they did unsterilized intervention and there was just very little understanding of

00:39:39.960 --> 00:39:41.400
[Guest]: what was going on.

00:39:41.400 --> 00:39:46.760
[Guest]: And then they started talking about that we are building reserves, that we're doing this

00:39:46.760 --> 00:39:49.140
[Guest]: because we are building reserves.

00:39:49.140 --> 00:39:51.360
[Guest]: It sounded very good to everybody in government.

00:39:51.360 --> 00:39:52.360
[Guest]: Why?

00:39:52.360 --> 00:39:57.720
[Guest]: Because in this 91 crisis where, you know, that whole story, I'm sure everybody has heard

00:39:57.720 --> 00:40:02.960
[Guest]: it a thousand times, but the story that India mortgaged a plane full of gold and we went

00:40:02.960 --> 00:40:07.200
[Guest]: with a begging bowl when we didn't have even 15 days worth of imports left, that story

00:40:07.200 --> 00:40:08.920
[Guest]: would be told again and again.

00:40:08.920 --> 00:40:13.240
[Guest]: And it would be said that, oh, so we are just, you know, we want to be safe, so we are buying

00:40:13.240 --> 00:40:14.240
[Guest]: reserves.

00:40:14.240 --> 00:40:19.920
[Guest]: People would justify holding those reserves by saying, oh, there is this in month rule,

00:40:19.920 --> 00:40:25.360
[Guest]: in month of import cover, there's this guidotti rule that we should have be holding so much

00:40:25.360 --> 00:40:30.560
[Guest]: of reserves or we, you know, there's so much hot money in, so we should be holding reserves

00:40:30.560 --> 00:40:31.760
[Guest]: for that.

00:40:31.760 --> 00:40:35.960
[Guest]: But essentially what was happening was that they were buying reserves to manipulate the

00:40:35.960 --> 00:40:36.960
[Guest]: rupee.

00:40:36.960 --> 00:40:40.040
[Guest]: They were just buying dollars because we are getting too much of an inflow of dollars.

00:40:40.040 --> 00:40:42.680
[Guest]: And this kind of continued for a while.

00:40:42.680 --> 00:40:48.960
[Guest]: And it was not that there was any great understanding of what is reserve adequacy and how much reserves

00:40:48.960 --> 00:40:50.120
[Guest]: would be held.

00:40:50.120 --> 00:40:54.440
[Guest]: So if one said that, look, this is an embarrassment of riches.

00:40:54.440 --> 00:40:59.600
[Guest]: I mean, I remember the phrase because I had a business standard column and, you know,

00:40:59.600 --> 00:41:04.200
[Guest]: the editor had very nicely found this nice, you know, that the titles are given by the

00:41:04.200 --> 00:41:05.200
[Guest]: page editor.

00:41:05.200 --> 00:41:07.920
[Guest]: So it was the embarrassment of riches.

00:41:07.920 --> 00:41:11.920
[Guest]: And you know, when one tried to say that, look, you don't need these, you're holding

00:41:11.920 --> 00:41:12.920
[Guest]: too much.

00:41:12.920 --> 00:41:18.920
[Guest]: I remember this was came up in a Nimrana conference, my first Nimrana conference where I said,

00:41:18.920 --> 00:41:21.800
[Guest]: look, this is becoming like Food Corporation of India.

00:41:21.800 --> 00:41:26.680
[Guest]: You know, you're just buying up something because it's there and then you won't be able

00:41:26.680 --> 00:41:27.680
[Guest]: to get rid of it.

00:41:27.680 --> 00:41:34.560
[Guest]: You try selling your reserves like you try to sell your wheat and your prices will drop.

00:41:34.560 --> 00:41:39.800
[Guest]: So what we are doing is not thought through policy.

00:41:39.800 --> 00:41:45.460
[Guest]: But you know, of course, people became very unhappy, particularly the RBI.

00:41:45.460 --> 00:41:52.400
[Guest]: So Dr. Rakesh Mohan used to be my boss at NCIR, he was the director general.

00:41:52.400 --> 00:41:53.880
[Guest]: And so I knew him very well.

00:41:53.880 --> 00:42:00.200
[Guest]: And so he would tell me that, oh, you know, every Wednesday, we read what Hazira said

00:42:00.200 --> 00:42:01.200
[Guest]: now.

00:42:01.200 --> 00:42:05.280
[Guest]: So they were not happy.

00:42:05.280 --> 00:42:09.320
[Amit Varma]: Because the RBI is going to come calling and they're going to, what was the pushback like

00:42:09.320 --> 00:42:10.320
[Amit Varma]: in those days?

00:42:10.320 --> 00:42:11.800
[Amit Varma]: Like, what were the other big battles?

00:42:11.800 --> 00:42:16.240
[Amit Varma]: One, of course, is this, as you pointed out with the RBI regarding inflation and so on.

00:42:16.240 --> 00:42:18.160
[Amit Varma]: But what were your through the years?

00:42:18.160 --> 00:42:21.960
[Amit Varma]: What were your other kind of, you know, big battles like in terms of mindset and did that

00:42:21.960 --> 00:42:23.560
[Amit Varma]: mindset ever begin to change?

00:42:23.560 --> 00:42:28.320
[Guest]: There are many more people today who agree on many of these issues.

00:42:28.320 --> 00:42:34.360
[Guest]: So among the other battles, one, for example, has been a later one, but one has been the

00:42:34.360 --> 00:42:37.240
[Guest]: Debt Management Office that we needed bond market.

00:42:37.240 --> 00:42:38.240
[Guest]: India needs a bond market.

00:42:38.240 --> 00:42:45.400
[Guest]: I mean, I thought that's something that everybody would very easily agree with that.

00:42:45.400 --> 00:42:47.720
[Guest]: I'm saying we need a bond market.

00:42:47.720 --> 00:42:50.520
[Guest]: I'm not saying we need a corporate bond market.

00:42:50.520 --> 00:42:51.520
[Guest]: OK.

00:42:51.520 --> 00:42:56.720
[Guest]: Now, to me, it seems obvious that if the government bond market and the corporate bond market

00:42:56.720 --> 00:43:01.600
[Guest]: are two different markets, you don't have liquidity, you don't have the players.

00:43:01.600 --> 00:43:06.640
[Guest]: But you'll see a lot of people talk about a corporate bond market.

00:43:06.640 --> 00:43:11.240
[Guest]: But when it comes to having a bond market, then because, you know, there's this issue

00:43:11.240 --> 00:43:15.320
[Guest]: of RBI is the regulator in the government bond market.

00:43:15.320 --> 00:43:16.440
[Guest]: So there's a lot of pushback.

00:43:16.440 --> 00:43:18.560
[Guest]: RBI is not just the regulator.

00:43:18.560 --> 00:43:23.480
[Guest]: They own the depository, they own the exchange, and, you know, they are themselves trading

00:43:23.480 --> 00:43:28.240
[Guest]: on that market and they are issuing securities for the government.

00:43:28.240 --> 00:43:31.360
[Guest]: So there is a lot of pushback on some of these.

00:43:31.360 --> 00:43:36.760
[Guest]: And I think a lot of that pushback is because of the fact that people don't like to see

00:43:36.760 --> 00:43:37.760
[Guest]: change.

00:43:37.760 --> 00:43:40.960
[Amit Varma]: They're kind of stuck in the inertia and their ways of thinking.

00:43:40.960 --> 00:43:45.520
[Amit Varma]: I'm trying to, you know, one question I've kind of had, and I know it's complicated.

00:43:45.520 --> 00:43:48.560
[Amit Varma]: What has been our direction since 91, since today?

00:43:48.560 --> 00:43:50.240
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, there's not one answer to that.

00:43:50.240 --> 00:43:55.480
[Amit Varma]: And even within the question, I mean it in multiple ways, like what is there a directionality

00:43:55.480 --> 00:43:58.140
[Amit Varma]: when we can talk about mindsets?

00:43:58.140 --> 00:44:03.160
[Amit Varma]: And this would involve like mindsets in government, this would involve mindsets, you know, in

00:44:03.160 --> 00:44:05.280
[Amit Varma]: the general discourse outside.

00:44:05.280 --> 00:44:08.520
[Amit Varma]: Because one of the things that seems to me is that, okay, we made some reforms, which

00:44:08.520 --> 00:44:10.940
[Amit Varma]: we had to in 91, and those happened.

00:44:10.940 --> 00:44:12.640
[Amit Varma]: And after that, everything was sporadic.

00:44:12.640 --> 00:44:17.360
[Amit Varma]: There were moments where there were impulses towards reform, where individuals kind of

00:44:17.360 --> 00:44:18.860
[Amit Varma]: tried to do things.

00:44:18.860 --> 00:44:24.120
[Amit Varma]: But in general, inertia set in again, and our default thinking has remained that the

00:44:24.120 --> 00:44:27.200
[Amit Varma]: thinking that the state has to have control of everything.

00:44:27.200 --> 00:44:32.240
[Amit Varma]: And you've kind of straddled this entire landscape, right, both as someone who's been in policy,

00:44:32.240 --> 00:44:35.720
[Amit Varma]: studying economics, and as a public intellectual of sorts.

00:44:35.720 --> 00:44:38.920
[Amit Varma]: So you know, what has that movement been like?

00:44:38.920 --> 00:44:42.080
[Amit Varma]: Has it been one step forward, one step backward?

00:44:42.080 --> 00:44:44.080
[Amit Varma]: Give me a sense of it.

00:44:44.080 --> 00:44:48.300
[Guest]: I think it's been a very difficult journey for reforms.

00:44:48.300 --> 00:44:54.960
[Guest]: So if I'm a reform set out on a journey, then I'm not gathering too much moss.

00:44:54.960 --> 00:44:58.920
[Guest]: There aren't too many people who are moving with me.

00:44:58.920 --> 00:45:03.800
[Guest]: Again, you know, I think there are tough wars, there are vested interests.

00:45:03.800 --> 00:45:05.520
[Guest]: So that is what holds back.

00:45:05.520 --> 00:45:11.640
[Guest]: So it's not so much that people don't understand, I think that there are vested interests, and

00:45:11.640 --> 00:45:14.480
[Guest]: then people pull back on reforms.

00:45:14.480 --> 00:45:19.600
[Guest]: So I mean, giving you this example that I was just giving about the bond market.

00:45:19.600 --> 00:45:25.240
[Guest]: So what we were trying to do for a long time, for a very long time, I mean, RBI had also

00:45:25.240 --> 00:45:31.040
[Guest]: proposed it, government was trying for a very long time is to set up an independent debt

00:45:31.040 --> 00:45:36.800
[Guest]: management office, so that that would, you know, that usually when we look around, then

00:45:36.800 --> 00:45:39.400
[Guest]: countries have done that.

00:45:39.400 --> 00:45:42.000
[Guest]: Most countries, not every country, but most countries have done that.

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:44.680
[Guest]: And that really helps in building your bond market.

00:45:44.680 --> 00:45:49.640
[Guest]: And, you know, so if you look, I'm just giving you this example, because I'm more familiar

00:45:49.640 --> 00:45:54.360
[Guest]: with the reforms in the financial sector than in any other space.

00:45:54.360 --> 00:45:56.960
[Guest]: So what happened?

00:45:56.960 --> 00:46:04.880
[Guest]: Finance Minister Jaitley, even he tabled the bill in Parliament, there's so much pushback.

00:46:04.880 --> 00:46:11.720
[Guest]: And then, because politicians also have, I guess, limited capital, political capital,

00:46:11.720 --> 00:46:16.560
[Guest]: that they don't want to use it on something that is not going to give them immediate returns.

00:46:16.560 --> 00:46:19.080
[Guest]: The bill was withdrawn.

00:46:19.080 --> 00:46:28.200
[Guest]: And you know, after years of pushing this, finally having it tabled in Parliament, and

00:46:28.200 --> 00:46:35.440
[Guest]: then, you know, when the budget was to be, this is the 2015 budget, when the budget was

00:46:35.440 --> 00:46:39.560
[Guest]: to be voted upon, that day, the finance minister rolled it back.

00:46:39.560 --> 00:46:44.600
[Guest]: And this was a reform that the country needed, that the country still needs.

00:46:44.600 --> 00:46:47.800
[Guest]: But you know, it's not on the table anymore.

00:46:47.800 --> 00:46:49.760
[Guest]: Many things don't even come to the table.

00:46:49.760 --> 00:46:51.920
[Guest]: At least this was a bill that had been tabled.

00:46:51.920 --> 00:46:53.320
[Guest]: But many things don't come to the table.

00:46:53.320 --> 00:46:59.320
[Guest]: There are others like the FRDI bill, the Financial Resolution and Deposit Insurance bill that

00:46:59.320 --> 00:47:01.480
[Guest]: went to Standing Committee.

00:47:01.480 --> 00:47:07.040
[Guest]: There was a lot of pushback from, you know, public sector banks who said, oh, this means

00:47:07.040 --> 00:47:10.880
[Guest]: that all these banks will be taken over, and all kinds of rumors were floated about the

00:47:10.880 --> 00:47:15.480
[Guest]: Bill in Clause, about the amount of deposit insurance, all kinds of things which were

00:47:15.480 --> 00:47:16.720
[Guest]: completely incorrect.

00:47:16.720 --> 00:47:20.160
[Guest]: But that led to the bill being withdrawn.

00:47:20.160 --> 00:47:26.320
[Guest]: So pushbacks happen, I think, not just because of the mindset.

00:47:26.320 --> 00:47:31.440
[Guest]: Of course, I completely agree with you, as I was saying that there is a mindset issue

00:47:31.440 --> 00:47:32.720
[Guest]: as well.

00:47:32.720 --> 00:47:44.320
[Guest]: But that mindset is actually used, used in the sense of taken, made you, you know, misused

00:47:44.320 --> 00:47:50.080
[Guest]: by those who have vested interests, and they managed to push back.

00:47:50.080 --> 00:47:53.000
[Guest]: And that's why I think a lot of things don't happen.

00:47:53.000 --> 00:47:59.280
[Guest]: Many things have been stuck at very early stages for years, but they don't go through.

00:47:59.280 --> 00:48:03.080
[Amit Varma]: So I have a couple of bigger questions I want to get to from here.

00:48:03.080 --> 00:48:07.440
[Amit Varma]: And the first one has a smaller question before it, in fact, which is sort of the definition

00:48:07.440 --> 00:48:08.440
[Amit Varma]: of reforms.

00:48:08.440 --> 00:48:13.640
[Amit Varma]: Like, if we are to define reforms, it seems to me that most reforms would go in one fundamental

00:48:13.640 --> 00:48:19.320
[Amit Varma]: direction, which is that our state has been too top heavy, it's been too oppressive.

00:48:19.320 --> 00:48:23.400
[Amit Varma]: And many reforms are just getting out of the way, letting society solve its own problems,

00:48:23.400 --> 00:48:24.960
[Amit Varma]: letting markets work and all of that.

00:48:24.960 --> 00:48:27.920
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of the 91 reforms were exactly about this.

00:48:27.920 --> 00:48:32.800
[Amit Varma]: Now, this leads me to the first of my questions, which is that if one of the things that reforms

00:48:32.800 --> 00:48:39.320
[Amit Varma]: are supposed to do is reduce the power of the state, and you know, empower common people,

00:48:39.320 --> 00:48:43.880
[Amit Varma]: then given that the state is supposed to make these reforms, doesn't it make reforms in

00:48:43.880 --> 00:48:47.180
[Amit Varma]: a sense impossible that there is always going to be pushback.

00:48:47.180 --> 00:48:53.360
[Amit Varma]: And unless you have, say, a transformative moment of crisis like 1991, that reforms are

00:48:53.360 --> 00:48:58.660
[Amit Varma]: just going to be very unusual, because they go against all incentives of anyone in a position

00:48:58.660 --> 00:48:59.660
[Amit Varma]: of power.

00:48:59.660 --> 00:49:03.840
[Amit Varma]: I mean, of course, the mindset issue is one issue that, you know, most of them will believe

00:49:03.840 --> 00:49:07.760
[Amit Varma]: by conviction that this is the right way that the state should control everything.

00:49:07.760 --> 00:49:12.880
[Amit Varma]: But even if that were not the case, you know, when is the state ever going to give up power?

00:49:12.880 --> 00:49:16.560
[Amit Varma]: So is that something that you kind of think about?

00:49:16.560 --> 00:49:18.800
[Guest]: Yeah, I think, yeah, yeah.

00:49:18.800 --> 00:49:24.520
[Guest]: But you know, I think that sometimes what happens is that the politician can see five

00:49:24.520 --> 00:49:30.400
[Guest]: years ahead, whereas the bureaucrat is seeing maybe the next six months until his retirement,

00:49:30.400 --> 00:49:33.100
[Guest]: and he's being risk averse and not doing anything.

00:49:33.100 --> 00:49:40.480
[Guest]: But the politician can see a little bit further ahead, he does have to win elections again.

00:49:40.480 --> 00:49:46.460
[Guest]: And you know, parties can see not just five years ahead, but even further, because they

00:49:46.460 --> 00:49:48.380
[Guest]: have to grow and stay.

00:49:48.380 --> 00:49:53.440
[Guest]: So I'm not saying that they all understand what is to be done, there is often lack of

00:49:53.440 --> 00:49:57.920
[Guest]: understanding and, you know, expertise and in-depth knowledge.

00:49:57.920 --> 00:50:03.520
[Guest]: But if there are things that need to be done, which they feel that people will not oppose,

00:50:03.520 --> 00:50:06.880
[Guest]: then those do get pushed through now the farm bills, okay.

00:50:06.880 --> 00:50:15.400
[Guest]: Now that was, I mean, we talk about the 91 reforms, but if you think about what were

00:50:15.400 --> 00:50:21.880
[Guest]: the reforms, they were just industry and trade, you left agriculture out, you left the bulk

00:50:21.880 --> 00:50:24.560
[Guest]: of the financial sector out, okay.

00:50:24.560 --> 00:50:31.040
[Guest]: So when you start doing farm bills or the reforms to liberalize financial, sorry, agricultural

00:50:31.040 --> 00:50:38.000
[Guest]: markets, which should have been done in 91, when you try to do them now, you saw the pushback.

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:43.440
[Guest]: And I think that that will reduce the ability of any government to go further.

00:50:43.440 --> 00:50:49.040
[Guest]: But it is not that nothing was tried and it would not have given immediate benefits.

00:50:49.040 --> 00:50:54.280
[Guest]: It would have liberalized agricultural markets in a manner that they should have been liberalized.

00:50:54.280 --> 00:50:59.800
[Guest]: So, you know, I think while people say that being a democracy means that you don't do

00:50:59.800 --> 00:51:03.800
[Guest]: reform because you do populist things and you only look at the short term.

00:51:03.800 --> 00:51:09.280
[Guest]: But I think that sometimes you do reforms because you are also answerable to the people

00:51:09.280 --> 00:51:11.000
[Guest]: who you're going to go back to five years later.

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:14.760
[Guest]: So you want to have something to show to the people.

00:51:14.760 --> 00:51:18.640
[Guest]: And if there is not much opposition, then you will do those.

00:51:18.640 --> 00:51:20.960
[Amit Varma]: No, I agree with that.

00:51:20.960 --> 00:51:24.040
[Amit Varma]: But I also disagree with the part of it like you spoke about, you know, the bureaucrats

00:51:24.040 --> 00:51:27.480
[Amit Varma]: having a six month window and the politicians having a longer term view.

00:51:27.480 --> 00:51:33.760
[Amit Varma]: But I think one of the things that gets in the way of reforms also is that politicians

00:51:33.760 --> 00:51:38.560
[Amit Varma]: have relatively short election cycles in terms of the next election is not always just five

00:51:38.560 --> 00:51:39.560
[Amit Varma]: years away.

00:51:39.560 --> 00:51:41.120
[Amit Varma]: There are elections happening somewhere or the other.

00:51:41.120 --> 00:51:45.040
[Amit Varma]: So if you're thinking at the national level, you're thinking, oh, Bengal elections is next

00:51:45.040 --> 00:51:46.880
[Amit Varma]: or UP elections is next year.

00:51:46.880 --> 00:51:48.840
[Amit Varma]: So you are kind of short termist.

00:51:48.840 --> 00:51:54.120
[Amit Varma]: And also your, you know, your bound is how people perceive what you are doing.

00:51:54.120 --> 00:51:59.040
[Amit Varma]: For example, a farm loan waiver, which almost became the rigor for every party to promise

00:51:59.040 --> 00:52:04.000
[Amit Varma]: before every polls, a farm loan waiver, which is, you know, just a short term anesthetic

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:10.280
[Amit Varma]: will always have more takers than deeper structural solutions to whatever the problem may be.

00:52:10.280 --> 00:52:15.760
[Amit Varma]: And also parties may kind of bind themselves into a corner with, say, the kind of nationalistic

00:52:15.760 --> 00:52:20.880
[Amit Varma]: rhetoric that we see from this party sometimes where you talk of Atma Nirbharta and so on.

00:52:20.880 --> 00:52:23.280
[Amit Varma]: And those can also lead to bad economics.

00:52:23.280 --> 00:52:25.640
[Amit Varma]: In fact, good politics can often lead to bad economics.

00:52:25.640 --> 00:52:29.080
[Amit Varma]: I've done an episode with Pooja Mehra on her book, The Lost Decade.

00:52:29.080 --> 00:52:33.920
[Amit Varma]: And she pointed out that how, you know, some of the impetus behind why Modi abandoned reforms

00:52:33.920 --> 00:52:37.040
[Amit Varma]: came after he was accused of being Sood Bhut ki Sarkar.

00:52:37.040 --> 00:52:40.760
[Amit Varma]: And then he went all populist and, you know, reforms just stalled.

00:52:40.760 --> 00:52:45.720
[Amit Varma]: And then the disastrous demonetization also came about his perception of what would play

00:52:45.720 --> 00:52:47.040
[Amit Varma]: well with the common people.

00:52:47.040 --> 00:52:51.640
[Amit Varma]: And maybe he was right because it did play well, even though it was, of course, a horrendous

00:52:51.640 --> 00:52:52.760
[Amit Varma]: misstep.

00:52:52.760 --> 00:52:56.480
[Amit Varma]: And what we see here, like I did an episode with our mutual friend Ajay Shah on the farm

00:52:56.480 --> 00:53:01.160
[Amit Varma]: bills, where we kind of discussed about how the economic thrust of it is was great.

00:53:01.160 --> 00:53:04.960
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, the ruling party completely messed up the politics of it and didn't go

00:53:04.960 --> 00:53:07.760
[Amit Varma]: about it the way that it should have.

00:53:07.760 --> 00:53:13.980
[Amit Varma]: And here also we see an example of where, you know, even like if you're trying to push

00:53:13.980 --> 00:53:18.640
[Amit Varma]: through a measure which you know will be good in the long run, but in the short run might

00:53:18.640 --> 00:53:22.400
[Amit Varma]: hurt people with vested interests or might hurt people in other ways.

00:53:22.400 --> 00:53:23.880
[Amit Varma]: They are, of course, going to fight back.

00:53:23.880 --> 00:53:28.640
[Amit Varma]: And our politics is so polarized that then that can paralyze all movement, as seems to

00:53:28.640 --> 00:53:30.920
[Amit Varma]: have happened in the case of the farm bills.

00:53:30.920 --> 00:53:35.280
[Amit Varma]: So this relationship between politics and economics, how do you see it?

00:53:35.280 --> 00:53:39.840
[Amit Varma]: Because it seems to me to be more an adversarial one than otherwise that good politics will

00:53:39.840 --> 00:53:43.800
[Amit Varma]: generally make for bad economics and vice versa, because, of course, the incentive of

00:53:43.800 --> 00:53:46.560
[Amit Varma]: the politician is to provide good governance.

00:53:46.560 --> 00:53:51.200
[Amit Varma]: But number one, that governance is more something that he or she wants to be visible in the

00:53:51.200 --> 00:53:52.320
[Amit Varma]: short term.

00:53:52.320 --> 00:53:55.880
[Amit Varma]: And they are more keen on narratives rather than actual governance on the ground, as we've

00:53:55.880 --> 00:53:56.880
[Amit Varma]: seen.

00:53:56.880 --> 00:54:05.800
[Guest]: So if I look back at the NDA 1 versus, say, the UPA 1 and 2, then what you're saying would

00:54:05.800 --> 00:54:10.720
[Guest]: imply that it doesn't matter, you know, there would have been no difference in the economic

00:54:10.720 --> 00:54:15.960
[Guest]: policies or, you know, the previous Congress regimes after that, OK?

00:54:15.960 --> 00:54:23.940
[Guest]: But when I actually look at what kind of reforms were done in NDA 1, they were much more than

00:54:23.940 --> 00:54:30.360
[Guest]: what was done in the previous five years or the later five years, and bringing the private

00:54:30.360 --> 00:54:37.080
[Guest]: sector in for infrastructure, because there were shortages of, you know, capital or liberalizing

00:54:37.080 --> 00:54:42.200
[Guest]: capital account opening, allowing Indian companies to go abroad, which, you know, ultimately

00:54:42.200 --> 00:54:46.720
[Guest]: they became bigger multinationals, brought in technology, many, many, many, many, there's

00:54:46.720 --> 00:54:50.660
[Guest]: a large number of pension reforms, OK?

00:54:50.660 --> 00:54:56.560
[Guest]: So going from a defined benefit to a defined contribution system and a list of many things.

00:54:56.560 --> 00:55:02.560
[Guest]: Now, many of those things were fundamentally a belief in markets, a belief in the private

00:55:02.560 --> 00:55:08.400
[Guest]: sector, which we did not see in the Congress regimes.

00:55:08.400 --> 00:55:12.880
[Guest]: So my sense is that it does matter.

00:55:12.880 --> 00:55:15.240
[Guest]: Of course, all parties have to win elections.

00:55:15.240 --> 00:55:19.360
[Guest]: Of course, all parties have their own, you know, machinery to take care of, individuals

00:55:19.360 --> 00:55:22.140
[Guest]: to take care of, whatever, whatever, and so on.

00:55:22.140 --> 00:55:30.280
[Guest]: But if there are opportunities, then we do see some not going towards markets.

00:55:30.280 --> 00:55:36.720
[Guest]: So instead, when UPA comes back, when you see Manrega, you see a lot of welfare programs.

00:55:36.720 --> 00:55:44.280
[Guest]: I mean, the state pretty much moves towards bankruptcy in that space, where before growing

00:55:44.280 --> 00:55:51.600
[Guest]: rich, you have started doing a lot of redistribution, which then, of course, means that you have

00:55:51.600 --> 00:56:01.080
[Amit Varma]: less money for, you know, the roads that I was fighting about, when you were 19.

00:56:01.080 --> 00:56:06.760
[Guest]: So I do think that it matters that the party, you know, has a certain thinking.

00:56:06.760 --> 00:56:11.240
[Guest]: And so there are tactics and then there are things which, OK, if you get an opportunity,

00:56:11.240 --> 00:56:12.240
[Guest]: let's do this.

00:56:12.240 --> 00:56:16.960
[Guest]: But it is a reform, and it is a reform that actually is a pro-market reform.

00:56:16.960 --> 00:56:23.120
[Guest]: And I'm not denying that politicians or bureaucrats want to have power.

00:56:23.120 --> 00:56:24.720
[Guest]: That's how the system till today.

00:56:24.720 --> 00:56:27.240
[Guest]: It's not that we don't have state intervention today.

00:56:27.240 --> 00:56:29.520
[Guest]: We have huge amounts of state intervention today.

00:56:29.520 --> 00:56:34.160
[Guest]: But I'm just saying that maybe, you know, you're a little younger, so you're not seeing

00:56:34.160 --> 00:56:37.400
[Guest]: this in these five-year chunks.

00:56:37.400 --> 00:56:44.720
[Guest]: But if you, sorry, if you look at NDA 1, and I look back, and I see there's quite a lot

00:56:44.720 --> 00:56:48.920
[Guest]: that was done, which was pro-market reforms, which was economic reforms.

00:56:48.920 --> 00:56:49.920
[Amit Varma]: That's true.

00:56:49.920 --> 00:56:51.040
[Amit Varma]: So I have a couple of follow-up questions.

00:56:51.040 --> 00:56:55.920
[Amit Varma]: And one of them actually, you know, you stated it as buttressing my point, but I think it

00:56:55.920 --> 00:56:59.480
[Amit Varma]: actually in a way it might buttress my point, which is that you spoke about the reforms

00:56:59.480 --> 00:57:00.480
[Amit Varma]: NDA 1 did.

00:57:00.480 --> 00:57:04.000
[Amit Varma]: And I agree that I think, you know, some of the stuff they did was terrific.

00:57:04.000 --> 00:57:08.400
[Amit Varma]: But first of all, would you agree that the benefits of that actually showed up in the

00:57:08.400 --> 00:57:10.400
[Amit Varma]: figures of the UPA?

00:57:10.400 --> 00:57:14.320
[Amit Varma]: Like people will today say that, oh, in the 10 years of the UPA, we grew this much.

00:57:14.320 --> 00:57:17.440
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, and I go nuts trying to say that, hey, this was because of the reforms

00:57:17.440 --> 00:57:19.140
[Amit Varma]: of Vajpayee put into place.

00:57:19.140 --> 00:57:23.760
[Amit Varma]: And then that would seem to state that if Vajpayee in retrospect was to, you know, sit

00:57:23.760 --> 00:57:27.400
[Amit Varma]: there, he would say that, look, I can do these, but I might lose the elections, and then the

00:57:27.400 --> 00:57:28.940
[Amit Varma]: next guy will take all the credit.

00:57:28.940 --> 00:57:30.560
[Amit Varma]: So why should I think so far ahead?

00:57:30.560 --> 00:57:32.680
[Amit Varma]: So that's kind of the first of my follow-ups.

00:57:32.680 --> 00:57:35.080
[Guest]: Yeah, that's a very good question.

00:57:35.080 --> 00:57:42.080
[Guest]: You see, so look at when NDA 1 lost, it was mainly attributed to the India Shining campaign,

00:57:42.080 --> 00:57:47.200
[Guest]: that it was because, you know, the better off were doing better than they had been.

00:57:47.200 --> 00:57:49.560
[Guest]: That is what should not have been said.

00:57:49.560 --> 00:57:52.160
[Guest]: And that is what lost the elections.

00:57:52.160 --> 00:57:54.720
[Guest]: And that the benefits, of course, showed up later.

00:57:54.720 --> 00:58:03.880
[Guest]: But I'm talking about a more deeper, shall I say, trait or character that you might do

00:58:03.880 --> 00:58:07.360
[Guest]: or not do something because of winning or losing elections.

00:58:07.360 --> 00:58:09.320
[Guest]: Okay, so that's one thing.

00:58:09.320 --> 00:58:15.400
[Guest]: But on the other hand, if you had no constraints, what would you do?

00:58:15.400 --> 00:58:22.600
[Guest]: So if you had no constraints, would you be bringing in more welfare programs, large ones,

00:58:22.600 --> 00:58:27.120
[Guest]: you know, and not ones that are interest subvention, where the government is putting this much

00:58:27.120 --> 00:58:29.720
[Guest]: money and, you know, getting leverage out of it?

00:58:29.720 --> 00:58:34.480
[Guest]: Not those, but, you know, very large welfare programs, which the state has little capacity

00:58:34.480 --> 00:58:39.880
[Guest]: to actually even handle, or would you be trying to do?

00:58:39.880 --> 00:58:47.760
[Guest]: In fact, if I look back at the Atmanirbhar package, a lot of those things were, many

00:58:47.760 --> 00:58:55.440
[Guest]: of those, including the farm bills, more prominently than anything else, the farm bills, were things

00:58:55.440 --> 00:58:59.800
[Guest]: that should have been done earlier, which were pro-market reforms.

00:58:59.800 --> 00:59:04.380
[Guest]: So what is it that you would do if you had been completely unconstrained?

00:59:04.380 --> 00:59:11.880
[Guest]: And what I'm saying is simply this, that different political parties do have different characters,

00:59:11.880 --> 00:59:16.720
[Guest]: do have different ideologies, would do different things if they were completely unconstrained.

00:59:16.720 --> 00:59:24.200
[Guest]: Then, of course, the constraint of elections comes in when the NDA would not run another

00:59:24.200 --> 00:59:28.920
[Guest]: India Shining program, wouldn't do many of those things, would back off when you say

00:59:28.920 --> 00:59:30.860
[Guest]: Sudbhut ki Sarkar.

00:59:30.860 --> 00:59:38.080
[Guest]: But if there was unconstrained maximization, then would they, you know, do things differently

00:59:38.080 --> 00:59:42.080
[Guest]: from what the Congress would do?

00:59:42.080 --> 00:59:48.240
[Guest]: And I think that parties, at least in our two big parties, from what I feel looking

00:59:48.240 --> 00:59:53.240
[Guest]: back is that they do differently, they do things, they pick different battles.

00:59:53.240 --> 00:59:59.520
[Guest]: And even though both are constrained, but, you know, to the extent, at least the PDMA

00:59:59.520 --> 01:00:02.720
[Guest]: bill was tabled in Parliament.

01:00:02.720 --> 01:00:03.720
[Amit Varma]: Maybe they rolled back.

01:00:03.720 --> 01:00:08.760
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I'm not sure how much of this sort of fundamental thinking, as you seem to imply,

01:00:08.760 --> 01:00:13.680
[Amit Varma]: we saw in Modi's first term, you know, where I think a lot of the, I mean, I wouldn't even

01:00:13.680 --> 01:00:16.640
[Amit Varma]: call demonetization a misstep, it was just a massive blunder.

01:00:16.640 --> 01:00:19.120
[Amit Varma]: And the thinking behind it was completely wrong.

01:00:19.120 --> 01:00:22.920
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of what seems to have happened in those five years seems to be more the whims

01:00:22.920 --> 01:00:28.280
[Amit Varma]: and fancies of certain individuals rather than any kind of directed thinking.

01:00:28.280 --> 01:00:32.960
[Amit Varma]: But leaving that aside, you know, the second question I had from what you sort of said

01:00:32.960 --> 01:00:36.920
[Amit Varma]: earlier is again, a kind of a mindset question, which is, again, you know, talking about the

01:00:36.920 --> 01:00:40.740
[Amit Varma]: growth versus welfare slash redistribution paradigm.

01:00:40.740 --> 01:00:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And I don't even want to use the word welfare, because it implies, you know, welfare is a

01:00:44.000 --> 01:00:47.480
[Amit Varma]: good word, you want people's welfare, but what we call welfare and economics doesn't

01:00:47.480 --> 01:00:50.400
[Amit Varma]: always lead to good outcomes.

01:00:50.400 --> 01:00:52.280
[Amit Varma]: You know, it just speaks to good intentions.

01:00:52.280 --> 01:00:57.160
[Amit Varma]: And we, you know, make the error of often judging policies by intentions and not outcomes.

01:00:57.160 --> 01:01:01.840
[Amit Varma]: But the truth again, there is that again, I think, to me is sort of shows a difference

01:01:01.840 --> 01:01:05.960
[Amit Varma]: between a positive some mindset and a zero some mindset where the redistribution mindset

01:01:05.960 --> 01:01:09.480
[Amit Varma]: is that some people are rich, some are poor, we got to do something about the poor, how

01:01:09.480 --> 01:01:11.480
[Amit Varma]: do we do it, we must redistribute.

01:01:11.480 --> 01:01:14.560
[Amit Varma]: But the point is, if overall, your country is poor, that's not going to achieve anything.

01:01:14.560 --> 01:01:18.640
[Amit Varma]: Whereas a growth mindset is that, you know, let's grow, everybody grows together, maybe

01:01:18.640 --> 01:01:20.760
[Amit Varma]: inequality grows as well.

01:01:20.760 --> 01:01:24.840
[Amit Varma]: But both the rich and the poorer will get a little richer, at least you're solving the

01:01:24.840 --> 01:01:25.840
[Amit Varma]: problem of poverty.

01:01:25.840 --> 01:01:30.120
[Amit Varma]: I mean, one of the things that I find is that most people think inequality and poverty are

01:01:30.120 --> 01:01:31.640
[Amit Varma]: exactly the same thing.

01:01:31.640 --> 01:01:35.040
[Amit Varma]: And if you're thinking in terms of growth, it doesn't seem to me that that is the case,

01:01:35.040 --> 01:01:39.640
[Amit Varma]: it seems to me that, you know, for example, through the 90s, I would say that, you know,

01:01:39.640 --> 01:01:43.800
[Amit Varma]: India lifted hundreds of millions of people out of poverty, and inequality grew.

01:01:43.800 --> 01:01:48.320
[Amit Varma]: And I don't see that inequality as a bad thing, I think a fundamental problem is poverty.

01:01:48.320 --> 01:01:52.960
[Amit Varma]: And it's really wealthier nations, that having solved the problem of poverty, can then look

01:01:52.960 --> 01:01:57.920
[Amit Varma]: at inequality and say that, okay, let's redistribute and all that, you know, even the Nordic states

01:01:57.920 --> 01:02:02.040
[Amit Varma]: really became welfare states after they reached a certain level of wealth, and they could

01:02:02.040 --> 01:02:04.800
[Amit Varma]: actually afford to redistribute.

01:02:04.800 --> 01:02:08.400
[Amit Varma]: And I'm not sure that we can really afford to redistribute too much.

01:02:08.400 --> 01:02:10.960
[Amit Varma]: So it just in terms of mindsets, have you seen this changing?

01:02:10.960 --> 01:02:15.240
[Amit Varma]: Or would you say that certain parties like the Congress, for example, have this zero

01:02:15.240 --> 01:02:16.920
[Amit Varma]: sum mindset.

01:02:16.920 --> 01:02:21.400
[Amit Varma]: And also, when you think about how it plays in politics, redistributive politics will

01:02:21.400 --> 01:02:26.440
[Amit Varma]: always play better, because you seem compassionate, that will bestow all this largesse on the

01:02:26.440 --> 01:02:30.460
[Amit Varma]: people, it seems compassionate, it plays better in political terms.

01:02:30.460 --> 01:02:34.480
[Amit Varma]: But a lot of these pro poor policies, as we have seen through the decades, actually harms

01:02:34.480 --> 01:02:35.680
[Amit Varma]: the poor.

01:02:35.680 --> 01:02:41.920
[Amit Varma]: And honestly, you know, even in the last few years, I haven't really seen, you know, I

01:02:41.920 --> 01:02:46.560
[Amit Varma]: agreed that the Vajpayee government was refreshing in many ways, but I haven't seen that in the

01:02:46.560 --> 01:02:47.560
[Amit Varma]: Modi government at all.

01:02:47.560 --> 01:02:49.680
[Amit Varma]: I mean, they've also been quite welfarist.

01:02:49.680 --> 01:02:54.240
[Amit Varma]: In fact, that could be one reason they did well in the 2019 elections, because Modi actually

01:02:54.240 --> 01:03:00.800
[Amit Varma]: managed to implement some of the welfarism in the heartland and so on.

01:03:00.800 --> 01:03:08.720
[Guest]: My understanding of what Modi tried to do was to get more to the people out of the same

01:03:08.720 --> 01:03:11.400
[Guest]: money that the Congress was spending.

01:03:11.400 --> 01:03:17.640
[Guest]: So if you beam it directly into their accounts, which is something that Montech used to be

01:03:17.640 --> 01:03:23.720
[Guest]: wanting to do towards, you know, Montech and Nandan, they were making plans and those are

01:03:23.720 --> 01:03:32.040
[Guest]: things that they were wanting to do, and in fact, UIDAI was set up as a structure that

01:03:32.040 --> 01:03:34.240
[Guest]: would allow them to do that.

01:03:34.240 --> 01:03:41.520
[Guest]: NIPFP had done a study for the then Planning Commission, where we had worked out on how

01:03:41.520 --> 01:03:48.680
[Guest]: ghost beneficiaries and duplicates would be reduced by Aadhaar and therefore all programs

01:03:48.680 --> 01:03:54.040
[Guest]: of the government should actually be done through Aadhaar and there should be direct

01:03:54.040 --> 01:03:55.040
[Guest]: benefit transfers.

01:03:55.040 --> 01:04:00.760
[Guest]: So, you know, when we study Latin American countries and we study direct benefit transfers,

01:04:00.760 --> 01:04:05.640
[Guest]: cash transfers, instead of the kind of stuff that we used to have, then we used to say

01:04:05.640 --> 01:04:08.800
[Guest]: that that is better economics, you're spending the money.

01:04:08.800 --> 01:04:15.700
[Guest]: Now that way Modi got more bang for the buck, because when something goes straight into

01:04:15.700 --> 01:04:22.160
[Guest]: a Jandhan account, Aadhaar-linked Jandhan account, instead of, you know, it being leaked,

01:04:22.160 --> 01:04:23.160
[Guest]: what did Rajiv Gandhi do?

01:04:23.160 --> 01:04:28.760
[Amit Varma]: I think Rajiv Gandhi said that something like 85% of, there's 85% leakage.

01:04:28.760 --> 01:04:32.600
[Amit Varma]: So if you give a hundred rupees to a guy, by the time it reaches him, there's 15 rupees

01:04:32.600 --> 01:04:33.600
[Guest]: left.

01:04:33.600 --> 01:04:34.600
[Guest]: Absolutely.

01:04:34.600 --> 01:04:35.600
[Guest]: Absolutely.

01:04:35.600 --> 01:04:40.800
[Guest]: So, when you are in a system where there are a lot of middlemen and the middlemen would,

01:04:40.800 --> 01:04:46.640
[Guest]: I guess, not something I know, but I guess over the years have allegiance to the Congress

01:04:46.640 --> 01:04:51.080
[Guest]: because, you know, that's the old elite, the old political elite.

01:04:51.080 --> 01:04:55.640
[Guest]: And now there's no point in your feeding those middlemen, right?

01:04:55.640 --> 01:04:57.360
[Guest]: Because they're not yours.

01:04:57.360 --> 01:05:02.240
[Guest]: And secondly, you will get more bang for the buck, you know, when the hundred rupees reaches

01:05:02.240 --> 01:05:09.600
[Guest]: your voter directly, in a manner which, I mean, all Latin American economists and many

01:05:09.600 --> 01:05:15.320
[Guest]: of us who, till it started happening here, were lauding cash transfers, were saying that

01:05:15.320 --> 01:05:17.360
[Guest]: that's the right thing to do.

01:05:17.360 --> 01:05:26.240
[Guest]: Then it is an approach that, just let's assume for a moment, you know, put the economic reforms,

01:05:26.240 --> 01:05:30.440
[Guest]: pro-market economic reforms, as we understand it, to one side for the moment.

01:05:30.440 --> 01:05:37.600
[Guest]: Let's just try to assume that it was a UPA-3, okay, which went with, I'm not saying that

01:05:37.600 --> 01:05:44.640
[Guest]: Modi was UPA-3, so please, you know, I'm not, I'm only saying that, let's just assume that

01:05:44.640 --> 01:05:52.040
[Guest]: we take it as a continuation of the plans that were made by Montek and Nandan for the

01:05:52.040 --> 01:06:00.040
[Guest]: Planning Commission, which was the cost-benefit analysis study that I did, okay, at an IPFP

01:06:00.040 --> 01:06:05.200
[Guest]: for the Planning Commission, that this is what should be done and that this is how you'll

01:06:05.200 --> 01:06:12.360
[Guest]: reduce the leakages, both for ghost beneficiaries and for duplicates, and you will reduce leakages

01:06:12.360 --> 01:06:17.800
[Guest]: that go to the middlemen, and then let's say they had implemented that.

01:06:17.800 --> 01:06:21.820
[Guest]: I think all of us would have been saying that's very good.

01:06:21.820 --> 01:06:27.880
[Guest]: What happened, in my opinion, was that we had very high expectations of NDA-1 sort of

01:06:27.880 --> 01:06:35.660
[Guest]: reforms from NDA-2, and instead of, and maybe in the meantime, the party had understood

01:06:35.660 --> 01:06:42.080
[Guest]: that doing the NDA-1 reforms doesn't get them votes, so maybe they could slip in a reform

01:06:42.080 --> 01:06:47.600
[Guest]: here and there because they're not opposed to those reforms, but they could not be showing

01:06:47.600 --> 01:06:51.660
[Guest]: them as their big, that was not, you know, the big thing that they did.

01:06:51.660 --> 01:06:57.960
[Guest]: In fact, if the big thing that they do is to stop leakages and directly reach people,

01:06:57.960 --> 01:07:04.720
[Guest]: then you know, I think it's a very, very clever, very, very smart, very smart political move,

01:07:04.720 --> 01:07:09.640
[Guest]: and I think that's perhaps a part of what won the 2019 election.

01:07:09.640 --> 01:07:13.200
[Amit Varma]: So to sort of paraphrase what you're saying, you're saying that yeah, okay, there's a trade-off

01:07:13.200 --> 01:07:18.000
[Amit Varma]: between growth and redistribution, we should have pro-growth policies, but given the political

01:07:18.000 --> 01:07:22.520
[Amit Varma]: reality that those are much harder to do, and much harder to pull off given political

01:07:22.520 --> 01:07:27.920
[Amit Varma]: constraints, maybe it makes sense that if you have to do a certain amount of redistribution,

01:07:27.920 --> 01:07:31.360
[Amit Varma]: do the damn thing well, just be much more efficient.

01:07:31.360 --> 01:07:34.520
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, something like this, which is cutting off leakage from, you know, leakage

01:07:34.520 --> 01:07:39.280
[Amit Varma]: of 85%, as it were, maybe more, maybe less in specific instances, is something that is

01:07:39.280 --> 01:07:45.320
[Amit Varma]: going to pay you kind of great political dividends, so why not do that, and maybe other reforms

01:07:45.320 --> 01:07:52.960
[Guest]: can happen, you know, economically, plus economically, economically, as I was repeating that, when

01:07:52.960 --> 01:07:59.960
[Guest]: you study the impact of leakages on the FISC, and you look at whether, you know, you want

01:07:59.960 --> 01:08:06.040
[Guest]: to keep on letting that money slip through without having an impact on poverty, then

01:08:06.040 --> 01:08:10.840
[Guest]: it makes economic sense to do direct cash transfers.

01:08:10.840 --> 01:08:16.000
[Guest]: And if you spend the first two years doing this, whatever, Jam, Aadhaar, Trinity, whatever

01:08:16.000 --> 01:08:22.360
[Guest]: they call it, Jandhan Aadhaar Mobile, right, Jam, yeah, Jandhan Aadhaar Mobile, so if you

01:08:22.360 --> 01:08:26.880
[Guest]: spend time building the whole infrastructure, so I was in the ministry at that time, I was

01:08:26.880 --> 01:08:33.680
[Guest]: in the Ministry of Finance, you know, so as far as I was concerned, they did all the macroeconomic

01:08:33.680 --> 01:08:39.440
[Guest]: stabilization things with fiscal policy and inflation targeting, and some limited reforms

01:08:39.440 --> 01:08:47.280
[Guest]: that I had been talking about, but on the other hand, this was a big focus of the government,

01:08:47.280 --> 01:08:51.280
[Guest]: that we just get the money directly to people.

01:08:51.280 --> 01:08:56.160
[Guest]: That's not bad economic policy, that if you were doing redistribution badly, and you start

01:08:56.160 --> 01:09:02.560
[Guest]: doing it properly, that let's say that's your focus, not your focus is not to do agricultural

01:09:02.560 --> 01:09:10.520
[Guest]: bills on the first day, you did that in India too, I think that was a smart thing to do.

01:09:10.520 --> 01:09:16.040
[Guest]: I think that makes sense, not just politically, not just politically, it saves your fiscal

01:09:16.040 --> 01:09:17.040
[Guest]: lot of money.

01:09:17.040 --> 01:09:21.920
[Guest]: Otherwise, you know, think of the corruption, the leakages, the rent-seeking, what we have,

01:09:21.920 --> 01:09:26.880
[Guest]: we can just spend all, everything possible.

01:09:26.880 --> 01:09:30.600
[Amit Varma]: So you were like a principal economic advisor in 2014 and 2015.

01:09:30.600 --> 01:09:33.920
[Amit Varma]: Now it's interesting that, you know, if I remember correctly, at that time, you sided

01:09:33.920 --> 01:09:38.080
[Amit Varma]: with Raghuram Rajan, when he spoke about inflation targeting and all that, and Piyush Goyal was

01:09:38.080 --> 01:09:39.720
[Amit Varma]: against it and so on.

01:09:39.720 --> 01:09:44.520
[Amit Varma]: So what's that experience like, like one of the things that, you know, Pooja Mehra wrote

01:09:44.520 --> 01:09:48.720
[Amit Varma]: about in her book, The Lost Decade was that there was a certain continuity that when Arun

01:09:48.720 --> 01:09:53.600
[Amit Varma]: Jaitley came in as FM, he carried forward some of the thinking of the later months of

01:09:53.600 --> 01:09:54.720
[Amit Varma]: Chidambaram.

01:09:54.720 --> 01:09:58.000
[Amit Varma]: At that time, there was some unity there, and then everything kind of fell apart as

01:09:58.000 --> 01:09:59.000
[Amit Varma]: it went along.

01:09:59.000 --> 01:10:01.960
[Amit Varma]: And of course, you know, I know that there will, of course, be things that you cannot

01:10:01.960 --> 01:10:04.920
[Amit Varma]: speak about or, you know, can't reveal.

01:10:04.920 --> 01:10:08.640
[Amit Varma]: But apart from that, what was that experience like of working within the government?

01:10:08.640 --> 01:10:12.560
[Amit Varma]: Was there a sense that there is one direction that we are going in?

01:10:12.560 --> 01:10:13.840
[Amit Varma]: Were you taken seriously?

01:10:13.840 --> 01:10:16.880
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you did one of the economic surveys, yeah?

01:10:16.880 --> 01:10:19.920
[Guest]: Yeah, very much, certainly on inflation targeting.

01:10:19.920 --> 01:10:28.280
[Guest]: I mean, this was work that I had done when I was part of the research team of FSLRC,

01:10:28.280 --> 01:10:31.000
[Guest]: the Financial Sector Legislative Reforms Commission.

01:10:31.000 --> 01:10:37.280
[Guest]: This was work where I had a chapter in the book that was released by Prime Minister Modi

01:10:37.280 --> 01:10:41.800
[Guest]: when he was just elected, I mean, within the first few days.

01:10:41.800 --> 01:10:44.400
[Guest]: And this was something that I'd been working on for quite a while.

01:10:44.400 --> 01:10:50.640
[Guest]: And then when it came to, you know, working on first the Monetary Policy Framework Agreement,

01:10:50.640 --> 01:10:52.920
[Guest]: that was done in 2015.

01:10:52.920 --> 01:10:59.160
[Guest]: And finance secretary knew, you know, the DEA secretary was Rajiv Mehrishi, who first

01:10:59.160 --> 01:11:05.400
[Guest]: it was Mr. Mayaram, who I worked with, and he was also continuing that agenda forward.

01:11:05.400 --> 01:11:14.960
[Guest]: And then Mr. Mehrishi came and he put, you know, the accelerator was pressed very hard.

01:11:14.960 --> 01:11:17.360
[Guest]: And a lot of this work got done at that time.

01:11:17.360 --> 01:11:25.640
[Guest]: So by March 2016, the inflation targeting, the bill was actually, the RBI Act was amended

01:11:25.640 --> 01:11:29.240
[Guest]: and the objective of monetary policy was changed.

01:11:29.240 --> 01:11:35.160
[Guest]: So this was a period that was, I should say, exhilarating.

01:11:35.160 --> 01:11:39.480
[Amit Varma]: You say this was a period which was exhilarating, why did the period end?

01:11:39.480 --> 01:11:47.920
[Guest]: Well, I moved back to NIPFP and Mr. Mehrishi moved on, he became the Home Secretary.

01:11:47.920 --> 01:11:53.120
[Guest]: And then I think the way things went, it was also Arvind then joined as CEA.

01:11:53.120 --> 01:11:55.800
[Guest]: So earlier he was not Chief Economic Advisor.

01:11:55.800 --> 01:12:00.480
[Guest]: And then they started, Arvind was focusing on infrastructure, public sector, public investment

01:12:00.480 --> 01:12:02.400
[Guest]: in infrastructure.

01:12:02.400 --> 01:12:11.400
[Guest]: There was focus on doing NIIF funds for investment, basically, the focus shifted to how can we

01:12:11.400 --> 01:12:16.640
[Guest]: increase public investment away from, you know, when you do financial sector reforms,

01:12:16.640 --> 01:12:23.360
[Guest]: the returns come a decade later.

01:12:23.360 --> 01:12:29.400
[Guest]: So I think part of what happened was that, yes, we've done some of this and this will

01:12:29.400 --> 01:12:35.480
[Guest]: take years to play out, but now we better get back to the task on hand, which is try

01:12:35.480 --> 01:12:37.240
[Guest]: to push investment.

01:12:37.240 --> 01:12:39.080
[Guest]: So the focus shifted a bit.

