01:13:59.240 --> 01:14:01.960
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene and the unseen.

01:14:01.960 --> 01:14:06.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Ela Patnaik about the Indian economy as it is today.

01:14:06.000 --> 01:14:10.760
[Amit Varma]: But I'll continue with kind of general questions for a while because this is sort of a question

01:14:10.760 --> 01:14:12.120
[Amit Varma]: that has a bearing on everything.

01:14:12.120 --> 01:14:14.120
[Amit Varma]: And it's a question about data.

01:14:14.120 --> 01:14:17.320
[Amit Varma]: Like as an economist, you need raw material to work with.

01:14:17.320 --> 01:14:21.880
[Amit Varma]: And in India, famously, the quality of data is incredibly iffy.

01:14:21.880 --> 01:14:25.880
[Amit Varma]: So much of India is actually in the informal sector, for example, like, I remember sort

01:14:25.880 --> 01:14:30.560
[Amit Varma]: of interrogating Arvind Subramaniam on this when he was on my show about, you know, the

01:14:30.560 --> 01:14:31.920
[Amit Varma]: impact of demonetization.

01:14:31.920 --> 01:14:35.360
[Amit Varma]: And my point is that, you know, so much of the data is just not there, because it would

01:14:35.360 --> 01:14:37.520
[Amit Varma]: have hurt the informal sector the most.

01:14:37.520 --> 01:14:42.160
[Amit Varma]: And even a lot of the data which is there, like the GDP, for example, which is like a

01:14:42.160 --> 01:14:45.400
[Amit Varma]: sort of a marker in the public eyes for how the economy is doing.

01:14:45.400 --> 01:14:49.840
[Amit Varma]: But number one, the methodology keeps changing and is somewhat opaque.

01:14:49.840 --> 01:14:53.360
[Amit Varma]: And number two, any metric that exists can be gamed.

01:14:53.360 --> 01:14:56.440
[Amit Varma]: I had done an episode with Rajeshwari Sengupta on the GDP as well.

01:14:56.440 --> 01:15:01.400
[Amit Varma]: And it's historically been a metric that can be gamed, has been gamed.

01:15:01.400 --> 01:15:06.080
[Amit Varma]: One doesn't know how much it truly reflects either progress or the opposite of it.

01:15:06.080 --> 01:15:10.520
[Amit Varma]: So what's your approach towards data in the sense that, you know, since the mid 90s, you

01:15:10.520 --> 01:15:14.480
[Amit Varma]: had to work in this environment where you know your data is iffy.

01:15:14.480 --> 01:15:17.520
[Amit Varma]: So do you figure out proxy ways of getting data?

01:15:17.520 --> 01:15:20.360
[Amit Varma]: Do you do different kinds of jugaad for your analysis?

01:15:20.360 --> 01:15:21.600
[Amit Varma]: What's your approach towards that?

01:15:21.600 --> 01:15:24.080
[Guest]: And how much of a hindrance is it?

01:15:24.080 --> 01:15:30.520
[Guest]: So I started working on business cycles, which mean trying to track the economy in 96.

01:15:30.520 --> 01:15:35.400
[Guest]: You know, that was one of my first projects and it was a project for the RBI at NCAR,

01:15:35.400 --> 01:15:40.240
[Guest]: where we were trying to look at how can we measure the economy as it is today?

01:15:40.240 --> 01:15:44.320
[Guest]: How can we measure the economy looking forward as well?

01:15:44.320 --> 01:15:47.240
[Guest]: And GDP is not even adequate for that.

01:15:47.240 --> 01:15:51.600
[Guest]: So one issue that you're talking about is the quality of the GDP data, but the second

01:15:51.600 --> 01:15:53.120
[Guest]: is that it comes later.

01:15:53.120 --> 01:15:58.440
[Guest]: So you know what happened if you know a bit about what happened earlier, but you don't

01:15:58.440 --> 01:16:00.040
[Guest]: know what is happening now.

01:16:00.040 --> 01:16:08.040
[Guest]: So what we did was to, well, we had 105 monthly series that were available.

01:16:08.040 --> 01:16:16.240
[Guest]: So you know, you think about price series, imports, exports, money supply, IIP, then

01:16:16.240 --> 01:16:21.760
[Guest]: now we've added more lately, I continue to, you know, do the same thing, because tracking

01:16:21.760 --> 01:16:24.040
[Guest]: the economy is something that's of deep interest to me.

01:16:24.040 --> 01:16:29.580
[Guest]: So now we've added data from sales and profits of firms.

01:16:29.580 --> 01:16:34.680
[Guest]: So there's a prowess database where they put together firm performance, so annual reports

01:16:34.680 --> 01:16:36.560
[Guest]: of firms, so we track that.

01:16:36.560 --> 01:16:42.920
[Guest]: So we don't just look at only GDP, we look at a number of indicators.

01:16:42.920 --> 01:16:49.320
[Guest]: There is actually a well-established literature on this, where starting from Mitchell and

01:16:49.320 --> 01:16:57.800
[Guest]: Burns at NBER in the US in the 40s, there is an attempt by economists to catch what

01:16:57.800 --> 01:17:02.040
[Guest]: is happening today, to catch it not just through GDP, but to understand it through a number

01:17:02.040 --> 01:17:03.360
[Guest]: of other indicators.

01:17:03.360 --> 01:17:10.160
[Guest]: We have also been trying to build a coincident indicator series and a leading indicator series

01:17:10.160 --> 01:17:12.080
[Guest]: to see how they behave.

01:17:12.080 --> 01:17:17.840
[Guest]: Now, very often, you know, we see things a little before they happen, because we are

01:17:17.840 --> 01:17:21.360
[Guest]: looking at these various indicators.

01:17:21.360 --> 01:17:25.560
[Guest]: Of course, we are constrained by not being able to see everything, because, you know,

01:17:25.560 --> 01:17:28.120
[Guest]: we don't capture the informal sector.

01:17:28.120 --> 01:17:31.960
[Guest]: But you know, we don't capture the informal sector from the production side.

01:17:31.960 --> 01:17:38.200
[Guest]: But if you think about it, then people in the informal sector also live, consume, buy

01:17:38.200 --> 01:17:39.200
[Guest]: things.

01:17:39.200 --> 01:17:44.560
[Guest]: So, you know, GDP is measured not in just one way, but in three different ways.

01:17:44.560 --> 01:17:47.520
[Guest]: And we do capture some of it.

01:17:47.520 --> 01:17:52.160
[Amit Varma]: Can you give me any example that comes to mind of when looking at data in all these

01:17:52.160 --> 01:17:57.180
[Amit Varma]: very granular, unconventional, nuanced ways might have given you insight about something

01:17:57.180 --> 01:18:00.800
[Amit Varma]: that is happening or something that is going to happen, which you would otherwise have

01:18:00.800 --> 01:18:01.800
[Amit Varma]: missed?

01:18:01.800 --> 01:18:05.280
[Amit Varma]: Like, were there any aha moments in all these years of studying the data, which kind of

01:18:05.280 --> 01:18:08.240
[Amit Varma]: made you see something a little better?

01:18:08.240 --> 01:18:15.320
[Guest]: Well, I think it's more a question of timeliness, that one is able to see that, you know, if

01:18:15.320 --> 01:18:16.320
[Guest]: it's imports.

01:18:16.320 --> 01:18:20.160
[Guest]: First of all, it's not very unconventional, by the way, as I said, it's been done since

01:18:20.160 --> 01:18:21.160
[Guest]: the 1940s.

01:18:21.160 --> 01:18:26.200
[Guest]: But in India, I mean, yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:18:26.200 --> 01:18:32.800
[Guest]: So you know, you start looking at import data, we even make an index of our leading indicators,

01:18:32.800 --> 01:18:34.040
[Guest]: some others also do.

01:18:34.040 --> 01:18:37.740
[Guest]: But if you look at import data, it reflects what is coming later.

01:18:37.740 --> 01:18:40.720
[Guest]: So you kind of catch on a little sooner.

01:18:40.720 --> 01:18:48.560
[Guest]: So it's a question of time, not so much of being, you know, knowing more or less about

01:18:48.560 --> 01:18:49.560
[Guest]: the economy.

01:18:49.560 --> 01:18:54.480
[Guest]: So you get to know a little bit sooner when you track other series, which are more frequent.

01:18:54.480 --> 01:18:57.200
[Guest]: Like I was looking at the export data.

01:18:57.200 --> 01:19:06.000
[Guest]: So weekly in the first week of May, this May, exports are showing an increase of 80% over

01:19:06.000 --> 01:19:08.940
[Guest]: the last year, when last year, there was a lockdown, of course.

01:19:08.940 --> 01:19:10.840
[Guest]: So there's a base effect as well.

01:19:10.840 --> 01:19:14.840
[Guest]: But at least it's showing 80%, it's showing a positive high growth, because the world

01:19:14.840 --> 01:19:16.680
[Guest]: economy has started picking up.

01:19:16.680 --> 01:19:22.280
[Guest]: So you know, then you it helps you understand better of where you're going, and you just

01:19:22.280 --> 01:19:24.640
[Guest]: get a bit of an early start.

01:19:24.640 --> 01:19:27.960
[Amit Varma]: So the way I want to talk about the economy is maybe the last few years and then come

01:19:27.960 --> 01:19:28.960
[Amit Varma]: to COVID.

01:19:28.960 --> 01:19:34.900
[Amit Varma]: But an immediate question, which is kind of sparked by the beginning of this pandemic,

01:19:34.900 --> 01:19:39.480
[Amit Varma]: because I just want to understand how an economist thinks about specific problems.

01:19:39.480 --> 01:19:43.760
[Amit Varma]: So now let's say that in March last year, if an economist working with government and

01:19:43.760 --> 01:19:48.320
[Amit Varma]: I'm specifying working with government in this hypothetical instance, because I don't

01:19:48.320 --> 01:19:52.920
[Amit Varma]: just want to think of how economists sitting on the outside whose views may have no bearing

01:19:52.920 --> 01:19:56.440
[Amit Varma]: on the world, how they think, but if you're working with government, if you're advising

01:19:56.440 --> 01:20:02.800
[Amit Varma]: government, then how would one begin to calibrate a policy move, like a lockdown, like you've

01:20:02.800 --> 01:20:06.600
[Amit Varma]: of course, characterized it as lives versus livelihoods, which of course it is.

01:20:06.600 --> 01:20:10.880
[Amit Varma]: And you could also say in a sense as lives versus lives, because, you know, in the long

01:20:10.880 --> 01:20:12.920
[Amit Varma]: run, there will be the impact of a lockdown.

01:20:12.920 --> 01:20:17.880
[Amit Varma]: Now, this kind of policy measure seems to me to really be a terrible Hobson's choice

01:20:17.880 --> 01:20:23.800
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that whatever you do, the bad effects of it are seen, and the good effects

01:20:23.800 --> 01:20:24.880
[Amit Varma]: are unseen.

01:20:24.880 --> 01:20:29.800
[Amit Varma]: So you you know, if you call a lockdown, you will, for example, see the impact on migrant

01:20:29.800 --> 01:20:34.120
[Amit Varma]: labour on the economy, you'll see all of that what you will not see is the opportunity costs

01:20:34.120 --> 01:20:35.680
[Amit Varma]: the lives that you've saved.

01:20:35.680 --> 01:20:36.680
[Amit Varma]: And vice versa.

01:20:36.680 --> 01:20:39.800
[Amit Varma]: If you don't call a lockdown, you'll see the lives of people who die.

01:20:39.800 --> 01:20:43.000
[Amit Varma]: But what you won't see is that the economy is still functioning.

01:20:43.000 --> 01:20:48.560
[Amit Varma]: Now, whenever one makes a decision like this, and unfortunately, with the Indian state,

01:20:48.560 --> 01:20:52.400
[Amit Varma]: because of state capacity, there are only these very blunt tools, you either do a lockdown

01:20:52.400 --> 01:20:53.560
[Amit Varma]: or you don't.

01:20:53.560 --> 01:20:57.640
[Amit Varma]: And you know, given that that is the case, how would an economist think about this?

01:20:57.640 --> 01:21:02.200
[Amit Varma]: Like what is the data you'd look at, what would you do to establish some kind of understanding

01:21:02.200 --> 01:21:04.760
[Amit Varma]: of what the probabilities might be?

01:21:04.760 --> 01:21:08.520
[Amit Varma]: And of course, the political calculus and all that is something completely separate.

01:21:08.520 --> 01:21:12.720
[Amit Varma]: But just to sort of understand how an economist thinks, what are the tools you're bringing

01:21:12.720 --> 01:21:13.720
[Amit Varma]: into play here?

01:21:13.720 --> 01:21:16.520
[Amit Varma]: How would you do it?

01:21:16.520 --> 01:21:19.800
[Guest]: I would think about what is the kind of shock that this is.

01:21:19.800 --> 01:21:24.040
[Guest]: So in the first lockdown, it was a supply side shock.

01:21:24.040 --> 01:21:29.600
[Guest]: Because we said, okay, shut down, and companies had to shut down.

01:21:29.600 --> 01:21:31.400
[Guest]: It wasn't so much a demand side shock.

01:21:31.400 --> 01:21:34.960
[Guest]: I mean, of course, to some extent, you would call it a demand side shock, but it was a

01:21:34.960 --> 01:21:39.080
[Guest]: temporary demand side shock, that is people could not go to the shops.

01:21:39.080 --> 01:21:42.200
[Guest]: And so they were not buying products.

01:21:42.200 --> 01:21:46.080
[Guest]: But suppose it had lasted, let's just because there's so much uncertainty that one doesn't

01:21:46.080 --> 01:21:49.040
[Guest]: know whether it was going, how long it was going to last.

01:21:49.040 --> 01:21:53.800
[Guest]: But suppose it had last, the lockdown and the pandemic had lasted one month.

01:21:53.800 --> 01:22:01.040
[Guest]: And let's say that my understanding from not economics, but epidemiology and you know,

01:22:01.040 --> 01:22:05.360
[Guest]: whatever, whatever the doctors were telling us was that it was going to last for one month.

01:22:05.360 --> 01:22:06.920
[Guest]: Let's just assume.

01:22:06.920 --> 01:22:15.120
[Guest]: Then I would try to understand, okay, if I, one month later, I allow people to get back

01:22:15.120 --> 01:22:20.320
[Guest]: to work, then it will almost be, you know, the demand would not be hit.

01:22:20.320 --> 01:22:22.280
[Guest]: It would mainly be the supply got affected.

01:22:22.280 --> 01:22:27.760
[Guest]: Yes, there would be some people whose balance sheets would hurt, but, you know, we can go

01:22:27.760 --> 01:22:28.760
[Guest]: forward.

01:22:28.760 --> 01:22:35.360
[Guest]: Now, if I turn to today, and suppose, so again, data is very limited.

01:22:35.360 --> 01:22:37.400
[Guest]: One would look at consumer sentiment.

01:22:37.400 --> 01:22:41.080
[Guest]: One looks at imports in terms of activity, one looks at exports.

01:22:41.080 --> 01:22:47.320
[Guest]: So, you know, looking at what is happening here, household expenditure, household, you

01:22:47.320 --> 01:22:52.080
[Guest]: know, unemployment data that one gets, Mandrega data, because Mandrega is a good indicator

01:22:52.080 --> 01:22:56.640
[Guest]: of people having gone back to villages and what they are doing now.

01:22:56.640 --> 01:23:01.560
[Guest]: Putting all of this together, one would try to understand, has there been a year long

01:23:01.560 --> 01:23:04.920
[Guest]: deep impact on people's incomes?

01:23:04.920 --> 01:23:13.320
[Guest]: And if so, then are we going to see a deeper demand effect than we saw in the first case?

01:23:13.320 --> 01:23:17.960
[Guest]: And that would help me to, and suppose, of course, somebody said that this would continue

01:23:17.960 --> 01:23:19.960
[Guest]: for a year, okay?

01:23:19.960 --> 01:23:23.680
[Guest]: Then one would try to think of what are the policies?

01:23:23.680 --> 01:23:24.680
[Guest]: These are not easy choices.

01:23:24.680 --> 01:23:29.640
[Guest]: As you very, very correctly said, whatever happens, you're going to be blamed for doing

01:23:29.640 --> 01:23:30.640
[Guest]: the wrong thing.

01:23:30.640 --> 01:23:31.640
[Guest]: Okay.

01:23:31.640 --> 01:23:36.240
[Guest]: But, you know, then one would try to understand, okay, what does one require to give a demand

01:23:36.240 --> 01:23:37.240
[Guest]: stimulus?

01:23:37.240 --> 01:23:41.360
[Guest]: Initially, if you notice, I mean, somebody must have figured this out.

01:23:41.360 --> 01:23:45.560
[Guest]: But there wasn't much of a demand stimulus given, because it was a supply side issue.

01:23:45.560 --> 01:23:50.200
[Guest]: So when the package came, it had, you know, food and so on.

01:23:50.200 --> 01:23:53.260
[Guest]: But other than that, it was reforms.

01:23:53.260 --> 01:23:58.280
[Guest]: In some other countries, they continue to, they gave wages.

01:23:58.280 --> 01:24:01.740
[Guest]: So I guess, you know, these are the tools I would use.

01:24:01.740 --> 01:24:03.680
[Amit Varma]: This is how I would think about it.

01:24:03.680 --> 01:24:07.760
[Amit Varma]: And how does one, like, for example, another policy debate that I've seen playing out in

01:24:07.760 --> 01:24:11.440
[Amit Varma]: the United States, for example, is that when do we open schools?

01:24:11.440 --> 01:24:13.120
[Amit Varma]: How long do we shut schools?

01:24:13.120 --> 01:24:19.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, Anup Malani in an episode with Milan Vaishnav on his podcast, the Grand Tamasha,

01:24:19.040 --> 01:24:22.600
[Amit Varma]: Milan's podcast, that is, had made the point that, you know, that if you shut schools for

01:24:22.600 --> 01:24:27.080
[Amit Varma]: a year, for example, in a hypothetic situation, the loss to the economy in the future is also

01:24:27.080 --> 01:24:29.720
[Amit Varma]: immense because human capital is getting affected.

01:24:29.720 --> 01:24:34.000
[Amit Varma]: And you simply don't know that just mentally how the kids will be and how everything will

01:24:34.000 --> 01:24:35.000
[Amit Varma]: proceed.

01:24:35.000 --> 01:24:36.000
[Amit Varma]: There are so many kinds of imponderables.

01:24:36.000 --> 01:24:41.280
[Amit Varma]: And at some level, when it comes to things like this, it seems to me that, you know,

01:24:41.280 --> 01:24:43.680
[Amit Varma]: the cost goes somewhere, the benefits go somewhere else.

01:24:43.680 --> 01:24:46.520
[Amit Varma]: How can you even do a cost to benefit analysis?

01:24:46.520 --> 01:24:49.180
[Amit Varma]: In many ways, it seems like apples and oranges.

01:24:49.180 --> 01:24:54.280
[Amit Varma]: And the very act of attempting to do an analysis would also come down to say putting a price

01:24:54.280 --> 01:24:55.320
[Amit Varma]: on a life.

01:24:55.320 --> 01:24:59.280
[Amit Varma]: Do economists who often get a rap for being heartless, do they do that?

01:24:59.280 --> 01:25:02.760
[Amit Varma]: Do they like implicitly are you having to put a price on lives?

01:25:02.760 --> 01:25:07.900
[Amit Varma]: Like, if I was to tell you that the lockdown will save 100 lives but cost so many 100 crores,

01:25:07.900 --> 01:25:09.760
[Amit Varma]: you would probably say, let's not have a lockdown.

01:25:09.760 --> 01:25:13.940
[Amit Varma]: But if I tell you it will save 100,000 lives, and you know, the calculus changes.

01:25:13.940 --> 01:25:18.080
[Amit Varma]: How does one, you know, come to grips with all of this?

01:25:18.080 --> 01:25:22.760
[Guest]: I'm not sure that economists do this very differently from the rest of us.

01:25:22.760 --> 01:25:26.200
[Guest]: And if they do, if they do, they're pretending to do it.

01:25:26.200 --> 01:25:29.120
[Guest]: Because nobody can put a cost to a life.

01:25:29.120 --> 01:25:33.440
[Guest]: You might have your measures, you might develop them because you want to be able to pay somebody

01:25:33.440 --> 01:25:35.560
[Guest]: in case of an accident.

01:25:35.560 --> 01:25:37.900
[Guest]: But you know, that's a bit of a practical thing.

01:25:37.900 --> 01:25:45.500
[Guest]: But if you do it prior to the event, then I don't think anybody, economist or not has

01:25:45.500 --> 01:25:53.580
[Guest]: the courage to say, these young girls, daughters of so and so can go die.

01:25:53.580 --> 01:25:54.880
[Guest]: Nobody has the courage to do that.

01:25:54.880 --> 01:25:58.300
[Guest]: And nobody, we don't think like that, we can't think like that.

01:25:58.300 --> 01:26:04.120
[Guest]: So I'm not sure that, you know, this is something that anybody actually does.

01:26:04.120 --> 01:26:08.160
[Guest]: Even though yes, you know, there might be academic papers and debates saying that, you

01:26:08.160 --> 01:26:12.480
[Guest]: know, it's okay to lose 1000 lives and, you know, not spend money.

01:26:12.480 --> 01:26:17.720
[Guest]: But you know, at least I've always been saying, initially spend what you have to on the RTPCR

01:26:17.720 --> 01:26:18.720
[Guest]: test.

01:26:18.720 --> 01:26:23.640
[Guest]: Let it be 1% of GDP and whoever spends it, whether it's state governments, central governments,

01:26:23.640 --> 01:26:26.600
[Guest]: companies, schools, institutions, whoever spends it.

01:26:26.600 --> 01:26:31.320
[Guest]: And today that spend what you need to on vaccination, you know, bring all the energy you have, bring

01:26:31.320 --> 01:26:32.320
[Guest]: all the money you have.

01:26:32.320 --> 01:26:38.960
[Guest]: I mean, you save a life, you can always earn more later, do something, not do something,

01:26:38.960 --> 01:26:43.960
[Guest]: live frugally, whatever happens, but you know, once you've lost a life, it doesn't come back.

01:26:43.960 --> 01:26:48.400
[Guest]: And you know, this is a pandemic, it's a once in, I don't know, we've never been in this

01:26:48.400 --> 01:26:51.200
[Guest]: situation before of making these choices.

01:26:51.200 --> 01:26:58.700
[Guest]: And I don't think anybody has the tools or is in a place to actually make these choices.

01:26:58.700 --> 01:27:04.720
[Guest]: This thing, I think, comes down to the question of when you decide whether to do a national

01:27:04.720 --> 01:27:11.040
[Guest]: lockdown or not to do a national lockdown, okay, that's what this will come down to.

01:27:11.040 --> 01:27:16.960
[Guest]: Then the question to ask would not be whether you were making the decision between saving

01:27:16.960 --> 01:27:22.720
[Guest]: lives and not saving lives, but it would really be that could a local lockdown save lives

01:27:22.720 --> 01:27:28.760
[Guest]: as well, compared to a national lockdown, because a national lockdown absolutely does

01:27:28.760 --> 01:27:31.800
[Guest]: lead to a lot of misery and loss of livelihoods.

01:27:31.800 --> 01:27:34.000
[Guest]: But does it actually save more lives?

01:27:34.000 --> 01:27:39.240
[Guest]: Does it, you know, so if somebody's ill in some other state, but like in Delhi, if we

01:27:39.240 --> 01:27:43.320
[Guest]: have started recovering and positivity rate has gone down, and the number of infections

01:27:43.320 --> 01:27:48.720
[Guest]: has gone down, then maybe a week or two down the line, if we decide to open up, even if

01:27:48.720 --> 01:27:52.920
[Guest]: cases somewhere else are rising, then is it not more rational to do so?

01:27:52.920 --> 01:27:54.600
[Amit Varma]: I think that's the choice.

01:27:54.600 --> 01:27:59.360
[Amit Varma]: Okay, so you know, when you said at the start of your answer that you think economists are

01:27:59.360 --> 01:28:02.920
[Amit Varma]: just the same as normal people, what you went on to say was that none of us will want to

01:28:02.920 --> 01:28:04.500
[Amit Varma]: place a value on a life.

01:28:04.500 --> 01:28:06.120
[Amit Varma]: But I thought you meant the opposite.

01:28:06.120 --> 01:28:09.840
[Amit Varma]: So I was a little surprised because I think implicitly everyone is placing a value on

01:28:09.840 --> 01:28:14.080
[Amit Varma]: our life, like even my own, for example, like every time I cross the road, I know there

01:28:14.080 --> 01:28:18.000
[Amit Varma]: is a very, very small probability that, you know, something will run me over.

01:28:18.000 --> 01:28:21.640
[Amit Varma]: But I choose to make that choice, because the sort of utility of crossing the road is

01:28:21.640 --> 01:28:25.400
[Amit Varma]: worth more to me than whatever that very tiny percentage is.

01:28:25.400 --> 01:28:28.920
[Amit Varma]: And this, of course, you know, every time I go out on a drive, for example, I'm making

01:28:28.920 --> 01:28:33.360
[Amit Varma]: the same kind of calculus, in a sense, I'm placing a certain value on my life.

01:28:33.360 --> 01:28:37.840
[Amit Varma]: And I think economists would also implicitly at least have to do that, even if they can't

01:28:37.840 --> 01:28:40.040
[Amit Varma]: put a number to it, because it is so icky.

01:28:40.040 --> 01:28:43.640
[Amit Varma]: And as human beings, we want to think every life is priceless.

01:28:43.640 --> 01:28:48.040
[Amit Varma]: But you know, in a thought experiment where a lockdown is going to cost, say, a thousand

01:28:48.040 --> 01:28:52.200
[Amit Varma]: crores, but is going to save just one life, you know, and you would say that the loss

01:28:52.200 --> 01:28:55.840
[Amit Varma]: of that thousand crores, the economy will actually cost many more lives somewhere down

01:28:55.840 --> 01:28:56.840
[Amit Varma]: the line.

01:28:56.840 --> 01:28:58.160
[Amit Varma]: And you don't actually know that.

01:28:58.160 --> 01:29:01.280
[Amit Varma]: So somewhere there is a number at which you say this is a threshold we have to call a

01:29:01.280 --> 01:29:02.280
[Amit Varma]: lockdown now.

01:29:02.280 --> 01:29:03.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, absolutely.

01:29:03.280 --> 01:29:08.720
[Guest]: But, you know, when it comes to things like giving indemnity, if the state has to say

01:29:08.720 --> 01:29:14.560
[Guest]: that, OK, if something goes wrong, we'll pay for it, while if, you know, people don't get

01:29:14.560 --> 01:29:19.760
[Guest]: the vaccine, oh, I will not give the vaccine, but I'll save, you know, whatever, ten thousand

01:29:19.760 --> 01:29:20.760
[Guest]: crores.

01:29:20.760 --> 01:29:25.040
[Guest]: OK, but, you know, ten crore people will die.

01:29:25.040 --> 01:29:29.800
[Guest]: If that's the kind of choice, then it's an open, nobody, yeah, yeah.

01:29:29.800 --> 01:29:34.400
[Guest]: So, you know, of course, I mean, I'm just saying that as economists, one is not doing

01:29:34.400 --> 01:29:35.400
[Guest]: anything different.

01:29:35.400 --> 01:29:39.240
[Guest]: I mean, you are you are placing a value on your life.

01:29:39.240 --> 01:29:40.240
[Guest]: Ask your mom.

01:29:40.240 --> 01:29:44.040
[Amit Varma]: No, no, I in this present circumstance, I mean, frankly, I think we're both in agreement

01:29:44.040 --> 01:29:47.880
[Amit Varma]: that we should just spend whatever to, you know, save lives because, you know, you'll

01:29:47.880 --> 01:29:51.060
[Amit Varma]: spend a thousand crores, but in the long run save way more.

01:29:51.060 --> 01:29:54.640
[Amit Varma]: And also indemnity, I guess you're referring to the whole Pfizer thing.

01:29:54.640 --> 01:29:57.560
[Amit Varma]: And I guess you agree with me that we should just give indemnity.

01:29:57.560 --> 01:30:01.200
[Amit Varma]: Every other country has given them indemnity, just bring them in, just get that, make the

01:30:01.200 --> 01:30:03.760
[Amit Varma]: damn vaccine available.

01:30:03.760 --> 01:30:08.960
[Guest]: Just feel that every day we are losing people and, you know, they won't come back.

01:30:08.960 --> 01:30:13.480
[Guest]: Whereas if we put some money down, then we can always earn more money or even if we don't

01:30:13.480 --> 01:30:14.480
[Amit Varma]: earn more money.

01:30:14.480 --> 01:30:15.480
[Amit Varma]: It's fine.

01:30:15.480 --> 01:30:16.480
[Guest]: I mean, we can live a bit more frugally.

01:30:16.480 --> 01:30:17.480
[Guest]: Yeah, it's fine.

01:30:17.480 --> 01:30:18.480
[Guest]: It's fine.

01:30:18.480 --> 01:30:21.440
[Guest]: So I think this should be at the top of the agenda.

01:30:21.440 --> 01:30:22.440
[Amit Varma]: It's just nuts.

01:30:22.440 --> 01:30:24.760
[Amit Varma]: But I mean, that's another discussion.

01:30:24.760 --> 01:30:27.320
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of get back to the economy now.

01:30:27.320 --> 01:30:30.880
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of zoom in and talk about, say, the trajectory of the last few years.

01:30:30.880 --> 01:30:35.160
[Amit Varma]: I'd done an episode with Pooja Mehra on her book, The Lost Decade, where the trajectory

01:30:35.160 --> 01:30:39.560
[Amit Varma]: that she shaped for me was that, look, our economy suddenly started doing much worse

01:30:39.560 --> 01:30:43.600
[Amit Varma]: at around the time Pranab Mukherjee took over as finance minister because there were the

01:30:43.600 --> 01:30:45.080
[Amit Varma]: terrorist attacks in Bombay.

01:30:45.080 --> 01:30:48.680
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, Shivraj Patil was Home Minister, did a lousy job.

01:30:48.680 --> 01:30:52.840
[Amit Varma]: They shifted Chidambaram there, therefore Pranab took over finance, made a complete

01:30:52.840 --> 01:30:58.240
[Amit Varma]: mess of it, started going downhill with a credit crisis, kind of got exacerbated.

01:30:58.240 --> 01:31:04.160
[Amit Varma]: And there was a whole atmosphere of retrospective taxation and what that did for the investment

01:31:04.160 --> 01:31:05.160
[Amit Varma]: mood.

01:31:05.160 --> 01:31:09.000
[Amit Varma]: There was just a bunch of things which listeners can go listen to that episode and all that.

01:31:09.000 --> 01:31:13.520
[Amit Varma]: And then when Modi came, they were, you know, Chidambaram took over after Pranab was elevated

01:31:13.520 --> 01:31:15.440
[Amit Varma]: to the presidency for a while.

01:31:15.440 --> 01:31:17.800
[Amit Varma]: But he was there for too short a time.

01:31:17.800 --> 01:31:19.680
[Amit Varma]: And then Modi took over.

01:31:19.680 --> 01:31:23.920
[Amit Varma]: And then politics came in the way the moment the suit boot ki sarkar jibes came, reforms

01:31:23.920 --> 01:31:30.200
[Amit Varma]: went out of the window and demon happened, the incredibly botched GST happened and so

01:31:30.200 --> 01:31:31.200
[Amit Varma]: on.

01:31:31.200 --> 01:31:32.200
[Amit Varma]: And it's just been downhill.

01:31:32.200 --> 01:31:35.760
[Amit Varma]: And then COVID hit and everything's just been downhill for the last 10 years.

01:31:35.760 --> 01:31:37.320
[Amit Varma]: Would you broadly agree with this narrative?

01:31:37.320 --> 01:31:39.860
[Amit Varma]: And you've been much, much closer to the action.

01:31:39.860 --> 01:31:41.680
[Amit Varma]: So what is your sense of it?

01:31:41.680 --> 01:31:45.120
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I'm sure there's a lot of nuance you can add to this.

01:31:45.120 --> 01:31:52.240
[Guest]: So I think 2011 or so is the period when I started seeing investment going down, private

01:31:52.240 --> 01:31:53.240
[Guest]: investment.

01:31:53.240 --> 01:32:00.520
[Guest]: I mean, really what has taken the economy up and down is cycles in private investment.

01:32:00.520 --> 01:32:04.720
[Guest]: So 2011 is the period when it starts going down.

01:32:04.720 --> 01:32:09.020
[Guest]: And I agree with most of what Pooja has said and what you're telling me.

01:32:09.020 --> 01:32:14.720
[Guest]: But just to add to the story, in my opinion, the story began earlier.

01:32:14.720 --> 01:32:20.200
[Guest]: The story began from 2004 to 2007.

01:32:20.200 --> 01:32:21.560
[Guest]: And why do I say that?

01:32:21.560 --> 01:32:25.600
[Guest]: Because that was the time when there was a lot of capital coming in.

01:32:25.600 --> 01:32:30.400
[Guest]: RBI was buying up dollars, pushing liquidity into the system.

01:32:30.400 --> 01:32:32.720
[Guest]: You know, we all look at it from our perspective.

01:32:32.720 --> 01:32:37.080
[Guest]: So I look at it from the perspective of monetary policy.

01:32:37.080 --> 01:32:43.760
[Guest]: And there was a time when credit was growing at about, in 2007, at about 40% per annum,

01:32:43.760 --> 01:32:46.440
[Guest]: a very high growth of credit.

01:32:46.440 --> 01:32:53.960
[Guest]: And banks were lending merrily, not being as prudent as they might have been if you

01:32:53.960 --> 01:32:59.800
[Guest]: didn't have this huge liquidity sloshing around in the system.

01:32:59.800 --> 01:33:03.760
[Guest]: And then came the 2007-2008 Lehman episode.

01:33:03.760 --> 01:33:09.600
[Guest]: In fact, things start going bad even towards the end, right at the end of 2007.

01:33:09.600 --> 01:33:12.880
[Guest]: So but of course, Lehman was the turning point.

01:33:12.880 --> 01:33:20.000
[Guest]: And after that, you had a sudden contraction in the economy and a decline in demand.

01:33:20.000 --> 01:33:27.760
[Guest]: A lot of the loans that had been given by the banking system were already in trouble.

01:33:27.760 --> 01:33:33.240
[Guest]: Most infrastructure companies, there had been a lot of emphasis on infrastructure.

01:33:33.240 --> 01:33:40.640
[Guest]: And you know, really, banks are not well suited to lend to infrastructure companies, because

01:33:40.640 --> 01:33:43.180
[Guest]: there is a maturity mismatch.

01:33:43.180 --> 01:33:49.000
[Guest]: The capacity of banks to assess those loans, to hold on to those loans for 30 years, to

01:33:49.000 --> 01:33:54.960
[Guest]: resist political influence, and not to give loans, especially public sector banks, you

01:33:54.960 --> 01:33:59.680
[Guest]: know, and with a regulator who would pretty much was turning a blind eye to the loans

01:33:59.680 --> 01:34:01.840
[Guest]: that were being given.

01:34:01.840 --> 01:34:07.520
[Guest]: So I can say that, you know, I've done some rough analysis, but roughly a third of the

01:34:07.520 --> 01:34:14.200
[Guest]: loans went bad, because just bad business decisions, people had been overoptimistic.

01:34:14.200 --> 01:34:18.640
[Guest]: And a third, of course, were frauds and cheats who ran away.

01:34:18.640 --> 01:34:25.280
[Guest]: And the others got into trouble because of what used to be famously called then policy

01:34:25.280 --> 01:34:31.520
[Guest]: paralysis, that you stepped out, you thought you'd get an environment clearance, you know,

01:34:31.520 --> 01:34:36.520
[Guest]: and somehow in the system, environment clearances were supposed to be gotten by the private

01:34:36.520 --> 01:34:38.740
[Guest]: contractor who was doing the project.

01:34:38.740 --> 01:34:42.200
[Guest]: It wasn't that the government, within the government got those clearances, they thought,

01:34:42.200 --> 01:34:44.280
[Guest]: oh, he let him bribe his way through.

01:34:44.280 --> 01:34:48.400
[Guest]: So a third, roughly a third went bad because of those.

01:34:48.400 --> 01:34:55.640
[Guest]: Now, this was a situation in say, 2010-11, when on top of this, you add retrospective

01:34:55.640 --> 01:35:01.640
[Guest]: taxes, and a badly managed Ministry of Finance.

01:35:01.640 --> 01:35:07.920
[Guest]: I was doing this NIPFPDA program that we've been doing, and it's a badly managed Ministry

01:35:07.920 --> 01:35:11.320
[Guest]: of Finance under Pranab Mukherjee, honestly.

01:35:11.320 --> 01:35:19.320
[Guest]: So put that all together, and you see that from 2011 onwards, investment starts declining.

01:35:19.320 --> 01:35:23.560
[Guest]: There's a little bit of a blip in 2015.

01:35:23.560 --> 01:35:29.600
[Guest]: So I expect that when Modi becomes Prime Minister, people start thinking that things will get

01:35:29.600 --> 01:35:32.360
[Guest]: some of those problems will get solved.

01:35:32.360 --> 01:35:38.360
[Guest]: But then that also, you know, goes away in about 16 or so, even before demonetization.

01:35:38.360 --> 01:35:42.000
[Guest]: So demonetization doesn't actually have a great visible impact.

01:35:42.000 --> 01:35:49.000
[Guest]: So I was one of the, you know, very outspoken opponents of demonetization.

01:35:49.000 --> 01:35:55.520
[Guest]: But when I look back, I didn't see as much of an effect as I thought there might be.

01:35:55.520 --> 01:35:58.800
[Guest]: But you know, be that as it may.

01:35:58.800 --> 01:36:00.800
[Guest]: Investment didn't pick up again.

01:36:00.800 --> 01:36:05.720
[Guest]: And we are, you know, I don't know where we will go in terms of, because the pandemic

01:36:05.720 --> 01:36:09.680
[Guest]: is I guess the last straw in this, because the more the uncertainty, investment always

01:36:09.680 --> 01:36:12.120
[Guest]: does badly under uncertainty.

01:36:12.120 --> 01:36:18.920
[Guest]: So if it didn't pick up from 2011 onwards, then this is not a time when I would think

01:36:18.920 --> 01:36:21.120
[Guest]: it's going to pick up very fast.

01:36:21.120 --> 01:36:24.400
[Guest]: Things will take time to work out.

01:36:24.400 --> 01:36:28.240
[Guest]: So that's the backstory I would add to Pooja's story.

01:36:28.240 --> 01:36:32.440
[Amit Varma]: How much of a factor in investments picking up is a quantitative easing, for example,

01:36:32.440 --> 01:36:35.640
[Amit Varma]: which happens out there, which happens in the US, for example, the easy money coming

01:36:35.640 --> 01:36:40.560
[Amit Varma]: in, so to say, because there is some of that happening right now after this pandemic, and

01:36:40.560 --> 01:36:42.240
[Amit Varma]: some of it will find its way into India.

01:36:42.240 --> 01:36:46.040
[Amit Varma]: In fact, some of it is why the stock market has done much better than you would expect

01:36:46.040 --> 01:36:48.400
[Amit Varma]: it to in these economic circumstances.

01:36:48.400 --> 01:36:54.480
[Amit Varma]: So are certain aspects of how our economy does independent of our economy itself?

01:36:54.480 --> 01:36:56.120
[Guest]: Yeah, absolutely.

01:36:56.120 --> 01:36:59.760
[Guest]: They are, but I think it's also about what is our policy response.

01:36:59.760 --> 01:37:03.920
[Guest]: So episodes such as the taper tantrum.

01:37:03.920 --> 01:37:09.480
[Guest]: So in 2013, when Ben Bernanke was expected to, you know, when he spoke and people thought

01:37:09.480 --> 01:37:14.080
[Guest]: that the Fed is going to start tightening right away, then money started flowing out

01:37:14.080 --> 01:37:17.440
[Guest]: of emerging economies.

01:37:17.440 --> 01:37:21.700
[Guest]: India's response was that we want to defend the rupee.

01:37:21.700 --> 01:37:27.600
[Guest]: And to try to defend the rupee, you know, we had Chidambaram and finance secretary and

01:37:27.600 --> 01:37:33.280
[Guest]: everybody just coming on TV every day, hiking up interest rates.

01:37:33.280 --> 01:37:34.280
[Guest]: This was a big mistake.

01:37:34.280 --> 01:37:38.320
[Guest]: I mean, the rupee kept slipping.

01:37:38.320 --> 01:37:39.720
[Guest]: They couldn't stop that.

01:37:39.720 --> 01:37:44.920
[Guest]: But they tightened monetary policy so much that, I mean, that's one thing that's really

01:37:44.920 --> 01:37:47.720
[Guest]: hurt the system.

01:37:47.720 --> 01:37:51.480
[Guest]: Because rates didn't go back down for a very long time.

01:37:51.480 --> 01:37:56.320
[Guest]: And so they didn't reverse, almost for a year, they didn't reverse all the measures that

01:37:56.320 --> 01:38:02.480
[Guest]: they had taken in the rupee defense of 2013, after the taper tantrum.

01:38:02.480 --> 01:38:12.200
[Guest]: And so let's just look forward now, see US is arguably overheating, because they've given

01:38:12.200 --> 01:38:15.160
[Guest]: a large fiscal stimulus and a large monetary stimulus.

01:38:15.160 --> 01:38:20.000
[Guest]: And if they're overheating, and if they start seeing inflation and the Fed starts tightening,

01:38:20.000 --> 01:38:25.560
[Guest]: then we could easily have again this risk on risk off situation where money goes out

01:38:25.560 --> 01:38:28.100
[Guest]: of emerging economies.

01:38:28.100 --> 01:38:32.440
[Guest]: The question would be what is going to be the policy response of the government and

01:38:32.440 --> 01:38:37.600
[Guest]: the RBI, if they start trying to defend the rupee, if this happens.

01:38:37.600 --> 01:38:39.440
[Guest]: So if it doesn't happen, fine.

01:38:39.440 --> 01:38:44.440
[Guest]: If this happens and they start trying to defend the rupee, and for that they tighten liquidity,

01:38:44.440 --> 01:38:53.880
[Guest]: raise interest rates, like they did in 2013, then whatever little chance we have of, you

01:38:53.880 --> 01:38:59.600
[Guest]: know, somehow getting up and trying to walk, we lose that as well.

01:38:59.600 --> 01:39:06.440
[Guest]: So the policy response, to a very large extent will determine the impact of what happens

01:39:06.440 --> 01:39:10.480
[Guest]: in the US on us.

01:39:10.480 --> 01:39:11.560
[Amit Varma]: So a couple of questions.

01:39:11.560 --> 01:39:17.080
[Amit Varma]: One is that it's kind of amusing to me how somehow in the popular narrative, the where

01:39:17.080 --> 01:39:21.080
[Amit Varma]: the rupee was got tied up with nationalism, that if the rupee was strong, we would be

01:39:21.080 --> 01:39:25.080
[Amit Varma]: proud and if the rupee was weak, we would be nahin yaar, woh dollar ko itna aage nahin

01:39:25.080 --> 01:39:26.080
[Amit Varma]: jaane dene ka.

01:39:26.080 --> 01:39:30.960
[Amit Varma]: So you know, how much of that is kind of a barrier and then if the if the popular sentiment

01:39:30.960 --> 01:39:35.960
[Amit Varma]: becomes like this, and definitely a lot of Modi's campaigning pre 2014 was look what

01:39:35.960 --> 01:39:40.080
[Amit Varma]: is happening to the rupee, and of course, forget what happened to it after he took over.

01:39:40.080 --> 01:39:44.920
[Amit Varma]: How much of this then involves the actual policy response like does it even matter like

01:39:44.920 --> 01:39:48.440
[Amit Varma]: shouldn't the rupee be wherever it is and we should simply not bother about it.

01:39:48.440 --> 01:39:49.440
[Amit Varma]: That's what I would imagine.

01:39:49.440 --> 01:39:51.400
[Amit Varma]: What's what's your take on that?

01:39:51.400 --> 01:39:57.200
[Guest]: So if you look back, it's a very interesting story that in the early 2000s, there was this

01:39:57.200 --> 01:40:01.880
[Guest]: huge attempt to prevent rupee appreciation.

01:40:01.880 --> 01:40:04.520
[Guest]: You wanted a weak rupee and why was that?

01:40:04.520 --> 01:40:08.300
[Guest]: Because the dominant lobby was the exporter lobby.

01:40:08.300 --> 01:40:13.560
[Guest]: The exporters were all the time, you know, whatever their federations are, whoever the

01:40:13.560 --> 01:40:21.680
[Guest]: exporters are, their industry lobbies, somehow, they always convince economists to say what

01:40:21.680 --> 01:40:28.000
[Guest]: they want said, but there was a lot of this, don't let the rupee get strong, CEO opened

01:40:28.000 --> 01:40:33.240
[Guest]: up capital flows, now capital is coming in, pushing the rupee up, making us uncompetitive,

01:40:33.240 --> 01:40:35.520
[Guest]: try to prevent rupee appreciation.

01:40:35.520 --> 01:40:41.360
[Guest]: And then RBI went on this major thing of trying to buy up rupees, preventing an appreciation.

01:40:41.360 --> 01:40:45.040
[Guest]: And then sometime in January 2004, they ran out of government bonds to sterilize their

01:40:45.040 --> 01:40:48.440
[Guest]: intervention because they were doing fully sterilized intervention because this was the

01:40:48.440 --> 01:40:49.440
[Guest]: second episode.

01:40:49.440 --> 01:40:52.200
[Unknown]: Remember, they hadn't done that in 96.

01:40:52.200 --> 01:40:56.200
[Guest]: So now, why did the situation change?

01:40:56.200 --> 01:41:01.760
[Guest]: In my opinion, the situation changed because once you allowed foreign borrowing, dollar

01:41:01.760 --> 01:41:06.560
[Guest]: denominated borrowing, then the people who were borrowing in dollars had a lot of dollar

01:41:06.560 --> 01:41:07.920
[Guest]: exposure.

01:41:07.920 --> 01:41:10.840
[Guest]: So they don't want a weak rupee.

01:41:10.840 --> 01:41:17.880
[Guest]: And in terms of the political influence and the, you know, cacophony, the everything,

01:41:17.880 --> 01:41:23.360
[Guest]: the need for a strong rupee became more important than the need for a weak rupee.

01:41:23.360 --> 01:41:29.620
[Guest]: The exporters had wanted a weak rupee, whereas the firms who have dollar denominated borrowings

01:41:29.620 --> 01:41:35.000
[Guest]: on their balance sheets, they want a strong rupee.

01:41:35.000 --> 01:41:37.720
[Guest]: So I don't think it's that much of nationalism.

01:41:37.720 --> 01:41:42.320
[Guest]: Of course, you know, somebody might say this or that, but I think eventually, at least

01:41:42.320 --> 01:41:49.360
[Guest]: what I see getting translated into policy and pressure for a certain kind of policy

01:41:49.360 --> 01:41:54.860
[Guest]: is how is industry getting impacted by the movement of the rupee, because there's a lot

01:41:54.860 --> 01:42:00.360
[Guest]: of exposure and that exposure, foreign currency exposure, which means that firms will get

01:42:00.360 --> 01:42:03.140
[Guest]: hit when the rupee moves.

01:42:03.140 --> 01:42:09.520
[Guest]: And this exposure is there because, you know, RBI is constantly intervening to try to prevent

01:42:09.520 --> 01:42:14.060
[Guest]: rupee, they call it volatility, let me call it flexibility, as you've just called it.

01:42:14.060 --> 01:42:17.780
[Guest]: They try to prevent the rupee from moving around too much.

01:42:17.780 --> 01:42:23.000
[Guest]: So when they try to prevent it, people think, aha, I can take, now they'll take care.

01:42:23.000 --> 01:42:26.980
[Guest]: So the rupee won't weaken too much or the rupee won't strengthen too much.

01:42:26.980 --> 01:42:29.340
[Guest]: So you get a lot of foreign currency exposure.

01:42:29.340 --> 01:42:34.120
[Guest]: This is part of the reason why you always have some sort of a pressure on RBI to do

01:42:34.120 --> 01:42:36.200
[Amit Varma]: something or the other.

01:42:36.200 --> 01:42:40.180
[Amit Varma]: And what's your recommended response to these kinds of pressures?

01:42:40.180 --> 01:42:47.540
[Guest]: Because exactly as yours was, stay out of it, just stay out of it, let it go wherever.

01:42:47.540 --> 01:42:50.020
[Guest]: And people will hedge their risks then.

01:42:50.020 --> 01:42:53.940
[Guest]: Today, it's a moral hazard problem, are not hedging their risk because they come back

01:42:53.940 --> 01:42:58.700
[Guest]: and scream at you, don't let the rupee this, don't let the rupee that, intervene, intervene,

01:42:58.700 --> 01:42:59.700
[Guest]: intervene.

01:42:59.700 --> 01:43:00.700
[Guest]: Oh, this has happened.

01:43:00.700 --> 01:43:02.340
[Guest]: And then the RBI steps in and intervenes.

01:43:02.340 --> 01:43:08.660
[Guest]: Whereas if you allow it to be volatile, to be flexible, people will hedge and you won't

01:43:08.660 --> 01:43:13.420
[Guest]: get that kind of exposure, currency exposure.

01:43:13.420 --> 01:43:17.100
[Amit Varma]: So one of your core causes, and before we get to the COVID economy and all of that,

01:43:17.100 --> 01:43:20.260
[Amit Varma]: one of your core causes through all this time and something that you're known for and that

01:43:20.260 --> 01:43:23.980
[Amit Varma]: mutual friends speak very highly of is your work on inflation targeting.

01:43:23.980 --> 01:43:27.740
[Amit Varma]: So I'd like to kind of try and ask you to demystify it a bit.

01:43:27.740 --> 01:43:31.900
[Amit Varma]: So first of all, I'll quickly kind of sum up what the role that monetary policy plays

01:43:31.900 --> 01:43:32.900
[Amit Varma]: in terms of inflation.

01:43:32.900 --> 01:43:36.220
[Amit Varma]: And you can correct me if I'm being too simplistic or if I mess up somewhere.

01:43:36.220 --> 01:43:40.900
[Amit Varma]: But basically what happens is that the RBI controls, your central bank controls the flow

01:43:40.900 --> 01:43:42.380
[Amit Varma]: of money into the economy.

01:43:42.380 --> 01:43:46.600
[Amit Varma]: So they can lower interest rates, which would mean that there is effectively a greater flow

01:43:46.600 --> 01:43:47.600
[Amit Varma]: of money into the economy.

01:43:47.600 --> 01:43:51.820
[Amit Varma]: And if the money supply goes up, but everything else remains the same, the prices of everything

01:43:51.820 --> 01:43:52.820
[Amit Varma]: will rise.

01:43:52.820 --> 01:43:53.980
[Amit Varma]: It's a supply and demand thing.

01:43:53.980 --> 01:43:58.620
[Amit Varma]: And it's the opposite thing that if they tighten it, then, you know, there is less money out

01:43:58.620 --> 01:43:59.620
[Amit Varma]: there.

01:43:59.620 --> 01:44:04.380
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, the price of everything might even go down or it'll affect the rate of inflation.

01:44:04.380 --> 01:44:09.620
[Amit Varma]: And the reason for the political impetus for loosening interest rates would be that, you

01:44:09.620 --> 01:44:13.580
[Amit Varma]: know, in the short term, you get, you know, more money out there, there's more buoyancy,

01:44:13.580 --> 01:44:14.580
[Amit Varma]: there's more spending.

01:44:14.580 --> 01:44:17.540
[Amit Varma]: And that makes the economy kind of look better.

01:44:17.540 --> 01:44:21.620
[Amit Varma]: So that is kind of one of the pressures that you sort of have to balance.

01:44:21.620 --> 01:44:28.780
[Amit Varma]: Now, you know, one is this summation broadly correct in its necessarily simplistic way.

01:44:28.780 --> 01:44:30.580
[Amit Varma]: And two, what then is inflation targeting?

01:44:30.580 --> 01:44:34.200
[Amit Varma]: Like, is there an ideal rate of inflation that we should have?

01:44:34.200 --> 01:44:37.360
[Amit Varma]: What is the role of a central bank here?

01:44:37.360 --> 01:44:42.780
[Amit Varma]: Can you then demystify all of this that why did this become such an important thing?

01:44:42.780 --> 01:44:50.720
[Guest]: Yeah, so let's say that we have an economy that tries to target the exchange rate.

01:44:50.720 --> 01:44:52.260
[Guest]: It doesn't care about inflation.

01:44:52.260 --> 01:44:53.780
[Guest]: It targets the exchange rate.

01:44:53.780 --> 01:44:57.380
[Guest]: It wants a stable rupee.

01:44:57.380 --> 01:45:04.020
[Guest]: And as a consequence, we do what we did, let's say, what Bimal Jalan did in the Asian crisis,

01:45:04.020 --> 01:45:08.460
[Guest]: that when there was pressure on the rupee to depreciate, he hiked up interest rates

01:45:08.460 --> 01:45:14.500
[Guest]: by 200 basis point on 16th of January 1999 on one single day.

01:45:14.500 --> 01:45:20.060
[Guest]: Similarly, we do what we did during the period of the Tipper Tantrum that we thought the

01:45:20.060 --> 01:45:22.420
[Guest]: rupee is weak or will weaken.

01:45:22.420 --> 01:45:26.200
[Guest]: So we hiked short-term rates, tighten liquidity.

01:45:26.200 --> 01:45:32.140
[Guest]: What we're doing then is that let's assume that at that time, which is true in this case,

01:45:32.140 --> 01:45:36.380
[Guest]: but let's assume at that time the economy is not doing very well.

01:45:36.380 --> 01:45:40.580
[Guest]: Then what you end up doing is making it worse.

01:45:40.580 --> 01:45:46.540
[Guest]: Because the economy was already weak and because of that, perhaps, you know, you got this pressure

01:45:46.540 --> 01:45:47.540
[Guest]: on the rupee.

01:45:47.540 --> 01:45:53.940
[Guest]: Now, we were repeatedly seeing episodes of that happen, that, you know, the economy needed

01:45:53.940 --> 01:45:54.940
[Guest]: something.

01:45:54.940 --> 01:46:00.220
[Guest]: Okay, so your business cycle conditions were such that we needed an accommodative or lose

01:46:00.220 --> 01:46:01.940
[Guest]: monetary policy.

01:46:01.940 --> 01:46:07.740
[Guest]: But what happened instead was that because you were trying to defend the rupee, you went

01:46:07.740 --> 01:46:10.180
[Guest]: and hiked rates.

01:46:10.180 --> 01:46:17.100
[Guest]: What that does is actually makes your policy pro-cyclical.

01:46:17.100 --> 01:46:21.860
[Guest]: You were already going down and it makes you go down further.

01:46:21.860 --> 01:46:25.340
[Amit Varma]: Because there's less spending and so on.

01:46:25.340 --> 01:46:31.380
[Guest]: Because of what you described just now that when interest rates are higher, so you've

01:46:31.380 --> 01:46:34.080
[Guest]: hiked rates to defend the rupee, right?

01:46:34.080 --> 01:46:37.580
[Guest]: But when rates are higher, people borrow less, people spend less, you know.

01:46:37.580 --> 01:46:43.060
[Guest]: So that's why rates get raised when inflation goes up or when, as we just talked about,

01:46:43.060 --> 01:46:45.340
[Guest]: the US economy overheating.

01:46:45.340 --> 01:46:48.580
[Guest]: So when it is overheating, the Fed may raise interest rates.

01:46:48.580 --> 01:46:52.820
[Guest]: So when there's too much demand in the economy, you try to bring it down.

01:46:52.820 --> 01:46:55.460
[Guest]: So we were seeing a lot of that happen.

01:46:55.460 --> 01:46:59.620
[Guest]: So in the Indian context, why did inflation targeting make sense?

01:46:59.620 --> 01:47:01.620
[Guest]: And why did the government go ahead with it?

01:47:01.620 --> 01:47:05.780
[Guest]: It's not because, you know, some of us write about things, we write about many things.

01:47:05.780 --> 01:47:13.580
[Guest]: But why it made sense was that repeatedly there were these episodes when you were doing

01:47:13.580 --> 01:47:19.780
[Guest]: something which was actually bad for the wider economy as a whole.

01:47:19.780 --> 01:47:23.340
[Guest]: So while it might have given you rupee stabilization.

01:47:23.340 --> 01:47:24.980
[Guest]: So that was the choice.

01:47:24.980 --> 01:47:30.020
[Guest]: The third choice, which would have been to close the capital account, we don't have that

01:47:30.020 --> 01:47:31.140
[Guest]: choice anymore.

01:47:31.140 --> 01:47:32.900
[Guest]: So we are such a global economy.

01:47:32.900 --> 01:47:38.260
[Guest]: And anyway, even if we try to close some accounts, money finds a way to move around.

01:47:38.260 --> 01:47:40.220
[Guest]: So we don't want to go there.

01:47:40.220 --> 01:47:45.420
[Guest]: Though sometimes, you know, they do try to impose some capital controls, gold, this,

01:47:45.420 --> 01:47:46.420
[Guest]: that and the other.

01:47:46.420 --> 01:47:48.540
[Guest]: That tendency is very much there.

01:47:48.540 --> 01:47:49.540
[Guest]: Okay.

01:47:49.540 --> 01:47:53.380
[Guest]: But as you said earlier, the mindset of trying to control is very much there.

01:47:53.380 --> 01:47:57.140
[Guest]: But let's just say that, you know, we put that aside because that's not going to solve

01:47:57.140 --> 01:47:58.140
[Guest]: your problem.

01:47:58.140 --> 01:48:03.660
[Guest]: So then you have a choice between these two things, between trying to stabilize the currency,

01:48:03.660 --> 01:48:09.100
[Guest]: which could be pro cyclical, if your economy is on a decline and your hiking rates, you're

01:48:09.100 --> 01:48:10.780
[Guest]: just doing the wrong thing.

01:48:10.780 --> 01:48:16.820
[Guest]: And the other is that you respond to the business cycle conditions in the economy.

01:48:16.820 --> 01:48:24.340
[Guest]: So while we say inflation targeting, but actually inflation doesn't happen on some island on

01:48:24.340 --> 01:48:25.780
[Guest]: its own.

01:48:25.780 --> 01:48:30.940
[Guest]: Inflation is happening when there is excess demand in the economy.

01:48:30.940 --> 01:48:34.140
[Guest]: And that is happening when the economy is on upswing.

01:48:34.140 --> 01:48:37.820
[Guest]: So what you're really trying to do is to stabilize the business cycle.

01:48:37.820 --> 01:48:41.620
[Guest]: You're trying to do counter cyclical monetary policy.

01:48:41.620 --> 01:48:46.280
[Guest]: That's the essence of why inflation targeting makes sense.

01:48:46.280 --> 01:48:50.580
[Amit Varma]: So now a further question, because from the term, it would seem that there is an optimal

01:48:50.580 --> 01:48:52.500
[Amit Varma]: rate of inflation you have to maintain.

01:48:52.500 --> 01:48:54.540
[Amit Varma]: So is there an optimal rate of inflation?

01:48:54.540 --> 01:48:55.900
[Amit Varma]: And why is it optimal?

01:48:55.900 --> 01:48:58.140
[Amit Varma]: And how does one arrive at it?

01:48:58.140 --> 01:48:59.140
[Amit Varma]: And so on.

01:48:59.140 --> 01:49:00.140
[Guest]: Broader question.

01:49:00.140 --> 01:49:03.540
[Guest]: So I think Raghu was the governor at that time.

01:49:03.540 --> 01:49:11.820
[Guest]: And this one was chosen as 2% above the inflation target in advanced economies.

01:49:11.820 --> 01:49:17.500
[Guest]: So advanced economies have roughly 2% and you want a positive inflation rate because

01:49:17.500 --> 01:49:22.500
[Guest]: you want relative prices to be able to move and you can't really have disinflation.

01:49:22.500 --> 01:49:25.180
[Guest]: So that's painful for too many people.

01:49:25.180 --> 01:49:27.700
[Guest]: So the advanced economies have chosen 2%.

01:49:27.700 --> 01:49:33.900
[Guest]: Now if you kind of think, Bilasa Samuelson, that you're getting a productivity improvement

01:49:33.900 --> 01:49:39.460
[Guest]: because you're an emerging economy, so you can have an inflation, you want to choose

01:49:39.460 --> 01:49:45.300
[Guest]: your target, your productivity improvement at a long term average rate of 2%.

01:49:45.300 --> 01:49:50.520
[Guest]: So your currency could kind of stay where it is roughly stable.

01:49:50.520 --> 01:49:57.540
[Guest]: You choose an inflation rate of 2% above the inflation target of advanced economies.

01:49:57.540 --> 01:50:00.020
[Guest]: So that's where that number came from.

01:50:00.020 --> 01:50:06.260
[Guest]: But the second number, which is our own number, is this 2 to 6.

01:50:06.260 --> 01:50:10.660
[Guest]: The 2 to 6 is the band around the 4% target.

01:50:10.660 --> 01:50:17.660
[Guest]: And that's really because one, inflation targeting was something so new and very few people really

01:50:17.660 --> 01:50:24.300
[Guest]: understood whether you'll actually be able to get to 4% inflation by moving around interest

01:50:24.300 --> 01:50:25.300
[Guest]: rates.

01:50:25.300 --> 01:50:29.240
[Guest]: And second, because monetary policy transmission is very, very weak.

01:50:29.240 --> 01:50:35.360
[Guest]: You don't have competitive, well-functioning bond markets and banks that would actually

01:50:35.360 --> 01:50:37.020
[Guest]: do this transmission.

01:50:37.020 --> 01:50:42.260
[Guest]: So in the absence of a well-functioning monetary policy transmission, you don't want a very

01:50:42.260 --> 01:50:47.180
[Guest]: tight target because then you would have to hike rates around, you have to jack them around

01:50:47.180 --> 01:50:48.980
[Guest]: up and down depending on the inflation.

01:50:48.980 --> 01:50:52.980
[Guest]: So what you want to do is get a bit of flexibility there.

01:50:52.980 --> 01:50:53.980
[Amit Varma]: Makes sense.

01:50:53.980 --> 01:50:56.140
[Amit Varma]: Let's now come to the current time.

01:50:56.140 --> 01:51:00.980
[Amit Varma]: Before COVID struck, let's say maybe February last year, before COVID struck, if you were

01:51:00.980 --> 01:51:06.580
[Amit Varma]: to sort of talk about the state of the economy then, you know, not just in a static way,

01:51:06.580 --> 01:51:11.020
[Amit Varma]: but as you know, part of different trends that have been playing out, how would you

01:51:11.020 --> 01:51:13.020
[Amit Varma]: then sort of sum that up?

01:51:13.020 --> 01:51:17.660
[Amit Varma]: Like for example, I've done episodes on the credit crisis with Arvind, Viral, various

01:51:17.660 --> 01:51:18.660
[Amit Varma]: people.

01:51:18.660 --> 01:51:20.400
[Amit Varma]: And you know, what was the state of that?

01:51:20.400 --> 01:51:22.660
[Amit Varma]: What was the state of our economy generally?

01:51:22.660 --> 01:51:25.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, what did it look like before COVID struck?

01:51:25.000 --> 01:51:29.660
[Amit Varma]: Because I think it's important also to kind of think about that before we get down to

01:51:29.660 --> 01:51:33.740
[Amit Varma]: talking about the impact of COVID, like I'd done an episode with Vivek Kaul on the Indian

01:51:33.740 --> 01:51:35.180
[Amit Varma]: economy in 2019.

01:51:35.180 --> 01:51:39.460
[Amit Varma]: And I remember, you know, everything we had to say was extremely bleak anyway.

01:51:39.460 --> 01:51:44.100
[Amit Varma]: It feels like, you know, things were just going downhill, things look pretty bad.

01:51:44.100 --> 01:51:46.740
[Amit Varma]: What was your sense of it at the time?

01:51:46.740 --> 01:51:48.920
[Guest]: I was worrying about two things.

01:51:48.920 --> 01:51:53.380
[Guest]: I was worrying about the fact that investment had still not picked up.

01:51:53.380 --> 01:51:59.380
[Guest]: And second, about the non-performing assets in the banking system.

01:51:59.380 --> 01:52:05.900
[Guest]: And that basically, I thought that this was a time when we should start moving towards

01:52:05.900 --> 01:52:08.580
[Guest]: privatization of public sector banks.

01:52:08.580 --> 01:52:15.900
[Guest]: And you know, some of the stuff I was writing was that unless we move away from this public

01:52:15.900 --> 01:52:22.820
[Guest]: sector banking setup that we somehow seem to be stuck with, we will actually not be

01:52:22.820 --> 01:52:24.180
[Guest]: able to recover.

01:52:24.180 --> 01:52:30.020
[Guest]: Third, that we have not done the financial sector reforms that are needed for us to be

01:52:30.020 --> 01:52:33.020
[Guest]: able to get back on track.

01:52:33.020 --> 01:52:37.220
[Guest]: You know, so the kind of things that need to be done are, one, a competitive banking

01:52:37.220 --> 01:52:43.060
[Guest]: system, which for me means either you reduce your shareholdership or you give a lot of

01:52:43.060 --> 01:52:45.140
[Guest]: private sector bank licenses.

01:52:45.140 --> 01:52:46.620
[Guest]: So that also brings competition.

01:52:46.620 --> 01:52:53.380
[Guest]: And you know, the telecom model or the aviation model where you don't, you know, you don't

01:52:53.380 --> 01:52:55.780
[Guest]: want to privatize them for whatever reason.

01:52:55.780 --> 01:53:00.740
[Guest]: The unions will make trouble or then give more licenses, but at least bring competition

01:53:00.740 --> 01:53:02.220
[Guest]: into the sector.

01:53:02.220 --> 01:53:07.020
[Guest]: So I thought that was a difficult enough agenda.

01:53:07.020 --> 01:53:14.780
[Guest]: But I mean, that was mainly the investment, credit, the shape of the banking sector were

01:53:14.780 --> 01:53:16.140
[Amit Varma]: what were worrying me.

01:53:16.140 --> 01:53:19.780
[Amit Varma]: You know, on a tangent, since we are reaching COVID, I came across this interesting paper

01:53:19.780 --> 01:53:24.580
[Amit Varma]: you wrote with Supriya Krishnan called Health and Disaster Risk Management in India, which

01:53:24.580 --> 01:53:29.460
[Amit Varma]: was published in February 2020, last year before the pandemic struck, where you're doing

01:53:29.460 --> 01:53:33.580
[Amit Varma]: various things, you're assessing our public health infrastructure and blah, blah, blah.

01:53:33.580 --> 01:53:37.820
[Amit Varma]: So to what extent, and you also talk about communicable diseases in it and so on.

01:53:37.820 --> 01:53:42.620
[Amit Varma]: So to what extent did, like, were there any new revelations or did things play out kind

01:53:42.620 --> 01:53:48.060
[Amit Varma]: of the way you expected that we were nowhere close to being prepared?

01:53:48.060 --> 01:53:53.380
[Guest]: I think even if we had been optimally prepared, according to whatever we were measuring in

01:53:53.380 --> 01:53:58.540
[Guest]: that paper, we would still have been unprepared because, you know, I don't think anybody can

01:53:58.540 --> 01:54:02.660
[Guest]: be prepared for this magnitude of so many people falling ill.

01:54:02.660 --> 01:54:07.780
[Guest]: You know, you're not going to ever have so many doctors and so many people, so many nurses

01:54:07.780 --> 01:54:12.980
[Guest]: and so many hospitals, because otherwise they'll be unprofitable and lying vacant for decades,

01:54:12.980 --> 01:54:13.980
[Guest]: you know.

01:54:13.980 --> 01:54:19.900
[Guest]: So some arrangements, you don't have arrangements for a tenfold increase in oxygen demand.

01:54:19.900 --> 01:54:22.260
[Guest]: You don't have arrangements for this.

01:54:22.260 --> 01:54:28.540
[Guest]: So I mean, that was taking into a, you know, just assuming a normal, not a pandemic like

01:54:28.540 --> 01:54:33.300
[Guest]: this, but we couldn't have been prepared.

01:54:33.300 --> 01:54:38.140
[Guest]: At least I felt that even if we'd done everything we could, we couldn't have been prepared for

01:54:38.140 --> 01:54:42.820
[Guest]: this kind of magnitude of the crisis, health crisis.

01:54:42.820 --> 01:54:47.500
[Amit Varma]: And given what we know in hindsight about how it was handled, assume that we use that

01:54:47.500 --> 01:54:51.540
[Amit Varma]: knowledge and we can go back in a time machine and do everything right, right?

01:54:51.540 --> 01:54:53.660
[Amit Varma]: So we end up with the best case scenario.

01:54:53.660 --> 01:54:55.260
[Amit Varma]: What do you think that would have been?

01:54:55.260 --> 01:55:01.540
[Guest]: I mean, we would have tested more, if we could have tested more, we could have, we would

01:55:01.540 --> 01:55:08.260
[Guest]: have done local lockdowns more because we didn't understand what the full implication

01:55:08.260 --> 01:55:15.060
[Guest]: of a national lockdown would be, we would have pre-ordered vaccines when they started,

01:55:15.060 --> 01:55:20.820
[Guest]: when people started working on vaccines, not even when they did trial, phase one trials,

01:55:20.820 --> 01:55:28.420
[Guest]: but, you know, we would have pre-ordered vaccines and, you know, prepared hospitals so that

01:55:28.420 --> 01:55:33.340
[Guest]: in case that we still get the disease, but you know, all this is with the benefit of

01:55:33.340 --> 01:55:34.340
[Guest]: hindsight.

01:55:34.340 --> 01:55:41.620
[Guest]: I must admit that neither I, nor any of the big critics that I hear talk about this, were

01:55:41.620 --> 01:55:45.500
[Guest]: writing that, how much pre-ordering of vaccines have you done?

01:55:45.500 --> 01:55:50.300
[Guest]: On the contrary, one heard people say, oh, Covaxin is not tested, why are you allowing

01:55:50.300 --> 01:55:51.300
[Guest]: it?

01:55:51.300 --> 01:55:53.780
[Guest]: And why are you buying it?

01:55:53.780 --> 01:55:58.740
[Guest]: So with the benefit of hindsight, one can say a lot of things, but if I were to be honest

01:55:58.740 --> 01:56:04.460
[Guest]: and say that would I have figured out all this, then I don't think I would have figured

01:56:04.460 --> 01:56:05.460
[Guest]: out all this then.

01:56:05.460 --> 01:56:06.460
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:56:06.460 --> 01:56:09.700
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you know, there's this really nice quote I came across where someone said that

01:56:09.700 --> 01:56:13.580
[Amit Varma]: if you act optimally, then before a pandemic, it will always seem like you are doing too

01:56:13.580 --> 01:56:14.580
[Amit Varma]: much.

01:56:14.580 --> 01:56:16.340
[Amit Varma]: You know, that's what it will seem like before.

01:56:16.340 --> 01:56:19.580
[Amit Varma]: And after a pandemic, it will always seem like you did too little.

01:56:19.580 --> 01:56:25.420
[Amit Varma]: It's just, you know, we are kind of in this very tough spot, but looking at the pandemic

01:56:25.420 --> 01:56:30.020
[Amit Varma]: as it kind of proceeded, I mean, obviously there are disasters at various levels like

01:56:30.020 --> 01:56:32.740
[Amit Varma]: the humanitarian disaster, and let's not even go into that.

01:56:32.740 --> 01:56:38.100
[Amit Varma]: But as an economist, when you're thinking of what is the economic impact of this, number

01:56:38.100 --> 01:56:44.220
[Amit Varma]: one, and number two, when you're thinking of what can we do to ameliorate it with whatever

01:56:44.220 --> 01:56:49.360
[Amit Varma]: limited resources we have, then tell me a little bit about what that kind of thinking

01:56:49.360 --> 01:56:54.680
[Amit Varma]: is like, like what kind of data gives you the fullest possible picture of this?

01:56:54.680 --> 01:56:58.340
[Amit Varma]: It appears to me that, you know, when the first lockdown happened, all the migrant labor

01:56:58.340 --> 01:56:59.500
[Amit Varma]: is going back.

01:56:59.500 --> 01:57:02.740
[Amit Varma]: You don't know what the sentiment is, you don't know how many of them are coming back.

01:57:02.740 --> 01:57:07.060
[Amit Varma]: Maybe there is some MNREGS data, which suddenly shows a spike, and you know that all these

01:57:07.060 --> 01:57:10.060
[Amit Varma]: people have come back from the cities, there's no work and blah, blah.

01:57:10.060 --> 01:57:13.780
[Amit Varma]: But you don't know the longer term sentiment and how it's going to play out when all these

01:57:13.780 --> 01:57:14.780
[Amit Varma]: people die.

01:57:14.780 --> 01:57:18.520
[Amit Varma]: Number one, what we are seeing today is that deaths are massively underreported.

01:57:18.520 --> 01:57:22.260
[Amit Varma]: You don't know how those deaths will affect things going forward.

01:57:22.260 --> 01:57:23.560
[Amit Varma]: So many things we don't know.

01:57:23.560 --> 01:57:26.220
[Amit Varma]: So how do you begin to make sense of what is going wrong?

01:57:26.220 --> 01:57:31.220
[Amit Varma]: And then how do you begin to make sense of what to do about it?

01:57:31.220 --> 01:57:36.460
[Guest]: Looking at CMI household survey data, the surveys are still continuing, does give you

01:57:36.460 --> 01:57:37.460
[Guest]: some sense.

01:57:37.460 --> 01:57:41.220
[Guest]: So they talk about, they ask you, are you looking for a job?

01:57:41.220 --> 01:57:43.460
[Guest]: So that's labor force participation.

01:57:43.460 --> 01:57:45.540
[Guest]: They ask you, are you employed?

01:57:45.540 --> 01:57:47.380
[Guest]: So that's the employment rate.

01:57:47.380 --> 01:57:50.280
[Guest]: They also ask you how many members of the family there are.

01:57:50.280 --> 01:57:54.060
[Guest]: So if there are some missing, which were there, so it's the same set of households, same set

01:57:54.060 --> 01:57:59.680
[Guest]: of, I think, 200,000 plus households that are interviewed three times a year.

01:57:59.680 --> 01:58:04.500
[Guest]: So you can make out, because it's the same household and you're going back to the household,

01:58:04.500 --> 01:58:12.300
[Guest]: so you can get some idea of the missing people there, or you also get data on expenditure

01:58:12.300 --> 01:58:18.420
[Guest]: that will tell you whether people are, so if they're eating less or spending less on

01:58:18.420 --> 01:58:20.180
[Guest]: what are they spending less.

01:58:20.180 --> 01:58:24.420
[Guest]: So the items on which they spend have been changing.

01:58:24.420 --> 01:58:30.260
[Guest]: And so that's something that some of us do look at.

01:58:30.260 --> 01:58:32.660
[Guest]: And of course, things are bad.

01:58:32.660 --> 01:58:40.660
[Guest]: I mean, I don't, the data is reflecting whatever that people have lost their jobs and many

01:58:40.660 --> 01:58:45.500
[Guest]: are dropping out of the labor force, but then that is something that one would expect.

01:58:45.500 --> 01:58:51.980
[Guest]: So that, you know, if that answers the data question, the question on what would you do?

01:58:51.980 --> 01:58:59.240
[Guest]: I mean, other than vaccinating and trying to do COVID appropriate behavior and not doing

01:58:59.240 --> 01:59:06.900
[Guest]: the non-essential things that would hurt everyone, I'm not sure what else we can do.

01:59:06.900 --> 01:59:12.740
[Guest]: I think the way out is to vaccinate, to have COVID appropriate behavior, to let people

01:59:12.740 --> 01:59:18.300
[Guest]: come back to work when you feel that it's safe, and by now people are scared enough.

01:59:18.300 --> 01:59:26.160
[Guest]: So people who used to be, you know, I mean, out of the people who we've lost among friends

01:59:26.160 --> 01:59:31.600
[Guest]: and family, a lot of them were refusing to take the vaccine, but today their families

01:59:31.600 --> 01:59:33.420
[Guest]: are queuing up for vaccines.

01:59:33.420 --> 01:59:40.780
[Guest]: So that vaccine, that hesitancy, the resistance to vaccine has gone away, at least, I mean,

01:59:40.780 --> 01:59:45.300
[Guest]: I don't have data on that, but the demand for vaccines has increased.

01:59:45.300 --> 01:59:52.460
[Guest]: So the gap may actually increase because as this spreads, till the supply comes back.

01:59:52.460 --> 01:59:54.220
[Guest]: So I think that's what you can do.

01:59:54.220 --> 01:59:58.880
[Guest]: So that at least people can come back to economic activity.

01:59:58.880 --> 02:00:06.220
[Guest]: You have to allow them to come back and the economy will, I think, you know, people who

02:00:06.220 --> 02:00:10.780
[Guest]: either had COVID or had a vaccine will be able to get back to work pretty soon.

02:00:10.780 --> 02:00:16.380
[Guest]: I mean, those who are not, you know, suffering from some of the ill effects other than that,

02:00:16.380 --> 02:00:19.980
[Guest]: many will be, most will be able to come back to work pretty soon.

02:00:19.980 --> 02:00:23.820
[Amit Varma]: And in terms of economic policy at the government level, is there something special that the

02:00:23.820 --> 02:00:27.460
[Amit Varma]: government can do that one would not recommend that it does otherwise?

02:00:27.460 --> 02:00:32.500
[Amit Varma]: Like, for example, people speak about put a special stimulus out there or whatever,

02:00:32.500 --> 02:00:35.940
[Amit Varma]: you know, fiscal policy, monetary policy.

02:00:35.940 --> 02:00:38.500
[Amit Varma]: What is your sense of what can and should be done there?

02:00:38.500 --> 02:00:43.780
[Amit Varma]: Like, is there something that should be done now that would not otherwise have been necessary

02:00:43.780 --> 02:00:45.700
[Guest]: in normal times?

02:00:45.700 --> 02:00:48.900
[Guest]: So maybe you can cut taxes and borrow.

02:00:48.900 --> 02:00:52.460
[Guest]: You can cut import duties that might boost your exports.

02:00:52.460 --> 02:00:58.900
[Guest]: You can cut taxes so whoever's having to pay an 18% GST on something gets a relief.

02:00:58.900 --> 02:01:02.900
[Guest]: And the government, I'm not saying it can borrow too much because, you know, it doesn't

02:01:02.900 --> 02:01:04.540
[Guest]: have much fiscal space.

02:01:04.540 --> 02:01:11.460
[Guest]: But to some extent, this is the way to provide relief, rather than to try to find who all

02:01:11.460 --> 02:01:12.740
[Guest]: to pay to.

02:01:12.740 --> 02:01:17.900
[Guest]: I would just say cutting taxes gives everybody relief across the board.

02:01:17.900 --> 02:01:22.900
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you know, in fact, I saw this very interesting Elonomics episode of yours where you spoke

02:01:22.900 --> 02:01:26.900
[Amit Varma]: about the absurdity of cutting the personal income tax while raising GST.

02:01:26.900 --> 02:01:32.140
[Amit Varma]: And you're like, whatever, you know, it doesn't, it's not kind of remotely coherent.

02:01:32.140 --> 02:01:35.340
[Amit Varma]: And of course, the idea of cutting taxes is you leave the money in the hands of the people,

02:01:35.340 --> 02:01:40.940
[Amit Varma]: you know, which leads me to sort of this interesting question about how so and this is again a

02:01:40.940 --> 02:01:46.260
[Amit Varma]: sort of a mindset question where so many people in government will often behave as if one

02:01:46.260 --> 02:01:51.380
[Amit Varma]: of the aims or one of the metrics of a healthy economy is how much your tax collections have

02:01:51.380 --> 02:01:52.380
[Amit Varma]: gone up.

02:01:52.380 --> 02:01:56.860
[Amit Varma]: And I'm not sure that's such a great metric because, you know, that tells you something

02:01:56.860 --> 02:02:00.340
[Amit Varma]: about the health of the state and the state is, of course, a predatory state.

02:02:00.340 --> 02:02:02.020
[Amit Varma]: So do you really want it to be healthy?

02:02:02.020 --> 02:02:04.740
[Amit Varma]: You know, while your focus should be on the health of society.

02:02:04.740 --> 02:02:08.940
[Amit Varma]: So is this something that you have thoughts on?

02:02:08.940 --> 02:02:14.660
[Guest]: Sometimes I wonder, when I look at bureaucrats, I wonder that is the way to increase the tax

02:02:14.660 --> 02:02:18.500
[Guest]: GDP ratio done through reducing the denominator?

02:02:18.500 --> 02:02:27.420
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah, they don't care, they don't care, they don't care that you impose taxes that

02:02:27.420 --> 02:02:30.300
[Guest]: are actually going to reduce investment.

02:02:30.300 --> 02:02:34.220
[Guest]: So you do some retrospective tax, right, you'll get some X crore rupees.

02:02:34.220 --> 02:02:38.420
[Guest]: But you end up reducing investment, you end up reducing GDP.

02:02:38.420 --> 02:02:43.220
[Guest]: And that's how your, you know, tax to GDP ratio may look better.

02:02:43.220 --> 02:02:47.420
[Guest]: But I mean, I'm kidding, I'm, you know, this is the...

02:02:47.420 --> 02:02:51.860
[Unknown]: You know, you're kidding, but you're not really kidding.

02:02:51.860 --> 02:02:54.100
[Guest]: I mean, basically, they don't care.

02:02:54.100 --> 02:02:58.860
[Guest]: I think what's happened is that the tax administration is in charge of tax policy.

02:02:58.860 --> 02:03:03.540
[Guest]: On a more serious note, that separation is essential.

02:03:03.540 --> 02:03:10.660
[Guest]: Because the job of tax administration is given what we have, we have to, you know, collect

02:03:10.660 --> 02:03:15.100
[Guest]: taxes without too much cost, and there has to be improved compliance and so on.

02:03:15.100 --> 02:03:23.460
[Guest]: But the role of tax policy is to make taxes such that we improve output, we improve productivity,

02:03:23.460 --> 02:03:30.420
[Guest]: we don't put, you know, deadweight loss on the economy, we don't put extra burden on the economy.

02:03:30.420 --> 02:03:37.740
[Guest]: Because we don't have much tax policy thinking outside of tax administration.

02:03:37.740 --> 02:03:44.500
[Guest]: I think that the way tax policy gets made in India, it's blind to the impact on GDP.

02:03:44.500 --> 02:03:50.660
[Guest]: We started this conversation talking about, you know, retrospective taxes, your interview

02:03:50.660 --> 02:03:57.780
[Guest]: with Pooja, and how that actually turned the economy around, we are 10 years later, maybe

02:03:57.780 --> 02:04:03.300
[Guest]: a little more than 10 years later, we are still suffering the impact of trying to collect

02:04:03.300 --> 02:04:06.140
[Guest]: just this much of more of taxes.

02:04:06.140 --> 02:04:08.500
[Guest]: So I have very strong views on that.

02:04:08.500 --> 02:04:10.300
[Amit Varma]: But that's kind of...

02:04:10.300 --> 02:04:14.820
[Amit Varma]: No, like you said, it's completely nuts that the tax administration people should have

02:04:14.820 --> 02:04:19.700
[Amit Varma]: so much influence on tax policy, because obviously, they'll want more money to spend, who kind

02:04:19.700 --> 02:04:20.700
[Amit Varma]: of wouldn't.

02:04:20.700 --> 02:04:24.140
[Amit Varma]: And I'll bring you into another issue you've written about, you know, a couple of episodes

02:04:24.140 --> 02:04:28.460
[Amit Varma]: ago, I had Karthik Mulyadharan on my show, The Economist, and we were talking health

02:04:28.460 --> 02:04:29.460
[Amit Varma]: care policy.

02:04:29.460 --> 02:04:32.460
[Amit Varma]: But one of the digressions we took was the petrol taxes.

02:04:32.460 --> 02:04:36.980
[Amit Varma]: And I said, the high petrol taxes are a bad thing, because they affect the common person,

02:04:36.980 --> 02:04:38.820
[Amit Varma]: inflationary effect, blah, blah, blah.

02:04:38.820 --> 02:04:41.980
[Amit Varma]: And he was defending it from a public finance point of view, saying that if the government

02:04:41.980 --> 02:04:44.980
[Amit Varma]: collects taxes, that's how I would like them to collect it.

02:04:44.980 --> 02:04:47.180
[Amit Varma]: What's your view on this?

02:04:47.180 --> 02:04:49.620
[Guest]: So I'm very conflicted.

02:04:49.620 --> 02:04:56.060
[Guest]: On the one hand, I think, you know, it's a carbon tax, it reduces your consumption of,

02:04:56.060 --> 02:04:58.160
[Guest]: you know, carbon fuels.

02:04:58.160 --> 02:05:04.180
[Guest]: And so, in one sense, I think that, you know, I should not be saying anything.

02:05:04.180 --> 02:05:09.420
[Guest]: But on the other hand, I feel that in the period when oil prices were declining, the

02:05:09.420 --> 02:05:14.740
[Guest]: FISC became too dependent on these taxes.

02:05:14.740 --> 02:05:23.100
[Guest]: And you know, today, you're paying so much more taxes than the actual fuel, it hurts.

02:05:23.100 --> 02:05:28.500
[Guest]: And today, the FISC cannot do away with these taxes, because they've become too dependent

02:05:28.500 --> 02:05:29.980
[Guest]: on them.

02:05:29.980 --> 02:05:35.180
[Guest]: And in that perspective, as you know, an economist, I would say that I don't think this is good

02:05:35.180 --> 02:05:40.260
[Guest]: public finance when you're too dependent on any one kind of tax on this, apart from everything

02:05:40.260 --> 02:05:41.820
[Guest]: that you have said.

02:05:41.820 --> 02:05:45.460
[Guest]: So but you know, because it's a carbon tax, I'm a little conflicted.

02:05:45.460 --> 02:05:49.500
[Guest]: If this was on gold, I might say something else.

02:05:49.500 --> 02:05:51.740
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no.

02:05:51.740 --> 02:05:55.820
[Amit Varma]: And just to kind of give perspective to those listeners, you know, after 2014, Modi got

02:05:55.820 --> 02:05:59.420
[Amit Varma]: this massive bonanza when oil prices, global oil prices went down.

02:05:59.420 --> 02:06:02.620
[Amit Varma]: And he could have chosen to let petrol prices in India come down.

02:06:02.620 --> 02:06:05.620
[Amit Varma]: And that benefit would have been passed on to people, not just people who drive cars,

02:06:05.620 --> 02:06:09.420
[Amit Varma]: by the way, but petrol prices affect everything, everything would have become cheaper.

02:06:09.420 --> 02:06:11.500
[Amit Varma]: But instead, they just raise the taxes.

02:06:11.500 --> 02:06:15.200
[Amit Varma]: So it seemed to the common person that okay, petrol prices haven't really gone up.

02:06:15.200 --> 02:06:18.300
[Amit Varma]: But we were just you know, the tax became a larger percentage of that.

02:06:18.300 --> 02:06:20.700
[Amit Varma]: And now the taxes only go up, they don't go down.

02:06:20.700 --> 02:06:22.220
[Amit Varma]: So that's something to think about.

02:06:22.220 --> 02:06:24.180
[Amit Varma]: I'll link to an article you wrote on this.

02:06:24.180 --> 02:06:27.580
[Amit Varma]: So to be honest, right, when I asked you, I did know that you would kind of come out

02:06:27.580 --> 02:06:31.740
[Amit Varma]: on my side on this, I will send that link to Karthik.

02:06:31.740 --> 02:06:37.420
[Amit Varma]: So a final big question before we end up by talking about the COVID scenario also, you

02:06:37.420 --> 02:06:43.100
[Amit Varma]: know, when we kind of look at the Indian economy, like whenever I talk about problems in India,

02:06:43.100 --> 02:06:49.660
[Amit Varma]: whether it's in agriculture, in whatever, within that bigger problem, there is a subset

02:06:49.660 --> 02:06:53.020
[Amit Varma]: that is even worse, which is the role of women in it, right.

02:06:53.020 --> 02:06:56.860
[Amit Varma]: And I'd done an episode with Namita Bhandare on the women's participation in the labor

02:06:56.860 --> 02:07:01.860
[Amit Varma]: force, where she pointed out that it's actually gone down over the last sort of decade and

02:07:01.860 --> 02:07:06.740
[Amit Varma]: a half that there are less women in percentage terms working today than was the case.

02:07:06.740 --> 02:07:10.260
[Amit Varma]: And even before COVID, you would expect the opposite to be the case, because the economy

02:07:10.260 --> 02:07:12.940
[Amit Varma]: has been growing, everything is fine.

02:07:12.940 --> 02:07:14.700
[Amit Varma]: Why are less women working?

02:07:14.700 --> 02:07:19.740
[Amit Varma]: And it also seems to me that there's a massive loss there, the fact that of course, I mean,

02:07:19.740 --> 02:07:25.260
[Amit Varma]: some of it is cultural issues, that, you know, we have this very misogynistic backward view

02:07:25.260 --> 02:07:28.740
[Amit Varma]: of women that a woman's places in the kitchen and blah, blah, blah, and some of those are

02:07:28.740 --> 02:07:29.980
[Amit Varma]: cultural issues.

02:07:29.980 --> 02:07:35.220
[Amit Varma]: But there is a massive loss in terms of, you know, just productivity, human capital, all

02:07:35.220 --> 02:07:39.460
[Amit Varma]: of that, the fact that half our people are almost, you know, treated differently.

02:07:39.460 --> 02:07:44.540
[Amit Varma]: And you know, given this kind of inferior status, and therefore inferior opportunities.

02:07:44.540 --> 02:07:47.020
[Amit Varma]: So what is your sense of that?

02:07:47.020 --> 02:07:52.220
[Amit Varma]: Like, is there any way to kind of quantify, say, whether it's the unpaid labor of women

02:07:52.220 --> 02:07:56.300
[Amit Varma]: or quantify the opportunity cost that what if, you know, women were getting the same

02:07:56.300 --> 02:07:57.820
[Amit Varma]: kind of opportunities?

02:07:57.820 --> 02:08:01.620
[Amit Varma]: And also, when you look at the general drift, what is the tendency?

02:08:01.620 --> 02:08:05.180
[Amit Varma]: Is there reason to hope in this in this regard?

02:08:05.180 --> 02:08:12.940
[Guest]: So I think one of the big factors is the economy, that when employment doesn't grow fast enough,

02:08:12.940 --> 02:08:17.060
[Guest]: then within a family, it is the male who takes up a job rather than the female.

02:08:17.060 --> 02:08:21.500
[Guest]: So if one of them is going to be able to go out and work, then who goes out to work?

02:08:21.500 --> 02:08:25.740
[Guest]: So she does the childcare, she does the homework, and the male goes out to work.

02:08:25.740 --> 02:08:31.420
[Guest]: So the, you know, aggregate rate of growth of jobs, if that slows down, it is going to,

02:08:31.420 --> 02:08:35.220
[Guest]: in my opinion, it also impacts how many women go out to work.

02:08:35.220 --> 02:08:38.980
[Guest]: The second thing that has been happening here, so there have, you know, this is an issue

02:08:38.980 --> 02:08:41.740
[Guest]: that has been studied by quite a few people.

02:08:41.740 --> 02:08:48.020
[Guest]: The second thing that seems to be happening here is that as the family income goes up

02:08:48.020 --> 02:08:53.980
[Guest]: because the male earns more, then the woman actually stays at home because she's able

02:08:53.980 --> 02:09:01.060
[Guest]: to give her children childcare, which she cannot afford if the male earns less.

02:09:01.060 --> 02:09:06.020
[Guest]: And this is a paradoxical situation where it's not very easy to say, what would you

02:09:06.020 --> 02:09:07.020
[Guest]: want?

02:09:07.020 --> 02:09:08.020
[Guest]: Do you want him to earn less?

02:09:08.020 --> 02:09:09.020
[Guest]: No, you don't.

02:09:09.020 --> 02:09:13.580
[Guest]: You want him to earn more and her to be able to go out, but are there good facilities for

02:09:13.580 --> 02:09:14.580
[Guest]: childcare?

02:09:14.580 --> 02:09:15.580
[Guest]: No, there aren't.

02:09:15.580 --> 02:09:20.740
[Guest]: So, you know, you find that women usually are the ones who would say they would stay

02:09:20.740 --> 02:09:24.940
[Guest]: back even though they could have got a job.

02:09:24.940 --> 02:09:29.300
[Guest]: The first is clearly a bad, the second is a paradoxical one.

02:09:29.300 --> 02:09:31.740
[Guest]: And I think the third is that women migrate.

02:09:31.740 --> 02:09:34.580
[Guest]: So when married women migrate a lot.

02:09:34.580 --> 02:09:40.220
[Guest]: So when you look at migration data, a lot of migration is happening because the woman

02:09:40.220 --> 02:09:45.340
[Guest]: goes and, you know, goes to the village where her husband and his family live.

02:09:45.340 --> 02:09:48.580
[Guest]: And there it is not very easy for her to find a job.

02:09:48.580 --> 02:09:51.620
[Guest]: I mean, you don't have these thriving labor markets.

02:09:51.620 --> 02:09:54.980
[Guest]: Of course, then also they try to, some of them get jobs.

02:09:54.980 --> 02:09:56.580
[Guest]: I'm not saying it's zero.

02:09:56.580 --> 02:10:03.380
[Guest]: But both society, you know, the society is very conservative, a young bride in a village

02:10:03.380 --> 02:10:09.300
[Guest]: is not expected to come and start working if they can afford to have her stay at home

02:10:09.300 --> 02:10:11.940
[Guest]: and look after her kids.

02:10:11.940 --> 02:10:17.540
[Guest]: So it's both cultural, it is the economy.

02:10:17.540 --> 02:10:22.940
[Guest]: And then, of course, it is skill development that if the man starts earning more, then

02:10:22.940 --> 02:10:27.700
[Guest]: and he becomes more skilled, even if she's also skilled, if they both get skilled.

02:10:27.700 --> 02:10:32.380
[Guest]: But if the household income allows her to look after the children, then she does that.

02:10:32.380 --> 02:10:33.380
[Guest]: So it's a combination.

02:10:33.380 --> 02:10:35.860
[Guest]: I think it's a very complex issue.

02:10:35.860 --> 02:10:38.420
[Guest]: It's not an easy one for us to solve looking ahead.

02:10:38.420 --> 02:10:43.300
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I done this episode with Chinmay Tumbay on his great book, India Moving, about migration

02:10:43.300 --> 02:10:44.300
[Amit Varma]: in and outside India.

02:10:44.300 --> 02:10:48.300
[Amit Varma]: And one of the great TIL moments for me there was when he said that the largest cause of

02:10:48.300 --> 02:10:52.380
[Amit Varma]: internal migration within the country is just women getting married and going to their husband's

02:10:52.380 --> 02:10:53.780
[Amit Varma]: home, which is something to my shame.

02:10:53.780 --> 02:10:58.900
[Amit Varma]: I had never even thought about it in those terms, but suddenly it just becomes so stark.

02:10:58.900 --> 02:11:02.820
[Amit Varma]: And Namita had, of course, also mentioned that this happens that as the men start earning

02:11:02.820 --> 02:11:06.740
[Amit Varma]: more, the women kind of drop out because they can actually afford to stay at home.

02:11:06.740 --> 02:11:10.860
[Amit Varma]: And I would therefore imagine that when the men start earning so much more, that the women

02:11:10.860 --> 02:11:14.780
[Amit Varma]: don't have to drop out, that they can also work and find satisfaction elsewhere that

02:11:14.780 --> 02:11:16.180
[Amit Varma]: maybe then that rate goes up.

02:11:16.180 --> 02:11:20.460
[Amit Varma]: So is it then like a kind of a reverse bell curve there in terms of women's participation?

02:11:20.460 --> 02:11:24.020
[Amit Varma]: Do you think, is there any data from anywhere in the world which gives us a clue?

02:11:24.020 --> 02:11:30.580
[Guest]: So I don't particularly do women's studies, I am a macroeconomist.

02:11:30.580 --> 02:11:34.940
[Guest]: I don't know whether there's data elsewhere in the world, but I think we'll be a long

02:11:34.940 --> 02:11:35.940
[Guest]: way from that.

02:11:35.940 --> 02:11:40.140
[Guest]: I mean, there will be sections of society which will start moving, but how that affects

02:11:40.140 --> 02:11:41.340
[Guest]: the aggregate.

02:11:41.340 --> 02:11:48.860
[Guest]: It might be that we see lower reduced labor force participation of women for a long time.

02:11:48.860 --> 02:11:54.340
[Guest]: And particularly given the schools and the way they are, given the childcare facilities

02:11:54.340 --> 02:12:01.700
[Guest]: the way they are, it's very hard for a woman to leave her children anywhere and go off

02:12:01.700 --> 02:12:02.700
[Guest]: for a whole day.

02:12:02.700 --> 02:12:08.300
[Guest]: I mean, maybe work from home helps, maybe it's going to put double burden on her, but

02:12:08.300 --> 02:12:11.300
[Guest]: still she'll be able to work.

02:12:11.300 --> 02:12:17.060
[Guest]: And if she doesn't have to leave her children and go, I think it's a very difficult issue.

02:12:17.060 --> 02:12:19.660
[Guest]: In fact, around the world you see that.

02:12:19.660 --> 02:12:24.820
[Guest]: So if you look at Switzerland, for example, I read a paper which was talking about how

02:12:24.820 --> 02:12:31.140
[Guest]: one member of the family works, because a lot of studies are showing that when children

02:12:31.140 --> 02:12:36.860
[Guest]: are brought up by their parents, by them, you know, mother or father, and they are spoken

02:12:36.860 --> 02:12:41.180
[Guest]: to, they become more intelligent, they become better human beings.

02:12:41.180 --> 02:12:46.860
[Guest]: So instead of leaving children in creches where it's rather impersonal, as a society,

02:12:46.860 --> 02:12:51.300
[Guest]: I think her contribution today, whether we measure it in income, whether we measure it

02:12:51.300 --> 02:12:58.860
[Guest]: in GDP, but she's making a very big contribution when she's looking after her own children.

02:12:58.860 --> 02:13:02.340
[Guest]: So I'm not sure where we will go on this.

02:13:02.340 --> 02:13:09.420
[Guest]: So if we jump stages and go the way some advanced economies are going, we could well be saying

02:13:09.420 --> 02:13:16.740
[Guest]: that either parent, when both are getting skilled, for example, it's not necessarily

02:13:16.740 --> 02:13:21.180
[Guest]: that the man has to go out and work, but he could be the one who could be looking after

02:13:21.180 --> 02:13:22.180
[Guest]: the children.

02:13:22.180 --> 02:13:26.060
[Amit Varma]: And speaking of jumping stages, I think the first imperative for the Indian economy would

02:13:26.060 --> 02:13:29.980
[Amit Varma]: be to get back to where it was before COVID kind of did what it did.

02:13:29.980 --> 02:13:31.580
[Amit Varma]: So I have three final questions for you.

02:13:31.580 --> 02:13:34.500
[Amit Varma]: And one of them is about economics, but the last two are not.

02:13:34.500 --> 02:13:39.180
[Amit Varma]: And so here's the economics one, that, you know, just looking at where we are today,

02:13:39.180 --> 02:13:42.620
[Amit Varma]: looking at the fact that the second wave is still kind of going on, that is devastating

02:13:42.620 --> 02:13:43.820
[Amit Varma]: rural India.

02:13:43.820 --> 02:13:45.740
[Amit Varma]: We don't know what the end game is.

02:13:45.740 --> 02:13:49.900
[Amit Varma]: We don't know if there'll be more variants or whatever, when we look forward to the job

02:13:49.900 --> 02:13:54.780
[Amit Varma]: that the Indian economy has to do to get back on track, you know, what are the things which

02:13:54.780 --> 02:13:57.500
[Amit Varma]: for you are reasons to be hopeful?

02:13:57.500 --> 02:14:01.780
[Amit Varma]: And what are the things which for you are reasons to despair?

02:14:01.780 --> 02:14:07.700
[Guest]: So I'm hopeful that now that we've allowed, we're not stopping people from getting the

02:14:07.700 --> 02:14:13.900
[Guest]: vaccine, whether it's individuals, private hospitals, companies, wherever, there will

02:14:13.900 --> 02:14:19.260
[Guest]: be a lot of energy that will be devoted to solving this issue, we'll get better at it.

02:14:19.260 --> 02:14:23.620
[Guest]: So I'm hoping that once one is able to get them and those negotiations will also work.

02:14:23.620 --> 02:14:28.300
[Guest]: So I'm hoping that even if things will get a little worse now, but that they will get

02:14:28.300 --> 02:14:29.520
[Guest]: better soon.

02:14:29.520 --> 02:14:32.380
[Guest]: So that certainly makes me optimistic.

02:14:32.380 --> 02:14:37.980
[Guest]: But in terms of how soon, what worries me is how soon will we be able to get back on

02:14:37.980 --> 02:14:38.980
[Guest]: track?

02:14:38.980 --> 02:14:43.940
[Guest]: How soon will the companies who, you know, eventually we give them a moratorium, but

02:14:43.940 --> 02:14:49.660
[Guest]: moratoriums can't continue forever after all, banks are paying interest to us, to those

02:14:49.660 --> 02:14:51.540
[Guest]: who have deposited money, to depositors.

02:14:51.540 --> 02:14:57.780
[Guest]: So moratoriums will go away, people will have to pay back their loans, many loans will,

02:14:57.780 --> 02:15:02.900
[Guest]: many companies have, you know, small businesses anyway, don't get too much.

02:15:02.900 --> 02:15:09.420
[Guest]: But when they, whatever they have, this has been a very, very bad time for small companies.

02:15:09.420 --> 02:15:16.380
[Guest]: So how many people will be able to get back on their feet, find work, find income, make,

02:15:16.380 --> 02:15:19.500
[Guest]: you know, make some money, be able to sustain themselves?

02:15:19.500 --> 02:15:20.980
[Guest]: That worries me.

02:15:20.980 --> 02:15:21.980
[Amit Varma]: Right.

02:15:21.980 --> 02:15:27.020
[Amit Varma]: So the penultimate question now, and I'll take you back to the young 19 year old Ila,

02:15:27.020 --> 02:15:29.500
[Amit Varma]: who's standing up and saying, no, we need roads.

02:15:29.500 --> 02:15:34.060
[Amit Varma]: If you were to, with all this life experience and hindsight, if you were to speak to that

02:15:34.060 --> 02:15:38.260
[Amit Varma]: young girl for a moment and give her some advice or tell her things she may not know

02:15:38.260 --> 02:15:42.100
[Amit Varma]: yet, but which would be useful for her to know in advance, what would you say?

02:15:42.100 --> 02:15:45.100
[Guest]: What advice would you give her?

02:15:45.100 --> 02:15:49.060
[Guest]: India is a very, very complex, very, very complex nation.

02:15:49.060 --> 02:15:52.940
[Guest]: Don't spend your initial years only studying economics.

02:15:52.940 --> 02:15:59.900
[Guest]: Study a lot more, study more subjects, study sociology, politics, history, and you'll do

02:15:59.900 --> 02:16:03.540
[Guest]: the same things better and make less mistakes.

02:16:03.540 --> 02:16:06.260
[Guest]: So do you wish you'd done all of those things?

02:16:06.260 --> 02:16:07.260
[Guest]: Absolutely.

02:16:07.260 --> 02:16:08.260
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

02:16:08.260 --> 02:16:12.780
[Amit Varma]: And now the final question, it's kind of a meme on the show that my guests have to recommend

02:16:12.780 --> 02:16:16.900
[Amit Varma]: books which have either sort of changed the way they look at the world or influence them

02:16:16.900 --> 02:16:20.660
[Amit Varma]: greatly or even something they've read recently and they want to share with everyone.

02:16:20.660 --> 02:16:24.260
[Amit Varma]: These don't necessarily have to be books on your subject or economics or whatever, but

02:16:24.260 --> 02:16:28.260
[Amit Varma]: just what are the most memorable books for you which have had an impact on you or that

02:16:28.260 --> 02:16:33.300
[Amit Varma]: you would want to share just out of the sheer joy of reading them?

02:16:33.300 --> 02:16:38.580
[Guest]: So Seeing Like a State would be something that I'd like to, yeah, by James Scott is

02:16:38.580 --> 02:16:40.580
[Guest]: something that I'd like to share.

02:16:40.580 --> 02:16:48.900
[Guest]: There are books that I've read over the years that the books in themselves were not like

02:16:48.900 --> 02:16:58.500
[Guest]: very, very brilliant, but putting them all, they add up to a whole worldview, you know,

02:16:58.500 --> 02:17:08.300
[Guest]: so whether you read Milton Friedman or whether you read what PJ Roark, however you pronounce

02:17:08.300 --> 02:17:09.300
[Guest]: that.

02:17:09.300 --> 02:17:16.820
[Guest]: So, you know, they all helped in helping me think, of course, the most recent book by

02:17:16.820 --> 02:17:23.100
[Amit Varma]: Kilkaran Shah is my latest, is our latest favorite.

02:17:23.100 --> 02:17:26.580
[Guest]: So with that, I guess that's the latest.

